{"title_page": "Kamleshwar Patel", "text_new": "{{short description|Indian politician (born 1974)}}\n{{Use Indian English|date=October 2019}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=October 2019}}\n{{Infobox officeholder\n| name             = Kamleshwar Patel\n| honorific_prefix = \n| image            = Kamleshwar patel bhaiya.jpg\n| caption          = \n| birth_date       = {{Birth date and age|df=y|1974|05|01}}\n| birth_place      = [[Sidhi]]\n| residence        = [[Sidhi, Madhya Pradesh]], India\n| citizenship      = \n| office           = Member of the [[Madhya Pradesh Legislative Assembly]]\n| term_start       = [[2013 Madhya Pradesh Legislative Assembly election|2013]]\n| term_end         = \n| constituency     = [[Sihawal (Vidhan Sabha constituency)|Sihawal]]\n| predecessor      = \n| education        = [[LLB]]<ref>{{cite web|title=MLA Profile|url=http://mpvidhansabha.nic.in/14thvs/2014_78.pdf|website=MP Vidhansabha|accessdate=16 May 2018}}</ref>\n| alma_mater       = \n| profession       = Politician\n| website          = {{url|kamleshwarpatel.com|kamleshwarpatel.com}}\n| footnotes        = \n| party            = [[Indian National Congress]]\n| spouse           = Priti Patel\n| father           = Indrajeet Kumar\n| children         = \n}}\n'''Kamleshwar Patel''' is an Indian politician and a member of the [[Indian National Congress]] party.\n\nKamleshwar Patel was born on 1 May 1974 in [[Sidhi, Madhya Pradesh]]. He was elected from the Sihawal Vidhan Sabha constituency for the first time in the year 2013 and retained the seat in 2018 elections.His father Mr. Inderjeet Kumar was a member of Indian National Congress party and also cabinet minister in state Govt of Madhya Pradesh. He was elected from the Sihawal Vidhan Sabha constituency for the first time in the year 2013 and retained the seat in 2018 elections. Kamleshwar Patel is minister of Panchayat and Rural Development in Madhya Pradesh government.\n\nKamleshwar Patel is minister of Panchayat and Rural Development in Madhya Pradesh government.\n\n==Political career==\n\u2022  Cabinet  Minister (Panchayat and Rural Development)<ref>{{Citation|title=Kamal Nath ministry|date=2020-03-25|url=https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=Kamal_Nath_ministry&oldid=947288976|work=Wikipedia|language=en|access-date=2020-04-02}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://economictimes.indiatimes.com/news/politics-and-nation/28-legislators-take-oath-as-ministers-in-madhya-pradesh/articleshow/67243311.cms|title=Kamal Nath expands Cabinet; inducts 28 ministers, including 2 women|date=2018-12-25|work=The Economic Times|access-date=2020-04-02}}</ref> from December 2018 to March 2020.\n\n\u2022 Became an MLA for the first time in [[2013 Madhya Pradesh Legislative Assembly election|2013]]<ref>{{cite web|title=MLA Information|url=http://myneta.info/mp2013/candidate.php?candidate_id=767|website=myneta.info|accessdate=16 May 2018}}</ref> to 2018 & 2018 reelected (''Sihawal -Sidhi)''\n\n==Legal matters==\nThe MP High Court had ordered the police to order an FIR against Kamleshwar Patel for forgery in the election form.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Editorial|first1=Team|title=Court orders FIR against Sihawal MLA Kamleshwar Patel|url=https://naidunia.jagran.com/madhya-pradesh/jabalpur-court-orders-fir-against-shivlal-mla-kamleshwar-patel-1171025|accessdate=16 May 2018|agency=Naidunia|publisher=naidunia.jagran.com|date=25 May 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|last1=Kale|first1=Makarand|title=FIR lodged against Congress MLA on the orders of the High Court|url=https://hindi.news18.com/madhya-pradesh/bhopal-news-fir-lodged-against-congress-mla-kamleshwar-patel-at-bhopal-1018367.html|accessdate=16 May 2018|agency=ETV MP/Chhattisgarh|publisher=hindi.news18.com|date=16 June 2017}}</ref>\n\n==See also==\n*[[Madhya Pradesh Legislative Assembly]]\n*[[2013 Madhya Pradesh Legislative Assembly election]]\n*[[Sihawal (Vidhan Sabha constituency)]]\n*[[Indian National Congress]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* [http://www.kamleshwarpatel.com/ Kamleshwar Patel] (personal)\n\n{{Indian National Congress}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Patel, Kamleshwar}}\n[[Category:Madhya Pradesh MLAs 2013\u20132018]]\n[[Category:Madhya Pradesh MLAs 2018\u2013]]\n[[Category:Indian National Congress politicians from Madhya Pradesh]][[Category:1974 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n\n\n{{INC-politician-stub}}\n", "text_old": "{{short description|Indian politician (born 1974)}}\n{{Use Indian English|date=October 2019}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=October 2019}}\n\n{{Infobox officeholder\n| name                = Kamleshwar Patel\n| honorific_prefix    = \n| image               = \n[[File:Kamleshwar patel bhaiya.jpg|thumb|Kamleshwar Patel]]\n| birth_date          = {{Birth date and age|df=y|1974|05|01}}\n| birth_place         = [[Sidhi]]\n| residence           = [[Sidhi]]\n| nationality         = Indian\n| citizenship         = \n| office              = Member of the [[Madhya Pradesh Legislative Assembly]]\n| term_start          = [[2013 Madhya Pradesh Legislative Assembly election|2013]]\n| term_end            = \n| constituency        = [[Sihawal (Vidhan Sabha constituency)|Sihawal]]\n| predecessor         = \n| education           = [[LLB]]<ref>{{cite web|title=MLA Profile|url=http://mpvidhansabha.nic.in/14thvs/2014_78.pdf|website=MP Vidhansabha|accessdate=16 May 2018}}</ref>\n| alma_mater          = \n| profession          = Politician\n| website             = {{url|kamleshwarpatel.com|kamleshwarpatel.com}}\n| footnotes           = \n| party               = [[Indian National Congress]]\n| spouse              = Priti Patel\n| father              = Indrajeet Kumar\n| children            = \n}}\n'''Kamleshwar Patel''' is an Indian politician and a member of the [[Indian National Congress]] party.\n\nKamleshwar Patel was born on 1 May 1974 in [[Sidhi]].\nHe was elected from the Sihawal Vidhan Sabha constituency for the first time in the year 2013 and retained the seat in 2018 elections.His father Mr. Inderjeet Kumar was a member of Indian National Congress party and also cabinet minister in state Govt of Madhya Pradesh. He was elected from the Sihawal Vidhan Sabha constituency for the first time in the year 2013 and retained the seat in 2018 elections. Kamleshwar Patel is minister of Panchayat and Rural Development in Madhya Pradesh government.\n\nKamleshwar Patel is minister of Panchayat and Rural Development in Madhya Pradesh government.\n\n==Political career==\n\u2022  Cabinet  Minister (Panchayat and Rural Development)<ref>{{Citation|title=Kamal Nath ministry|date=2020-03-25|url=https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=Kamal_Nath_ministry&oldid=947288976|work=Wikipedia|language=en|access-date=2020-04-02}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://economictimes.indiatimes.com/news/politics-and-nation/28-legislators-take-oath-as-ministers-in-madhya-pradesh/articleshow/67243311.cms|title=Kamal Nath expands Cabinet; inducts 28 ministers, including 2 women|date=2018-12-25|work=The Economic Times|access-date=2020-04-02}}</ref> from December 2018 to March 2020.\n\n\u2022 Became an MLA for the first time in [[2013 Madhya Pradesh Legislative Assembly election|2013]]<ref>{{cite web|title=MLA Information|url=http://myneta.info/mp2013/candidate.php?candidate_id=767|website=myneta.info|accessdate=16 May 2018}}</ref> to 2018 & 2018 reelected (''Sihawal -Sidhi)''\n\n==Legal matters==\nThe MP High Court had ordered the police to order an FIR against Kamleshwar Patel for forgery in the election form.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Editorial|first1=Team|title=Court orders FIR against Sihawal MLA Kamleshwar Patel|url=https://naidunia.jagran.com/madhya-pradesh/jabalpur-court-orders-fir-against-shivlal-mla-kamleshwar-patel-1171025|accessdate=16 May 2018|agency=Naidunia|publisher=naidunia.jagran.com|date=25 May 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|last1=Kale|first1=Makarand|title=FIR lodged against Congress MLA on the orders of the High Court|url=https://hindi.news18.com/madhya-pradesh/bhopal-news-fir-lodged-against-congress-mla-kamleshwar-patel-at-bhopal-1018367.html|accessdate=16 May 2018|agency=ETV MP/Chhattisgarh|publisher=hindi.news18.com|date=16 June 2017}}</ref>\n\n==See also==\n*[[Madhya Pradesh Legislative Assembly]]\n*[[2013 Madhya Pradesh Legislative Assembly election]]\n*[[Sihawal (Vidhan Sabha constituency)]]\n*[[Indian National Congress]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* [http://www.kamleshwarpatel.com/ Kamleshwar Patel] (personal)\n\n{{Indian National Congress}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Patel, Kamleshwar}}\n[[Category:Madhya Pradesh MLAs 2013\u20132018]]\n[[Category:Madhya Pradesh MLAs 2018\u2013]]\n[[Category:Indian National Congress politicians from Madhya Pradesh]][[Category:1974 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n\n\n{{INC-politician-stub}}\n", "name_user": "MB", "label": "safe", "comment": "Fix infobox image syntax", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Kamleshwar_Patel"}
{"title_page": "She's All That", "text_new": "{{Use mdy dates|date=April 2020}}\n{{short description|1999 film directed by Robert Iscove}}\n{{lead too short|date=September 2017}}\n{{Infobox film\n| name           = She's All That\n| image          = Shes All That.jpg\n| caption        = Theatrical release poster\n| director       = [[Robert Iscove]]\n| producer       = {{Plainlist | \n* Peter Abrams\n* Richard N. Gladstein\n* [[Robert L. Levy (film producer)|Robert L. Levy]]\n}}\n| writer         = R. Lee Fleming, Jr.\n| starring       = {{Plainlist |\n* [[Freddie Prinze Jr.]]\n* [[Rachael Leigh Cook]]\n* [[Matthew Lillard]]\n* [[Paul Walker]]\n* [[Jodi Lyn O'Keefe]]\n* [[Kevin Pollak]]\n* [[Kieran Culkin]]\n* [[Elden Henson]]\n* [[Usher (singer)|Usher Raymond]]\n* [[Lil' Kim|Kimberly \"Lil' Kim\" Jones]]\n* [[Anna Paquin]]\n}}\n| music          = [[Stewart Copeland]]\n| cinematography = [[Francis Kenny]]\n| editing        = Casey O. Rohrs\n| studio         = Tapestry Films, FilmColony\n| distributor    = [[Miramax Films]]\n| released       = {{Film date|1999|01|19|[[Westwood, Los Angeles|Westwood]]|1999|01|29|United States}}\n| runtime        = 97 minutes\n| country        = United States\n| language       = English\n| budget         = $7\u201310 million<ref>{{cite web |last1= Prinze Jr. |first1= Freddie |title= Freddie Prinze Jr. Twitter |url= https://twitter.com/RealFPJr/status/1090271398134611968 |website= Twitter }}</ref><ref>{{cite web |last1=Prinze Jr. |first1= Freddie |title= Freddie Prinze Jr. Twitter |url= https://twitter.com/RealFPJr/status/1090299405498871808 |website= Twitter }}</ref><ref name=\"mojo\" />\n| gross          = $103.2 million<ref name=\"mojo\">{{cite web | url = http://www.boxofficemojo.com/movies/?id=shesallthat.htm | title = She's All That (1999) | work = [[Box Office Mojo]] | publisher = IMDB | accessdate = June 12, 2011 }}</ref>\n}}\n'''''She's All That''''' is a 1999 American [[Teen film|teen]] [[romantic comedy]] film directed by [[Robert Iscove]] and starring [[Freddie Prinze Jr.]], [[Rachael Leigh Cook]], [[Paul Walker]] and [[Matthew Lillard]]. It is a [[List of modernized retellings of old stories|modern adaptation]] of [[George Bernard Shaw]]'s play ''[[Pygmalion (play)|Pygmalion]]'' and [[George Cukor]]'s 1964 film ''[[My Fair Lady (film)|My Fair Lady]]''. It was one of the most popular [[teen film]]s of the late 1990s and reached No. 1 at the box office in its first week of release.<ref name=\"mojo\" />\n\n== Plot ==\nZackary Siler ([[Freddie Prinze Jr.]]) is the big man on campus at his [[Southern California]] [[high school]]. His popular and narcissistic girlfriend, Taylor Vaughan ([[Jodi Lyn O'Keefe]]), ditches him for a crude reality TV star from ''[[The Real World]]'', Brock Hudson ([[Matthew Lillard]]), whom she met on Spring Break in Florida. Zack consoles himself, claiming that Taylor is replaceable by any girl in the school. Zack's friend, Dean Sampson, Jr. ([[Paul Walker]]), disagrees and challenges him to a bet on whether Zack can turn any random girl into the Prom Queen within six weeks. Dean chooses Laney Boggs ([[Rachael Leigh Cook]]), a dorky, solitary, unpopular art student.\n\nZack attempts to befriend Laney, but fails utterly, as she pointedly ignores his advances and walks away. Zack's sister Mac ([[Anna Paquin]]) encourages him to try again, and make a proper effort to get to learn what Laney is interested in and cares about. Zack approaches Laney again at her workplace and with the help of Laney's childhood friend, Jesse Jackson ([[Elden Henson]]) convinces her to give him a chance. Laney takes him to a small theater lounge where she will be performing. Intending to deter him, Laney has Zack called on stage to perform. Zack manages to improvise a show with the [[Hacky Sack]] he happens to carry in his pocket. Laney is impressed by the performance, but rejects him again after he attempts to charm her.\n\nZack befriends her brother, Simon ([[Kieran Culkin]]), and in an attempt to stop this, Laney agrees to go to the beach with him once. Dean unexpectedly shows up with the popular crowd, and Laney gets a chance to know them all. Preston ([[Dul\u00e9 Hill]]) invites them to a party at his house that night. Laney pretends to be busy but Zack persuades her go, and enlists his sister to give her a makeover, transforming her and revealing her true beauty. At Preston's, Taylor is embarrassed by Brock and jealous of Laney, who she publicly humiliates and brings her to tears. Outside Zack consoles Laney, telling her that by opening up to people there will be some bad with the good.\n\nNewly popular, Laney is surprised to be nominated for Prom Queen and competes with Taylor for the crown. Zack and Laney begin to genuinely fall for each other; Taylor is humiliated when Brock ends their relationship, as he is leaving for [[Road Rules: All Stars]]. Dean begins to show an interest in Laney, aggravating Zack. Dean tries to invite Laney to prom, but she refuses. After falling out with Zack, Dean deliberately tells Laney about the bet and she forces a confession from Zack in public. Humiliated, Laney refuses to see Zack again.\n\nUnable to reconcile with Laney, Zack takes his sister to the prom, while Taylor arrives alone, thinking that Zack is still interested in her despite his refusal of her advances. A disheartened Laney reluctantly dresses up after some persuasion from her father Wayne ([[Kevin Pollak]]) and goes to the dance with Dean after he shows up at her house in a tuxedo to invite her again to be his prom date.\n\nAt the prom, after a dance scene presided over by the school's resident DJ ([[Usher (entertainer)|Usher Raymond]]), Mac meets Jesse and they become friends. In the bathroom Dean boasts that he is succeeding in seducing Laney and has rented a hotel room with intention of having sex with her. Jesse overhears, and tries to tell Mac and they rush to warn Zack. Taylor is crowned Prom Queen with just over half the votes. Laney is magnanimous, as she believes the right person won, and leaves the prom with Dean. Zack attempts to intervene but is too late and loses track of them.\n\nLaney returns home, to find her father and Simon waiting up for her, and Zack is there waiting too. Laney explains how she fought off Dean's advances by deafening him with an [[Air horn#Portable or personal air horns|air horn]]. Zack confesses his true feelings to Laney, and asks for forgiveness as well as the chance to further their relationship, which she grants and the two officially become a couple. Laney tells Zack that she is considering art school after graduation, and Zack jokingly tells her that she has inspired him to pursue a career in performance art. After they dance and kiss, Laney asks Zack about the bet, and Zack responds that he will honor the terms.\n\nAt the graduation ceremony, it is revealed, that Zack must appear nude on stage. Zack is wearing only a graduation cap and strategically carrying a [[soccer ball]] to cover himself. Zack takes the stage, Laney catches the soccer ball and reacts with a smile, as the students applaud.\n\n== Cast ==\n{{Cast listing|\n* [[Freddie Prinze, Jr.]] as Zachary \"Zack\" Siler\n* [[Rachael Leigh Cook]] as Laney Boggs\n* [[Paul Walker]] as Dean Sampson, Jr.\n* [[Matthew Lillard]] as Brock Hudson\n* [[Jodi Lyn O'Keefe]] as Taylor Vaughan\n* [[Kevin Pollak]] as Wayne Boggs\n* [[Usher (entertainer)|Usher Raymond]] as Campus DJ\n* [[Lil' Kim|Kimberly \"Lil' Kim\" Jones]] as Alex Chason Sawyer\n* [[Anna Paquin]] as Mackenzie \"Mac\" Siler\n* [[Kieran Culkin]] as Simon Boggs\n* [[Elden Henson]] as Jesse Jackson\n* [[Sarah Michelle Gellar]] as Girl in Cafeteria (''uncredited'')<ref name=\"Greco\" /><ref name=\"Macatee\" />{{efn|Named in the credits under ''The Producers Wish To Thank'', subsection ''They're All That''.}}\n* [[Gabrielle Union]] as Katarina \"Katie\" Darlingson\n* [[Dul\u00e9 Hill]] as Preston\n* [[Tamara Mello]] as Chandler\n* [[Clea DuVall]] as Misty\n* [[Tim Matheson]] as Harlan Siler\n* [[Alexis Arquette]] as Mitch\n* [[Chris Owen (actor)|Chris Owen]] as Derek Funkhouser Rutley\n* [[Vanessa Lee Chester]] as Melissa's Friend\n* [[Milo Ventimiglia]] as Soccer Player\n* [[Takbir Bashir]] as Rapper\n* [[Brandon Mychal Smith]] as JV Cleaning Boy\n* [[Flex Alexander]] as Kadeem\n* [[Debbi Morgan]] as Laney's Art Teacher\n* [[Carlos Jacott]] as Prom Photographer\n* [[Michael Milhoan]] as Principal Stickley\n* [[Patricia Charbonneau]] as Lois Siler\n* Katharine Towne as Savannah\n}}\n\n== Production ==\n{{Anchor|Casting}}\nThe film had an impressive ensemble cast of up-and-coming actors, including Kieran Culkin, Oscar winner Anna Paquin, musician Usher Raymond, Gabrielle Union in her film debut, Dul\u00e9 Hill and [[Lil' Kim]]. Jodi Lynn O'Keefe was known for [[Nash Bridges]] but this was only her second film role.<ref>{{cite web |date= January 29, 2019 |last1= Kupfer |first1= Lindsey |title= \u2018She\u2019s All That\u2019 mean girl reflects on the movie 20 years later |url= https://pagesix.com/2019/01/29/jodi-lyn-okeefe-reflects-on-shes-all-that-20-years-later/ |website=Page Six }}</ref> Producer Richard N. Gladstein puts it, \"There were other films that you could've seen them in, but they weren't usually the leads in those films.\"<ref name=\"Macatee\">{{cite web |date= January 29, 2019  |author= Rebecca Macatee |title= Rachael Leigh Cook Shares Her Favorite She's All That Memories |url= https://www.eonline.com/news/1008141/rachael-leigh-cook-shares-the-secrets-of-why-she-s-all-that-has-stayed-special-for-20-years |website= E! Online |url-status= live |archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20190129195205/https://www.eonline.com/news/1008141/rachael-leigh-cook-shares-the-secrets-of-why-she-s-all-that-has-stayed-special-for-20-years| archive-date= January 29, 2019 }}</ref> According to Robert Iscove Harvey Weinstein was very involved in script development and very involved in casting, and was able to get great actors in very small parts, as a personal favor.<ref name=\"Marlow\" />\n\nKevin Pollak said he signed up for the movie in part because he was impressed with Freddie Prinze, Jr., in [[The House of Yes]] a few years earlier and was interested to work with him.<ref>{{cite web |date= April 7, 2019 |author1= STEPHEN SILVER |title= Kevin Pollak on comedy, Mrs. Maisel, and more |url= https://www.phillyvoice.com/kevin-pollak-comedy-mrs-maisel-and-more/ |website= www.phillyvoice.com |quote= }}</ref><ref name=\"Marlow\">{{cite web |date= January 29, 2014 |last1= Stern |first1= Marlow |title= \u2018She\u2019s All That' 15th Anniversary: Cast and Crew Reminisce About the Making of the \u201890s Classic |url= https://www.thedailybeast.com/shes-all-that-15th-anniversary-cast-and-crew-reminisce-about-the-making-of-the-90s-classic |website= [[The Daily Beast]] }}</ref>\n\nJodi Lyn O'Keefe describe her character as being completely unlike her: \"Literally everything that character did was something I would never do. I mean, just every single thing. There wasn't a single moment where I was like, I can relate to that, personally.\"<ref name=\"glamour\">{{cite web |date= February 1, 2018 |author1= JUSTINE HARMAN |title= Jaime Pressly, Rachael Leigh Cook, and More '90s Icons Look Back on the Genre They Invented |url= https://www.glamour.com/story/jaime-pressly-rachael-leigh-cook-and-90s-teen-stars-on-the-genre-they-invented |website= Glamour |publisher= Cond\u00e9 Nast |archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20180201150214/https://www.glamour.com/story/jaime-pressly-rachael-leigh-cook-and-90s-teen-stars-on-the-genre-they-invented |archive-date= February 1, 2018 }}</ref>\n\n{{Anchor|Writing}}\nR. Lee Fleming, Jr. is officially credited as the sole screenwriter for the film. In a 2002 interview, [[M. Night Shyamalan]] stated that he [[Script doctor|polished]] the screenplay while adapting ''[[Stuart Little (film)|Stuart Little]]'' and writing a [[spec script]] for ''[[The Sixth Sense]]''. This was also confirmed in the film's audio commentary by director [[Robert Iscove]].<ref>{{cite web |title= Night's Skies &#124; In Focus, Volume II, Number 8 |publisher= [[National Association of Theatre Owners]] |date= August 2002 |author= Mike Russell |accessdate= June 15, 2013 |url-status= dead |url= http://www.natoonline.org/infocus/02August/Night.htm |archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20130714052025/http://www.natoonline.org/infocus/02August/Night.htm |archive-date= July 14, 2013 }}</ref>\n\nIn 2013, Shyamalan claimed that, rather than simply polishing Fleming's original script, he actually [[Ghostwriter|ghost-wrote]] the film.<ref name=\"Movies.com\">[http://www.movies.com/movie-news/m-night-shyamalan-interview-after-earth/12370 \"M. Night Shyamalan on How People See His Movies, Plus: What '90s Rom-Com Did He Secretly Write?\"]. \"[[Movies.com]]\". Retrieved June 11, 2013.</ref> This was disputed by someone who claimed to be Fleming,<ref name=\"ddot\">{{cite web |date= June 13, 2013 |author= Daniel Kibblesmith|title= M. Night Shyamalan is a liar, says \"She's All That\" screenwriter |url= http://www.dailydot.com/entertainment/m-night-shyamalan-lied-about-shes-all-that/|publisher=[[The Daily Dot]]|accessdate= June 13, 2013 }}</ref> in a message on [[Twitter]] that has since been deleted.<ref>https://twitter.com/QualityShorts/status/344558387813556224  {{webarchive |url= https://web.archive.org/web/20140729164927/https://twitter.com/QualityShorts/status/344558387813556224 |date= July 29, 2014 }}</ref>\n\nOn June 17, 2013, Jack Lechner (who served as Miramax's head of development in the late 1990s) confirmed that technically both Shyamalan and Fleming contributed to the script: Fleming wrote the initial script that Miramax bought while Shyamalan did an uncredited rewrite (doing more than \"a polish\") that got the film green-lit. Lechner reiterated that content from both writers was included in the final cut of the film.<ref>{{cite web |date= June 17, 2013 |author= Hillary Busis |title= M. Night Shyamalan and 'She's All That': Did he really write it? &#124; PopWatch &#124; EW.com |url= http://popwatch.ew.com/2013/06/17/m-night-shyamalan-shes-all-that/ |website= [[Entertainment Weekly]] |accessdate= October 28, 2019 }}</ref><ref>{{cite web |date= June 13, 2013 |author= Jack Lechner | title= Comment #933013221 on M. Night Shyamalan Probably Did Not Write She's All That |website= [[The Mary Sue]] |url= http://www.themarysue.com/shyamalan-shes-all-that/#comment-933013221 |accessdate=June 18, 2013}}</ref> Producer Richard N. Gladstein said that the script \"was pretty much done\" already, but that Shyamalan's changes \"helped enormously with the relationship with Kevin Pollak [who played Laney's father, Wayne]\".<ref name=\"Macatee\" /> Iscove attributed the performance art piece and the hacky sack sequence to Shyamalan.<ref name=\"Marlow\" /> Fleming attributed the line \"Am I a fucking bet?\" to Shyamalan.<ref name=\"Sorokach\">{{cite web |date=January 29, 2019 |author1= Josh Sorokach |title= M. Night Shyamalan Helped \u2018She\u2019s All That\u2019 Deliver The Most Memorable F*ck in Teen Comedy History |url= https://decider.com/2019/01/29/shes-all-that-20th-anniversary-am-i-a-bet/ |website= Decider }}</ref> Fleming included various pop culture references in his script: Laney Boggs was named after two characters played by [[Winona Ryder]], Kim Boggs from [[Edward Scissorhands]] and Laney Pierce from [[Reality Bites]];<ref name=\"Marlow\" /> the characters Zack and Taylor were named after two of the three members of the band [[Hanson (band)|Hanson]].<ref name=\"Marlow\" /> Pollak constantly guessing [[Jeopardy]] answers incorrectly is a running joke, which he previously did in the 1997 film [[Truth or Consequences, N.M. (film)|Truth or Consequences, N.M.]]. The idea was in Fleming's script but Pollak expanded and improvised his answers.<ref name=\"Marlow\" />\n\nDirector Robert Iscove was influenced by the movies of [[John Hughes (filmmaker)|John Hughes]], and was trying do something different for the '90s generation that would still resonate. He stressed the importance of the story having a heart, how Zack had to be worthy of Laney, and Laney had to understand she had to learn to be more open.<ref name=\"huffpo\" /> The story was rewritten to better fit Prinze Jr. and make Zack more sympathetic and have his own challenges.<ref name=\"Greco\">{{cite web |date= June 10, 2015 |last= Greco |first= Patti |title= 10 Things You Probably Never Knew About \"She's All That\" |url= https://www.cosmopolitan.com/entertainment/movies/a41771/things-you-never-knew-about-shes-all-that/ |website= Cosmopolitan }}</ref> \nIscove was well aware that it was implausible to suggest Cook was ugly, but that it was standard practice in Hollywood to cast the beautiful girl, and that it requires the audience to suspend their disbelief: \"You either go along with it or you don't go along with it.\" He compared it to the [[Clark Kent#Identity change|transformation of Clark Kent into Superman]]. Noting that a real transformation would be impractical, he said it was more about finding an actor who had the range to give the necessary performance.<ref name=\"Greco\" />\n\n{{Anchor|Filming|Locations}}\nFilming took place in various California locations.<ref>{{cite web |date=March 24, 2018 |author=Global Film Locations |title=She\u2019s All That (1999) Film Locations |url=https://globalfilmlocations.net/2018/03/24/shes-all-that-1999-film-locations/ |website=Global Film Locations }}</ref> The highschool scenes were shot at [[Torrance High School]], where [[Buffy the Vampire Slayer]] and [[Beverly Hills, 90210]] had previously filmed.<ref name=\"Marlow\" />\n\n{{Anchor|Dance|Choreography}}\nIscove was also a choreographer and wanted to expand and embellish the prom scenes, but also show the Weinsteins how musical numbers could work in films. The dance scene was choreographed by [[Adam Shankman]], who was asked to by his sister Jennifer Gibgot who was co-producer on the film. Shankman was assisted by [[Anne Fletcher]]. Shankman was concerned about the scene and \"that, tonally, it wouldn\u2019t match into the rest of the movie\" but was Iscove committed to the idea it was up to him to make it fit. Test audiences didn't understand why the dance scene was happening so Bob Weinstein asked for a reshoot with Usher to link the scene.<ref name=\"huffpo\">{{cite web |date= January 29, 2019 |last= Blickley |first= Leigh |title= The Dance Scene No One Wanted: An Oral History Of The 'She's All That' Prom |url= https://www.huffpost.com/entry/dance-scene-shes-all-that_n_5c424345e4b0a8dbe171585b |website= HuffPost }}</ref> Shankman also worked with Matthew Lillard on his dance scenes.<ref name=\"Marlow\" /><ref name=\"huffpo\" />\n\n== Soundtrack ==\nThe song \"[[Kiss Me (Sixpence None the Richer song)|Kiss Me]]\" as was used as the main theme song. The film's box office success helped \"Kiss Me\" to gain widespread mainstream attention and chart success. \"Kiss Me\" climbed to No. 2 on Billboard's Hot 100 list, and stayed in the Top 10 for 16 straight weeks.\n\nThe film was released in Italy with the title \"Kiss Me\".<ref name=\"huffpo\" /><ref name=\"Marlow\" /><ref name=\"Greco\" />\n\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable plainrowheaders\"\n|- style=\"text-align:center;\"\n! Track no. !! Title !! Writer and music composer !! Performed by \n|-\n| 01.\n| Prophecy\n| Cinjun Tate, Shelby Tate, Cedric Lemoyne, Jeffrey Cain Thompson, Gregory Slay\n| [[Remy Zero]]\n|-\n| 02.\n| Baby Got Going\n| Liz Phair & Scott Litt\n| [[Liz Phair]]\n|-\n| 03.\n| Be Free\n| Apl.de.Ap, [[will.i.am]], Stahl, Goldberg\n| [[The Black Eyed Peas]]\n|-\n| 04.\n| Blacktop Beat\n| Lucas MacFadden\n| [[Jurassic 5]]\n|-\n| 05.\n| Up To Us\n| Allrighse, [[Robin Thicke]]\n| Allrighse\n|-\n| 06.\n| Wanderer\n| J. Ralph\n| Spy\n|-\n| 07.\n| Sugar\n| Jo Lloyd, James Wright, David Magee\n| [[Stretch Princess]]\n|-\n| 08.\n| [[Kiss Me (Sixpence None the Richer song)|Kiss Me]]\n| Matt Slocum\n| [[Sixpence None The Richer]]\n|-\n| 09.\n| Test The Theory\n| Robin File, Sean McCann, Martin Merchant & Robert Maxfield\n| [[Audioweb]]\n|-\n| 10.\n| Gorgeous\n| Kat Green\n| Girl Next Door\n|-\n| 11.\n| Ooh La La\n| Theo Keating\n| [[The Wiseguys]]\n|-\n| 12.\n| Give It To Me Baby\n| Rick James\n| [[Rick James]]\n|-\n| 13.\n| Shuck & Jive\n| John Davis\n| [[Superdrag]]\n|-\n| 14.\n| Hanging On\n| Emily Gerber and Carlos Calvo\n| Emily & Carlos\n|-\n| 15.\n| 66\n| Greg Dulli\n| [[The Afghan Whigs]]\n|-\n| 16.\n| Nonstop Operation\n| MC Tunes, S. Hickling, S. Jones, M. Lawrence, G. Gasper, P. Billington\n| The Dust Junkys\n|-\n| 17.\n| Believe\n| Goldie\n| [[Goldie]]\n|-\n| 18.\n| [[The Rockafeller Skank]]\n| Fatboy Slim, Terry Winford, John Barry\n| [[Fatboy Slim]]\n\n|}\n\n== Reception ==\n\n=== Critical response ===\n''She's All That'' received mixed reviews from film critics. On review aggregator [[Rotten Tomatoes]] the film has an approval rating of 41% based on reviews from 61 critics, with an average rating of 4.94/10. The website's consensus states: \"Despite its charming young leads, ''She's All That'' can't overcome its predictable, inconsistently funny script.\"<ref>{{cite web \n| url = https://www.rottentomatoes.com/m/shes_all_that \n| title = She's All That\n| work = [[Rotten Tomatoes]]\n| publisher = [[Fandango Media]]\n| access-date = January 2, 2019\n}}</ref> On [[Metacritic]] the film has a score of 51 based on reviews from 32 critics, indicating \"mixed or average reviews\".<ref>{{cite web \n| url = https://www.metacritic.com/movie/shes-all-that\n| title = She's All That 1999\n| work = [[Metacritic]]\n| publisher = [[CBS Interactive]]\n| access-date = January 2, 2019\n}}</ref>\n\nIt was the last movie to be reviewed by [[Gene Siskel]] before his death in February 1999. Siskel gave a positive review and wrote that \"Rachael Leigh Cook, as Laney, the plain Jane object of the makeover, is forced to demonstrate the biggest emotional range as a character, and she is equal to the assignment.\"<ref>{{cite web \n| date = January 29, 1999\n| author = Gene Siskel\n| author-link = Gene Siskel\n| title = 'She's All That' A Refreshing 'My Fair Lady' \n| work = [[Chicago Tribune]]\n| url = http://articles.chicagotribune.com/1999-01-29/entertainment/9901290001_1_senior-prom-fair-lady-rachael-leigh-cook\n| url-status = dead\n| archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20140222004053/http://articles.chicagotribune.com/1999-01-29/entertainment/9901290001_1_senior-prom-fair-lady-rachael-leigh-cook\n| archive-date = February 22, 2014\n| access-date = January 2, 2019\n}}</ref> [[Roger Ebert]] suggested: \"To give the movie credit, it's as bored with the underlying plot as we are. Even the prom queen election is only a backdrop for more interesting material, as ''She's All That'' explores differences in class and style, and peppers its screenplay with very funny little moments.\" Ebert says it \"is not a great movie, but it has its moments\" giving it 2.5 out of 4 stars.<ref>{{cite web \n| date = January 29, 1999\n| author = Roger Ebert\n| author-link = Roger Ebert\n| title = She's All That\n| work = [[Chicago Sun-Times]]\n| url = https://www.rogerebert.com/reviews/shes-all-that-1999\n| access-date = January 2, 2019\n}}</ref> Stephen Holden of the ''[[New York Times]]'' praised Cook for her performance, comparing her to [[Winona Ryder]], saying \"Unlike so many actors playing smart young people, she actually projects some intelligence along with a sly sense of comedy.\"<ref>{{cite web \n| date =  \n| author = Stephen Holden \n| title = 'She's All That': When 'Pygmalion' Meets MTV, the Bookworm Turns \n| url = https://archive.nytimes.com/www.nytimes.com/library/film/012999that-film-review.html \n| website = [[New York Times]] \n}}</ref> [[Mick LaSalle]] of the [[San Francisco Chronicle]] calls it \"About one idea short of being an excellent teenage romance. As it stands it's a pleasing but routine effort.\" LaSalle criticizes the film for running out of plot about half way, saying the \"story line is stretched to the breaking point. In one instance director Robert Iscove stops the action for a long dance sequence, set at the prom, that has nothing to do with anything.\" He says the film is \"intermittently funny\" and praises Matthew Lillard's performance, calling it the best thing in the picture.<ref>{{cite web \n| date = January 29, 1999\n| author = Mick LaSalle\n| author-link = Mick LaSalle\n| title = Teen Romance Is Amusing, But Not All That\n| work = [[San Francisco Chronicle]]\n| url = https://www.sfgate.com/movies/article/Teen-Romance-Is-Amusing-But-Not-All-That-2949714.php \n| access-date = January 2, 2019\n}}</ref>\n\nGeoff Berkshire ''[[Variety (magazine)|Variety magazine]]'' was critical of the lack of originality, and suggested that \"Miramax needs to put [[Kevin Williamson (screenwriter)|Kevin Williamson]] on permanent retainer if it's going to remain in the teen-pics field, ''She's All That'' notably fails to bring to comedy the insight that the Williamson-penned ''[[Scream (1996 film)|Scream]]'' brought so memorably to horror\". Berkshire is positive about the two leads, saying \"appealing young actors come off as competent, nothing more, given a context that can\u2019t be transcended.\" He describes the direction as \"nothing to be ashamed of here, but nothing of any distinction, either\" and notes the soundtrack as a not unexpected plus.<ref>{{cite web \n| date = January 27, 1999\n| author = Geoff Berkshire\n| author-link = Geoff Berkshire\n| title = She\u2019s All That\n| work = [[Variety (magazine)|Variety magazine]]\n| url = https://variety.com/1999/film/reviews/she-s-all-that-1200456368/\n| access-date = January 2, 2019\n}}</ref>\nJane Ganahl of The San Francisco Examiner wrote \"And once, just once, I'd love to see a teen flick that doesn't send out a message to young girls that to be acceptable, you have to conform. I liked the artist girl much better before.\"<ref>{{cite web \n| date = January 29, 1999\n| author = Jane Ganahl\n| author-link = Jane Ganahl\n| title = She's not quite \"All That'\n| work = [[San Francisco Examiner]]\n| url = https://www.sfgate.com/news/article/She-s-not-quite-All-That-3098868.php\n| access-date = January 2, 2019\n}}</ref>\nWilliam Thomas at ''[[Empire (magazine)|Empire magazine]]'' criticizes the film saying that despite a few scenes \"The rest is just breezy propaganda for American high school fascism\" and \"The most worrying thing about ''She's All That'' is its message. The \"ugly duckling\" (specs, dungarees, art-lover) must conform (she gets a makeover and the boys notice her \"bobos\" for the first time) to fit in.\"<ref>{{cite web \n| date = January 1, 2000\n| author = William Thomas\n| title = She's All That Review\n| work = [[Empire magazine]]\n| url = https://www.empireonline.com/movies/shesallthat/review/\n| archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20171207141035/https://www.empireonline.com/movies/shesallthat/review/\n| archive-date = December 7, 2017\n| url-status = dead\n}}</ref>\n\n=== Box office ===\n''She\u2019s All That'' premiered on January 19, 1999 at the Mann Festival Theater in [[Westwood, Los Angeles]].<ref>{{cite web |date= January 21, 1999 |author1= Variety Staff |title= \u2018All That\u2019 set for public bow |url= https://variety.com/1999/scene/vpage/all-that-set-for-public-bow-1117490448/ |website= Variety }}</ref> The film went into general release on January 29.\n\nThe film was reached No. 1 at the box office in the first week of its release, grossing $16.1 million over the [[Super Bowl]] opening weekend.<ref name=\"mojo\" /> It earned $63.4 million in the United States and $39.8 million at international box offices, totaling $103.2 million worldwide against a production budget between $7\u201310 million.<ref name=\"mojo\" /> Miramax spent a further <!-- according to Cook $12.5 million <ref name=\"Greco\" /> --> $18 million <!-- according to Iscove --> on television advertising to promote the film.<ref name=\"Marlow\" />\n\n=== Accolades ===\n{{Anchor|Awards}} \nThe film won eight awards, and was nominated for five others.\n\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\" \n|-\n! scope=\"col\" | Year\n! scope=\"col\" | Ceremony\n! scope=\"col\" | Category\n! scope=\"col\" | Recipients\n! scope=\"col\" | Result\n|-\n| rowspan=6| 1999\n| [[YoungStar Awards]]\n| Best Performance by a Young Actress in a Comedy Film\n| Rachael Leigh Cook\n| {{Won}}\n|-\n| rowspan=3| [[Teen Choice Awards]]\n| Choice Movie Actor\n| Freddie Prinze, Jr.\n| {{Won}}\n|-\n| Choice Movie: Love Scene\n| Freddie Prinze, Jr. & Rachael Leigh Cook\n| {{Won}}\n|-\n| colspan=2| Choice Movie: Comedy\n| {{Nominated}}\n|-\n| rowspan=2| [[MTV Movie Awards]]\n| Best Breakthrough Female Performance\n| Rachael Leigh Cook\n| {{Nominated}}\n|-\n| Best On-Screen Duo\n| Freddie Prinze, Jr. & Rachael Leigh Cook\n| {{Nominated}}\n|-\n| rowspan=7| 2000\n| rowspan=2| [[Young Hollywood Awards]]\n| Best Bad Girl\n| Jodi Lyn O'Keefe\n| {{Won}}\n|-\n| Best Song\n| [[Sixpence None the Richer]] <small>(\"[[Kiss Me (Sixpence None the Richer song)|Kiss Me]]\")</small>\n| {{Won}}\n|-\n| [[Kids' Choice Awards|Kids' Choice Awards, USA]]\n| Favorite Movie Couple\n| Freddie Prinze, Jr. & Rachael Leigh Cook\n| {{Won}}\n|-\n| rowspan=2| [[Blockbuster Entertainment Awards]] <ref>{{cite press release | date = February 8, 2000 |url= http://www.prnewswire.com/news-releases/nominees-announced-for-sixth-annual-blockbuster-entertainment-awardsr-to-air-in-june-on-fox-72458137.html |title= Nominees Announced for 'Sixth Annual Blockbuster Entertainment Awards(R)' To Air in June on FOX |work= [[Blockbuster Pressroom]] |publisher= Blockbuster LLC | archive-url = https://archive.today/20130615233011/http://blockbuster.mwnewsroom.com/manual-releases/Nominees-Announced-for--Sixth-Annual-Blockbuster-E | archive-date = June 15, 2013 | url-status = dead |access-date = January 2, 2019 }}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url= https://variety.com/2000/film/news/blockbuster-entertainment-award-winners-1117781474/ |title= Blockbuster Entertainment Award winners  |date= May 9, 2000 | author = Variety Staff |website=[[Variety (magazine)|Variety]] |publisher= |access-date= January 3, 2019 }}</ref>\n| Favorite Actress \u2013 Newcomer (Internet Only)\n| Rachael Leigh Cook\n| {{Won}}\n|-\n| Favorite Actor \u2013 Comedy/Romance\n| Freddie Prinze, Jr.\n| {{Nominated}}\n|-\n| [[ASCAP Film and Television Music Awards]]\n| Most Performed Songs from Motion Pictures\n| [[Matt Slocum]] <small>(\"Kiss Me\")</small>\n| {{Won}}\n|-\n| [[ALMA Awards]]\n| Outstanding Actor in a Feature Film\n| Freddie Prinze, Jr.\n| {{Nominated}}\n|}\n\n== References ==\n{{Notelist}}\n{{Reflist}}\n\n== External links ==\n{{Wikiquote}}\n* {{Official website|http://www.miramax.com/movie/shes-all-that}}\n* {{IMDb title|0160862|She's All That}}\n* {{Rotten Tomatoes|shes_all_that|She's All That}}\n* {{Mojo title|shesallthat|She's All That}}\n\n{{Robert Iscove}}\n{{Pygmalion}}\n\n[[Category:1999 films]]\n[[Category:1990s coming-of-age comedy films]]\n[[Category:1990s high school films]]\n[[Category:1990s romantic comedy films]]\n[[Category:1990s teen comedy films]]\n[[Category:1990s teen romance films]]\n[[Category:American coming-of-age films]]\n[[Category:American films]]\n[[Category:American high school films]]\n[[Category:American romantic comedy films]]\n[[Category:American teen comedy films]]\n[[Category:American teen romance films]]\n[[Category:Coming-of-age romance films]]\n[[Category:English-language films]]\n[[Category:Films scored by Stewart Copeland]]\n[[Category:Films set in California]]\n[[Category:Films shot in Los Angeles]]\n[[Category:Films about proms]]\n[[Category:Films directed by Robert Iscove]]\n[[Category:Miramax films]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use mdy dates|date=April 2020}}\n{{short description|1999 film directed by Robert Iscove}}\n{{lead too short|date=September 2017}}\n{{Infobox film\n| name           = She's All That\n| image          = Shes All That.jpg\n| caption        = Theatrical release poster\n| director       = [[Robert Iscove]]\n| producer       = {{Plainlist | \n* Peter Abrams\n* Richard N. Gladstein\n* [[Robert L. Levy (film producer)|Robert L. Levy]]\n}}\n| writer         = R. Lee Fleming, Jr.\n| starring       = {{Plainlist |\n* [[Freddie Prinze Jr.]]\n* [[Rachael Leigh Cook]]\n* [[Matthew Lillard]]\n* [[Paul Walker]]\n* [[Jodi Lyn O'Keefe]]\n* [[Kevin Pollak]]\n* [[Kieran Culkin]]\n* [[Elden Henson]]\n* [[Usher (singer)|Usher Raymond]]\n* [[Lil' Kim|Kimberly \"Lil' Kim\" Jones]]\n* [[Anna Paquin]]\n}}\n| music          = [[Stewart Copeland]]\n| cinematography = [[Francis Kenny]]\n| editing        = Casey O. Rohrs\n| studio         = Tapestry Films, FilmColony\n| distributor    = [[Miramax Films]]\n| released       = {{Film date|1999|01|19|[[Westwood, Los Angeles|Westwood]]|1999|01|29|United States}}\n| runtime        = 97 minutes\n| country        = United States\n| language       = English\n| budget         = $7\u201310 million<ref>{{cite web |last1= Prinze Jr. |first1= Freddie |title= Freddie Prinze Jr. Twitter |url= https://twitter.com/RealFPJr/status/1090271398134611968 |website= Twitter }}</ref><ref>{{cite web |last1=Prinze Jr. |first1= Freddie |title= Freddie Prinze Jr. Twitter |url= https://twitter.com/RealFPJr/status/1090299405498871808 |website= Twitter }}</ref><ref name=\"mojo\" />\n| gross          = $103.2 million<ref name=\"mojo\">{{cite web | url = http://www.boxofficemojo.com/movies/?id=shesallthat.htm | title = She's All That (1999) | work = [[Box Office Mojo]] | publisher = IMDB | accessdate = June 12, 2011 }}</ref>\n}}\n'''''She's All That''''' is a 1999 American [[Teen film|teen]] [[romantic comedy]] film directed by [[Robert Iscove]] and starring [[Freddie Prinze Jr.]], [[Rachael Leigh Cook]], [[Paul Walker]] and [[Matthew Lillard]]. It is a [[List of modernized retellings of old stories|modern adaptation]] of [[George Bernard Shaw]]'s play ''[[Pygmalion (play)|Pygmalion]]'' and [[George Cukor]]'s 1964 film ''[[My Fair Lady (film)|My Fair Lady]]''. It was one of the most popular [[teen film]]s of the late 1990s and reached No. 1 at the box office in its first week of release.<ref name=\"mojo\" />\n\n== Plot ==\nZackary Siler ([[Freddie Prinze Jr.]]) is the big man on campus at his [[Southern California]] [[high school]]. His popular and narcissistic girlfriend, Taylor Vaughan ([[Jodi Lyn O'Keefe]]), ditches him for a crude reality TV star from ''[[The Real World]]'', Brock Hudson ([[Matthew Lillard]]), whom she met on Spring Break in Florida. Zack consoles himself, claiming that Taylor is replaceable by any girl in the school. Zack's friend, Dean Sampson, Jr. ([[Paul Walker]]), disagrees and challenges him to a bet on whether Zack can turn any random girl into the Prom Queen within six weeks. Dean chooses Laney Boggs ([[Rachael Leigh Cook]]), a dorky, solitary, unpopular art student.\n\nZack attempts to befriend Laney, but fails utterly, as she pointedly ignores his advances and walks away. Zack's sister Mac ([[Anna Paquin]]) encourages him to try again, and make a proper effort to get to learn what Laney is interested in and cares about. Zack approaches Laney again at her workplace and with the help of Laney's childhood friend, Jesse Jackson ([[Elden Henson]]) convinces her to give him a chance. Laney takes him to a small theater lounge where she will be performing. Intending to deter him, Laney has Zack called on stage to perform. Zack manages to improvise a show with the [[Hacky Sack]] he happens to carry in his pocket. Laney is impressed by the performance, but rejects him again after he attempts to charm her.\n\nZack befriends her brother, Simon ([[Kieran Culkin]]), and in an attempt to stop this, Laney agrees to go to the beach with him once. Dean unexpectedly shows up with the popular crowd, and Laney gets a chance to know them all. Preston ([[Dul\u00e9 Hill]]) invites them to a party at his house that night. Laney pretends to be busy but Zack persuades her go, and enlists his sister to give her a makeover, transforming her and revealing her true beauty. At Preston's, Taylor is embarrassed by Brock and jealous of Laney, who she publicly humiliates and brings her to tears. Outside Zack consoles Laney, telling her that by opening up to people there will be some bad with the good.\n\nNewly popular, Laney is surprised to be nominated for Prom Queen and competes with Taylor for the crown. Zack and Laney begin to genuinely fall for each other; Taylor is humiliated when Brock ends their relationship, as he is leaving for [[Road Rules: All Stars]]. Dean begins to show an interest in Laney, aggravating Zack. Dean tries to invite Laney to prom, but she refuses. After falling out with Zack, Dean deliberately tells Laney about the bet and she forces a confession from Zack in public. Humiliated, Laney refuses to see Zack again.\n\nUnable to reconcile with Laney, Zack takes his sister to the prom, while Taylor arrives alone, thinking that Zack is still interested in her despite his refusal of her advances. A disheartened Laney reluctantly dresses up after some persuasion from her father Wayne ([[Kevin Pollak]]) and goes to the dance with Dean after he shows up at her house in a tuxedo to invite her again to be his prom date.\n\nAt the prom, after a dance scene presided over by the school's resident DJ ([[Usher (entertainer)|Usher Raymond]]), Mac meets Jesse and they become friends. In the bathroom Dean boasts that he is succeeding in seducing Laney and has rented a hotel room with intention of having sex with her. Jesse overhears, and tries to tell Mac and they rush to warn Zack. Taylor is crowned Prom Queen with just over half the votes. Laney is magnanimous, as she believes the right person won, and leaves the prom with Dean. Zack attempts to intervene but is too late and loses track of them.\n\nLaney returns home, to find her father and Simon waiting up for her, and Zack is there waiting too. Laney explains how she fought off Dean's advances by deafening him with an [[Air horn#Portable or personal air horns|air horn]]. Zack confesses his true feelings to Laney, and asks for forgiveness as well as the chance to further their relationship, which she grants and the two officially become a couple. Laney tells Zack that she is considering art school after graduation, and Zack jokingly tells her that she has inspired him to pursue a career in performance art. After they dance and kiss, Laney asks Zack about the bet, and Zack responds that he will honor the terms.\n\nAt the graduation ceremony, it is revealed, that Zack must appear nude on stage. Zack is wearing only a graduation cap and strategically carrying a [[soccer ball]] to cover himself. Zack takes the stage, Laney catches the soccer ball and reacts with a smile, as the students applaud.\n\n== Cast ==\n{{Cast listing|\n* [[Freddie Prinze, Jr.]] as Zachary \"Zack\" Siler\n* [[Rachael Leigh Cook]] as Laney Boggs\n* [[Paul Walker]] as Dean Sampson, Jr.\n* [[Matthew Lillard]] as Brock Hudson\n* [[Jodi Lyn O'Keefe]] as Taylor Vaughan\n* [[Kevin Pollak]] as Wayne Boggs\n* [[Usher (entertainer)|Usher Raymond]] as Campus DJ\n* [[Lil' Kim|Kimberly \"Lil' Kim\" Jones]] as Alex Chason Sawyer\n* [[Anna Paquin]] as Mackenzie \"Mac\" Siler\n* [[Kieran Culkin]] as Simon Boggs\n* [[Elden Henson]] as Jesse Jackson\n* [[Sarah Michelle Gellar]] as Girl in Cafeteria (''uncredited'')<ref name=\"Greco\" /><ref name=\"Macatee\" />{{efn|Named in the credits under ''The Producers Wish To Thank'', subsection ''They're All That''.}}\n* [[Gabrielle Union]] as Katarina \"Katie\" Darlingson\n* [[Dul\u00e9 Hill]] as Preston\n* [[Tamara Mello]] as Chandler\n* [[Clea DuVall]] as Misty\n* [[Tim Matheson]] as Harlan Siler\n* [[Alexis Arquette]] as Mitch\n* [[Chris Owen (actor)|Chris Owen]] as Derek Funkhouser Rutley\n* [[Vanessa Lee Chester]] as Melissa's Friend\n* [[Milo Ventimiglia]] as Soccer Player\n* [[Takbir Bashir]] as Rapper\n* [[Brandon Mychal Smith]] as JV Cleaning Boy\n* [[Flex Alexander]] as Kadeem\n* [[Debbi Morgan]] as Laney's Art Teacher\n* [[Carlos Jacott]] as Prom Photographer\n* [[Michael Milhoan]] as Principal Stickley\n* [[Patricia Charbonneau]] as Lois Siler\n* Katharine Towne as Savannah\n}}\n\n== Production ==\n{{Anchor|Casting}}\nThe film had an impressive ensemble cast of up-and-coming actors, including Kieran Culkin, Oscar winner Anna Paquin, musician Usher Raymond, Gabrielle Union in her film debut, Dul\u00e9 Hill and [[Lil' Kim]]. Jodi Lynn O'Keefe was known for [[Nash Bridges]] but this was only her second film role.<ref>{{cite web |date= January 29, 2019 |last1= Kupfer |first1= Lindsey |title= \u2018She\u2019s All That\u2019 mean girl reflects on the movie 20 years later |url= https://pagesix.com/2019/01/29/jodi-lyn-okeefe-reflects-on-shes-all-that-20-years-later/ |website=Page Six }}</ref> Producer Richard N. Gladstein puts it, \"There were other films that you could've seen them in, but they weren't usually the leads in those films.\"<ref name=\"Macatee\">{{cite web |date= January 29, 2019  |author= Rebecca Macatee |title= Rachael Leigh Cook Shares Her Favorite She's All That Memories |url= https://www.eonline.com/news/1008141/rachael-leigh-cook-shares-the-secrets-of-why-she-s-all-that-has-stayed-special-for-20-years |website= E! Online |url-status= live |archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20190129195205/https://www.eonline.com/news/1008141/rachael-leigh-cook-shares-the-secrets-of-why-she-s-all-that-has-stayed-special-for-20-years| archive-date= January 29, 2019 }}</ref> According to Robert Iscove Harvey Weinstein was very involved in script development and very involved in casting, and was able to get great actors in very small parts, as a personal favor.<ref name=\"Marlow\" />\n\nKevin Pollak said he signed up for the movie in part because he was impressed with Freddie Prinze, Jr., in [[The House of Yes]] a few years earlier and was interested to work with him.<ref>{{cite web |date= April 7, 2019 |author1= STEPHEN SILVER |title= Kevin Pollak on comedy, Mrs. Maisel, and more |url= https://www.phillyvoice.com/kevin-pollak-comedy-mrs-maisel-and-more/ |website= www.phillyvoice.com |quote= }}</ref><ref name=\"Marlow\">{{cite web |date= January 29, 2014 |last1= Stern |first1= Marlow |title= \u2018She\u2019s All That' 15th Anniversary: Cast and Crew Reminisce About the Making of the \u201890s Classic |url= https://www.thedailybeast.com/shes-all-that-15th-anniversary-cast-and-crew-reminisce-about-the-making-of-the-90s-classic |website= [[The Daily Beast]] }}</ref>\n\nJodi Lyn O'Keefe describe her character as being completely unlike her: \"Literally everything that character did was something I would never do. I mean, just every single thing. There wasn't a single moment where I was like, I can relate to that, personally.\"<ref name=\"glamour\">{{cite web |date= February 1, 2018 |author1= JUSTINE HARMAN |title= Jaime Pressly, Rachael Leigh Cook, and More '90s Icons Look Back on the Genre They Invented |url= https://www.glamour.com/story/jaime-pressly-rachael-leigh-cook-and-90s-teen-stars-on-the-genre-they-invented |website= Glamour |publisher= Cond\u00e9 Nast |archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20180201150214/https://www.glamour.com/story/jaime-pressly-rachael-leigh-cook-and-90s-teen-stars-on-the-genre-they-invented |archive-date= February 1, 2018 }}</ref>\n\n{{Anchor|Writing}}\nR. Lee Fleming, Jr. is officially credited as the sole screenwriter for the film. In a 2002 interview, [[M. Night Shyamalan]] stated that he [[Script doctor|polished]] the screenplay while adapting ''[[Stuart Little (film)|Stuart Little]]'' and writing a [[spec script]] for ''[[The Sixth Sense]]''. This was also confirmed in the film's audio commentary by director [[Robert Iscove]].<ref>{{cite web |title= Night's Skies &#124; In Focus, Volume II, Number 8 |publisher= [[National Association of Theatre Owners]] |date= August 2002 |author= Mike Russell |accessdate= June 15, 2013 |url-status= dead |url= http://www.natoonline.org/infocus/02August/Night.htm |archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20130714052025/http://www.natoonline.org/infocus/02August/Night.htm |archive-date= July 14, 2013 }}</ref>\n\nIn 2013, Shyamalan claimed that, rather than simply polishing Fleming's original script, he actually [[Ghostwriter|ghost-wrote]] the film.<ref name=\"Movies.com\">[http://www.movies.com/movie-news/m-night-shyamalan-interview-after-earth/12370 \"M. Night Shyamalan on How People See His Movies, Plus: What '90s Rom-Com Did He Secretly Write?\"]. \"[[Movies.com]]\". Retrieved June 11, 2013.</ref> This was disputed by someone who claimed to be Fleming,<ref name=\"ddot\">{{cite web |date= June 13, 2013 |author= Daniel Kibblesmith|title= M. Night Shyamalan is a liar, says \"She's All That\" screenwriter |url= http://www.dailydot.com/entertainment/m-night-shyamalan-lied-about-shes-all-that/|publisher=[[The Daily Dot]]|accessdate= June 13, 2013 }}</ref> in a message on [[Twitter]] that has since been deleted.<ref>https://twitter.com/QualityShorts/status/344558387813556224  {{webarchive |url= https://web.archive.org/web/20140729164927/https://twitter.com/QualityShorts/status/344558387813556224 |date= July 29, 2014 }}</ref>\n\nOn June 17, 2013, Jack Lechner (who served as Miramax's head of development in the late 1990s) confirmed that technically both Shyamalan and Fleming contributed to the script: Fleming wrote the initial script that Miramax bought while Shyamalan did an uncredited rewrite (doing more than \"a polish\") that got the film green-lit. Lechner reiterated that content from both writers was included in the final cut of the film.<ref>{{cite web |date= June 17, 2013 |author= Hillary Busis |title= M. Night Shyamalan and 'She's All That': Did he really write it? &#124; PopWatch &#124; EW.com |url= http://popwatch.ew.com/2013/06/17/m-night-shyamalan-shes-all-that/ |website= [[Entertainment Weekly]] |accessdate= October 28, 2019 }}</ref><ref>{{cite web |date= June 13, 2013 |author= Jack Lechner | title= Comment #933013221 on M. Night Shyamalan Probably Did Not Write She's All That |website= [[The Mary Sue]] |url= http://www.themarysue.com/shyamalan-shes-all-that/#comment-933013221 |accessdate=June 18, 2013}}</ref> Producer Richard N. Gladstein said that the script \"was pretty much done\" already, but that Shyamalan's changes \"helped enormously with the relationship with Kevin Pollak [who played Laney's father, Wayne]\".<ref name=\"Macatee\" /> Iscove attributed the performance art piece and the hacky sack sequence to Shyamalan.<ref name=\"Marlow\" /> Fleming attributed the line \"Am I a fucking bet?\" to Shyamalan.<ref name=\"Sorokach\">{{cite web |date=January 29, 2019 |author1= Josh Sorokach |title= M. Night Shyamalan Helped \u2018She\u2019s All That\u2019 Deliver The Most Memorable F*ck in Teen Comedy History |url= https://decider.com/2019/01/29/shes-all-that-20th-anniversary-am-i-a-bet/ |website= Decider }}</ref> Fleming included various pop culture references in his script: Laney Boggs was named after two characters played by [[Winona Ryder]], Kim Boggs from [[Edward Scissorhands]] and Laney Pierce from [[Reality Bites]];<ref name=\"Marlow\" /> the characters Zack and Taylor were named after two of the three members of the band [[Hanson (band)|Hanson]].<ref name=\"Marlow\" /> Pollak constantly guessing [[Jeopardy]] answers incorrectly is a running joke, which he previously did in the 1997 film [[Truth or Consequences, N.M. (film)|Truth or Consequences, N.M.]]. The idea was in Fleming's script but Pollak expanded and improvised his answers.<ref name=\"Marlow\" />\n\nDirector Robert Iscove was influenced by the movies of [[John Hughes (filmmaker)|John Hughes]], and was trying do something different for the '90s generation that would still resonate. He stressed the importance of the story having a heart, how Zack had to be worthy of Laney, and Laney had to understand she had to learn to be more open.<ref name=\"huffpo\" /> The story was rewritten to better fit Prinze Jr. and make Zack more sympathetic and have his own challenges.<ref name=\"Greco\">{{cite web |date= June 10, 2015 |last= Greco |first= Patti |title= 10 Things You Probably Never Knew About \"She's All That\" |url= https://www.cosmopolitan.com/entertainment/movies/a41771/things-you-never-knew-about-shes-all-that/ |website= Cosmopolitan }}</ref> \nIscove was well aware that it was implausible to suggest Cook was ugly, but that it was standard practice in Hollywood to cast the beautiful girl, and that it requires the audience to suspend their disbelief: \"You either go along with it or you don't go along with it.\" He compared it to the [[Clark Kent#Identity change|transformation of Clark Kent into Superman]]. Noting that a real transformation would be impractical, he said it was more about finding an actor who had the range to give the necessary performance.<ref name=\"Greco\" />\n\n{{Anchor|Filming|Locations}}\nFilming took place in various California locations.<ref>{{cite web |date=March 24, 2018 |author=Global Film Locations |title=She\u2019s All That (1999) Film Locations |url=https://globalfilmlocations.net/2018/03/24/shes-all-that-1999-film-locations/ |website=Global Film Locations }}</ref> The highschool scenes were shot at [[Torrance High School]], where [[Buffy the Vampire Slayer]] and [[Beverly Hills, 90210]] had previously filmed.<ref name=\"Marlow\" />\n\n{{Anchor|Dance|Choreography}}\nIscove was also a choreographer and wanted to expand and embellish the prom scenes, but also show the Weinsteins how musical numbers could work in films. The dance scene was choreographed by [[Adam Shankman]], who was asked to by his sister Jennifer Gibgot who was co-producer on the film. Shankman was assisted by [[Anne Fletcher]]. Shankman was concerned about the scene and \"that, tonally, it wouldn\u2019t match into the rest of the movie\" but was Iscove committed to the idea it was up to him to make it fit. Test audiences didn't understand why the dance scene was happening so Bob Weinstein asked for a reshoot with Usher to link the scene.<ref name=\"huffpo\">{{cite web |date= January 29, 2019 |last= Blickley |first= Leigh |title= The Dance Scene No One Wanted: An Oral History Of The 'She's All That' Prom |url= https://www.huffpost.com/entry/dance-scene-shes-all-that_n_5c424345e4b0a8dbe171585b |website= HuffPost }}</ref> Shankman also worked with Matthew Lillard on his dance scenes.<ref name=\"Marlow\" /><ref name=\"huffpo\" />\n\n== Soundtrack ==\nThe song \"[[Kiss Me (Sixpence None the Richer song)|Kiss Me]]\" as was used as the main theme song. The film's box office success helped \"Kiss Me\" to gain widespread mainstream attention and chart success. \"Kiss Me\" climbed to No. 2 on Billboard's Hot 100 list, and stayed in the Top 10 for 16 straight weeks.\n\nThe film was released in Italy with the title \"Kiss Me\".<ref name=\"huffpo\" /><ref name=\"Marlow\" /><ref name=\"Greco\" />\n\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable plainrowheaders\"\n|- style=\"text-align:center;\"\n! Track no. !! Title !! Writer and music composer !! Performed by \n|-\n| 01.\n| Prophecy\n| Cinjun Tate, Shelby Tate, Cedric Lemoyne, Jeffrey Cain Thompson, Gregory Slay\n| [[Remy Zero]]\n|-\n| 02.\n| Baby Got Going\n| Liz Phair & Scott Litt\n| [[Liz Phair]]\n|-\n| 03.\n| Be Free\n| Apl.de.Ap, [[will.i.am]], Stahl, Goldberg\n| [[The Black Eyed Peas]]\n|-\n| 04.\n| Blacktop Beat\n| Lucas MacFadden\n| [[Jurassic 5]]\n|-\n| 05.\n| Up To Us\n| Allrighse, [[Robin Thicke]]\n| Allrighse\n|-\n| 06.\n| Wanderer\n| J. Ralph\n| Spy\n|-\n| 07.\n| Sugar\n| Jo Lloyd, James Wright, David Magee\n| [[Stretch Princess]]\n|-\n| 08.\n| [[Kiss Me (Sixpence None the Richer song)|Kiss Me]]\n| Matt Slocum\n| [[Sixpence None The Richer]]\n|-\n| 09.\n| Test The Theory\n| Robin File, Sean McCann, Martin Merchant & Robert Maxfield\n| [[Audioweb]]\n|-\n| 10.\n| Gorgeous\n| Kat Green\n| Girl Next Door\n|-\n| 11.\n| Ooh La La\n| Theo Keating\n| [[The Wiseguys]]\n|-\n| 12.\n| Give It To Me Baby\n| Rick James\n| [[Rick James]]\n|-\n| 13.\n| Shuck & Jive\n| John Davis\n| [[Superdrag]]\n|-\n| 14.\n| Hanging On\n| Emily Gerber and Carlos Calvo\n| Emily & Carlos\n|-\n| 15.\n| 66\n| Greg Dulli\n| [[The Afghan Whigs]]\n|-\n| 16.\n| Nonstop Operation\n| MC Tunes, S. Hickling, S. Jones, M. Lawrence, G. Gasper, P. Billington\n| The Dust Junkys\n|-\n| 17.\n| Believe\n| Goldie\n| [[Goldie]]\n|-\n| 18.\n| [[The Rockafeller Skank]]\n| Fatboy Slim, Terry Winford, John Barry\n| [[Fatboy Slim]]\n\n|}\n\n== Reception ==\n\n=== Critical response ===\n''She's All That'' received mixed reviews from film critics. On review aggregator [[Rotten Tomatoes]] the film has an approval rating of 41% based on reviews from 61 critics, with an average rating of 4.94/10. The website's consensus states: \"Despite its charming young leads, ''She's All That'' can't overcome its predictable, inconsistently funny script.\"<ref>{{cite web \n| url = https://www.rottentomatoes.com/m/shes_all_that \n| title = She's All That\n| work = [[Rotten Tomatoes]]\n| publisher = [[Fandango Media]]\n| access-date = January 2, 2019\n}}</ref> On [[Metacritic]] the film has a score of 51 based on reviews from 32 critics, indicating \"mixed or average reviews\".<ref>{{cite web \n| url = https://www.metacritic.com/movie/shes-all-that\n| title = She's All That 1999\n| work = [[Metacritic]]\n| publisher = [[CBS Interactive]]\n| access-date = January 2, 2019\n}}</ref>\n\nIt was the last movie to be reviewed by [[Gene Siskel]] before his death in February 1999. Siskel gave a positive review and wrote that \"Rachael Leigh Cook, as Laney, the plain Jane object of the makeover, is forced to demonstrate the biggest emotional range as a character, and she is equal to the assignment.\"<ref>{{cite web \n| date = January 29, 1999\n| author = Gene Siskel\n| author-link = Gene Siskel\n| title = 'She's All That' A Refreshing 'My Fair Lady' \n| work = [[Chicago Tribune]]\n| url = http://articles.chicagotribune.com/1999-01-29/entertainment/9901290001_1_senior-prom-fair-lady-rachael-leigh-cook\n| url-status = dead\n| archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20140222004053/http://articles.chicagotribune.com/1999-01-29/entertainment/9901290001_1_senior-prom-fair-lady-rachael-leigh-cook\n| archive-date = February 22, 2014\n| access-date = January 2, 2019\n}}</ref> [[Roger Ebert]] suggested: \"To give the movie credit, it's as bored with the underlying plot as we are. Even the prom queen election is only a backdrop for more interesting material, as ''She's All That'' explores differences in class and style, and peppers its screenplay with very funny little moments.\" Ebert says it \"is not a great movie, but it has its moments\" giving it 2.5 out of 4 stars.<ref>{{cite web \n| date = January 29, 1999\n| author = Roger Ebert\n| author-link = Roger Ebert\n| title = She's All That\n| work = [[Chicago Sun-Times]]\n| url = https://www.rogerebert.com/reviews/shes-all-that-1999\n| access-date = January 2, 2019\n}}</ref> Stephen Holden of the ''[[New York Times]]'' praised Cook for her performance, comparing her to [[Winona Ryder]], saying \"Unlike so many actors playing smart young people, she actually projects some intelligence along with a sly sense of comedy.\"<ref>{{cite web \n| date =  \n| author = Stephen Holden \n| title = 'She's All That': When 'Pygmalion' Meets MTV, the Bookworm Turns \n| url = https://archive.nytimes.com/www.nytimes.com/library/film/012999that-film-review.html \n| website = [[New York Times]] \n}}</ref> [[Mick LaSalle]] of the [[San Francisco Chronicle]] calls it \"About one idea short of being an excellent teenage romance. As it stands it's a pleasing but routine effort.\" LaSalle criticizes the film for running out of plot about half way, saying the \"story line is stretched to the breaking point. In one instance director Robert Iscove stops the action for a long dance sequence, set at the prom, that has nothing to do with anything.\" He says the film is \"intermittently funny\" and praises Matthew Lillard's performance, calling it the best thing in the picture.<ref>{{cite web \n| date = January 29, 1999\n| author = Mick LaSalle\n| author-link = Mick LaSalle\n| title = Teen Romance Is Amusing, But Not All That\n| work = [[San Francisco Chronicle]]\n| url = https://www.sfgate.com/movies/article/Teen-Romance-Is-Amusing-But-Not-All-That-2949714.php \n| access-date = January 2, 2019\n}}</ref>\n\nGeoff Berkshire ''[[Variety (magazine)|Variety magazine]]'' was critical of the lack of originality, and suggested that \"Miramax needs to put [[Kevin Williamson (screenwriter)|Kevin Williamson]] on permanent retainer if it's going to remain in the teen-pics field, ''She's All That'' notably fails to bring to comedy the insight that the Williamson-penned ''[[Scream (1996 film)|Scream]]'' brought so memorably to horror\". Berkshire is positive about the two leads, saying \"appealing young actors come off as competent, nothing more, given a context that can\u2019t be transcended.\" He describes the direction as \"nothing to be ashamed of here, but nothing of any distinction, either\" and notes the soundtrack as a not unexpected plus.<ref>{{cite web \n| date = January 27, 1999\n| author = Geoff Berkshire\n| author-link = Geoff Berkshire\n| title = She\u2019s All That\n| work = [[Variety (magazine)|Variety magazine]]\n| url = https://variety.com/1999/film/reviews/she-s-all-that-1200456368/\n| access-date = January 2, 2019\n}}</ref>\nJane Ganahl of The San Francisco Examiner wrote \"And once, just once, I'd love to see a teen flick that doesn't send out a message to young girls that to be acceptable, you have to conform. I liked the artist girl much better before.\"<ref>{{cite web \n| date = January 29, 1999\n| author = Jane Ganahl\n| author-link = Jane Ganahl\n| title = She's not quite \"All That'\n| work = [[San Francisco Examiner]]\n| url = https://www.sfgate.com/news/article/She-s-not-quite-All-That-3098868.php\n| access-date = January 2, 2019\n}}</ref>\nWilliam Thomas at ''[[Empire (magazine)|Empire magazine]]'' criticizes the film saying that despite a few scenes \"The rest is just breezy propaganda for American high school fascism\" and \"The most worrying thing about ''She's All That'' is its message. The \"ugly duckling\" (specs, dungarees, art-lover) must conform (she gets a makeover and the boys notice her \"bobos\" for the first time) to fit in.\"<ref>{{cite web \n| date = January 1, 2000\n| author = William Thomas\n| title = She's All That Review\n| work = [[Empire magazine]]\n| url = https://www.empireonline.com/movies/shesallthat/review/\n| archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20171207141035/https://www.empireonline.com/movies/shesallthat/review/\n| archive-date = December 7, 2017\n| url-status = dead\n}}</ref>\n\n=== Box office ===\n''She\u2019s All That'' premiered on January 19, 1999 at the Mann Festival Theater in [[Westwood, Los Angeles]].<ref>{{cite web |date= January 21, 1999 |author1= Variety Staff |title= \u2018All That\u2019 set for public bow |url= https://variety.com/1999/scene/vpage/all-that-set-for-public-bow-1117490448/ |website= Variety }}</ref> The film went into general release on January 29.\n\nThe film was reached No. 1 at the box office in the first week of its release, grossing $16,065,430 over the [[Super Bowl]] opening weekend.<ref name=\"mojo\" /> It earned $63.4 million in the United States and $39.8 million at international box offices, totaling $103.2 million worldwide against a production budget between $7\u201310 million.<ref name=\"mojo\" /> Miramax spent a further <!-- according to Cook $12.5 million <ref name=\"Greco\" /> --> $18 million <!-- according to Iscove --> on television advertising to promote the film.<ref name=\"Marlow\" />\n\n=== Accolades ===\n{{Anchor|Awards}} \nThe film won eight awards, and was nominated for five others.\n\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\" \n|-\n! scope=\"col\" | Year\n! scope=\"col\" | Ceremony\n! scope=\"col\" | Category\n! scope=\"col\" | Recipients\n! scope=\"col\" | Result\n|-\n| rowspan=6| 1999\n| [[YoungStar Awards]]\n| Best Performance by a Young Actress in a Comedy Film\n| Rachael Leigh Cook\n| {{Won}}\n|-\n| rowspan=3| [[Teen Choice Awards]]\n| Choice Movie Actor\n| Freddie Prinze, Jr.\n| {{Won}}\n|-\n| Choice Movie: Love Scene\n| Freddie Prinze, Jr. & Rachael Leigh Cook\n| {{Won}}\n|-\n| colspan=2| Choice Movie: Comedy\n| {{Nominated}}\n|-\n| rowspan=2| [[MTV Movie Awards]]\n| Best Breakthrough Female Performance\n| Rachael Leigh Cook\n| {{Nominated}}\n|-\n| Best On-Screen Duo\n| Freddie Prinze, Jr. & Rachael Leigh Cook\n| {{Nominated}}\n|-\n| rowspan=7| 2000\n| rowspan=2| [[Young Hollywood Awards]]\n| Best Bad Girl\n| Jodi Lyn O'Keefe\n| {{Won}}\n|-\n| Best Song\n| [[Sixpence None the Richer]] <small>(\"[[Kiss Me (Sixpence None the Richer song)|Kiss Me]]\")</small>\n| {{Won}}\n|-\n| [[Kids' Choice Awards|Kids' Choice Awards, USA]]\n| Favorite Movie Couple\n| Freddie Prinze, Jr. & Rachael Leigh Cook\n| {{Won}}\n|-\n| rowspan=2| [[Blockbuster Entertainment Awards]] <ref>{{cite press release | date = February 8, 2000 |url= http://www.prnewswire.com/news-releases/nominees-announced-for-sixth-annual-blockbuster-entertainment-awardsr-to-air-in-june-on-fox-72458137.html |title= Nominees Announced for 'Sixth Annual Blockbuster Entertainment Awards(R)' To Air in June on FOX |work= [[Blockbuster Pressroom]] |publisher= Blockbuster LLC | archive-url = https://archive.today/20130615233011/http://blockbuster.mwnewsroom.com/manual-releases/Nominees-Announced-for--Sixth-Annual-Blockbuster-E | archive-date = June 15, 2013 | url-status = dead |access-date = January 2, 2019 }}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url= https://variety.com/2000/film/news/blockbuster-entertainment-award-winners-1117781474/ |title= Blockbuster Entertainment Award winners  |date= May 9, 2000 | author = Variety Staff |website=[[Variety (magazine)|Variety]] |publisher= |access-date= January 3, 2019 }}</ref>\n| Favorite Actress \u2013 Newcomer (Internet Only)\n| Rachael Leigh Cook\n| {{Won}}\n|-\n| Favorite Actor \u2013 Comedy/Romance\n| Freddie Prinze, Jr.\n| {{Nominated}}\n|-\n| [[ASCAP Film and Television Music Awards]]\n| Most Performed Songs from Motion Pictures\n| [[Matt Slocum]] <small>(\"Kiss Me\")</small>\n| {{Won}}\n|-\n| [[ALMA Awards]]\n| Outstanding Actor in a Feature Film\n| Freddie Prinze, Jr.\n| {{Nominated}}\n|}\n\n== References ==\n{{Notelist}}\n{{Reflist}}\n\n== External links ==\n{{Wikiquote}}\n* {{Official website|http://www.miramax.com/movie/shes-all-that}}\n* {{IMDb title|0160862|She's All That}}\n* {{Rotten Tomatoes|shes_all_that|She's All That}}\n* {{Mojo title|shesallthat|She's All That}}\n\n{{Robert Iscove}}\n{{Pygmalion}}\n\n[[Category:1999 films]]\n[[Category:1990s coming-of-age comedy films]]\n[[Category:1990s high school films]]\n[[Category:1990s romantic comedy films]]\n[[Category:1990s teen comedy films]]\n[[Category:1990s teen romance films]]\n[[Category:American coming-of-age films]]\n[[Category:American films]]\n[[Category:American high school films]]\n[[Category:American romantic comedy films]]\n[[Category:American teen comedy films]]\n[[Category:American teen romance films]]\n[[Category:Coming-of-age romance films]]\n[[Category:English-language films]]\n[[Category:Films scored by Stewart Copeland]]\n[[Category:Films set in California]]\n[[Category:Films shot in Los Angeles]]\n[[Category:Films about proms]]\n[[Category:Films directed by Robert Iscove]]\n[[Category:Miramax films]]\n", "name_user": "Sunshineisles2", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eBox office", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/She%27s_All_That"}
{"title_page": "Kaitlan Collins", "text_new": "{{short description|American journalist}}\n{{Use American English|date=November 2019}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=November 2019}}\n{{Infobox person\n| name               = Kaitlan Collins\n| image              = <!-- filename only, no \"File:\" or \"Image:\" prefix, and no enclosing [[brackets]] -->\n| alt                = <!-- descriptive text for use by speech synthesis (text-to-speech) software -->\n| caption            = \n| birth_name         = <!-- only use if different from name -->\n| birth_date         = {{Birth date and age|1992|04|07}}\n| birth_place        = \n| nationality        = \n| other_names        = \n| alma_mater         = [[University of Alabama]] (BA)\n| occupation         = Journalist\n| years_active       = 2014\u2013present\n| known_for          = \n| notable_works      = \n}}\n'''Kaitlan Collins''' (born April 7, 1992)<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.instagram.com/p/Bv9digXHmJa/|title=@kaitlancollins|publisher=Instagram|accessdate=17 January 2020|quote=Last ride on Air Force One as a 26-year-old. \ud83d\ude0e}}</ref> is an American journalist. She is a [[White House Correspondents' Association|White House correspondent]] for [[CNN]]. Previously, Collins served as the White House Correspondent for the website ''[[The Daily Caller]]''.<ref name=\"adweek\">{{cite web|url=http://www.adweek.com/tvnewser/kaitlan-collins-joins-cnn-from-the-daily-caller/332413|title=Kaitlan Collins Joins CNN from The Daily Caller|website=www.adweek.com|language=en-US|access-date=January 28, 2018}}</ref>\n\n== Early life ==\nCollins graduated from [[Prattville High School]] in [[Prattville, Alabama]] and went on to attend the [[University of Alabama]], where she a member of [[Alpha Phi]] sorority.<ref>Ivana Hrynkiw, [https://www.al.com/news/birmingham/2018/10/cnn_reporter_alabama_native_ap.html CNN's Kaitlan Collins apologizes for tweets from her University of Alabama days], [[AL.com]] (October 8, 2018).</ref> After graduating with a [[Bachelor of Arts]] in journalism and political science in May 2014, Collins moved to [[Washington, D.C.]].<ref name=\":0\" />\n\n==Career ==\nIn June 2014, Collins was hired by ''The Daily Caller'' as an entertainment reporter; she became the website's [[White House correspondent]] in January 2017.<ref name=\":0\">{{cite web|url=https://www.adweek.com/tvnewser/kaitlan-collins-joins-cnn-from-the-daily-caller/332413|title=Kaitlan Collins Joins CNN from The Daily Caller|website=www.adweek.com|language=en-US|access-date=August 4, 2018}}</ref> In 2017, Collins joined CNN as a White House correspondent.<ref name=\"adweek\" /> She has traveled with President Trump to at least half a dozen countries.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://edition.cnn.com/profiles/kaitlan-collins|title=Kaitlan Collins official Biography at the CNN site|accessdate=July 27, 2018|work=www.cnn.com}}</ref>\n\nIn July 2018, Collins was barred from a [[Trump administration]] press conference in the [[White House Rose Garden]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.foxnews.com/politics/cnn-correspondent-blocked-from-white-house-press-event|title=CNN correspondent blocked from White House press event|date=July 25, 2018|author=Matt Richardson|publisher=Fox News}}</ref> Collins said that she was barred from the event after asking Trump questions about Russian President [[Vladimir Putin]] and Trump's former attorney [[Michael Cohen (lawyer)|Michael Cohen]] in the Oval Office. Collins said she was told by senior White House officials that such questions were \"inappropriate for that venue.\"<ref name=bbcrow>{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/world-us-canada-44963659|title=Kaitlan Collins: Row over CNN reporter's White House ban|publisher=BBC News|date=July 26, 2018}}</ref> Trump's press secretary Sarah Sanders asserted that Collins \"shouted questions and refused to leave,\"<ref name=bbcrow/> while Trump's advisor [[Kellyanne Conway]] said that the action was about \"being polite.\"<ref name=\"abcnewsdeny\">{{cite web|url=https://abcnews.go.com/Politics/white-house-disputes-cnns-kaitlan-collins-banned/story?id=56837450|title=White House disputes that CNN's Kaitlan Collins was 'banned'|author=Jordyn Phelps|date=July 26, 2018|publisher=ABC News}}</ref> Trump's deputy chief of staff for communications, [[Bill Shine]], objected to the characterization of the White House's action as a \"ban\" but \"declined to tell reporters what word he would use to characterize the White House\u2019s decision to block her from attending the event.\"<ref name=\"abcnewsdeny\"/> CNN stated that the ban on Collins was \"retaliatory\" and \"not indicative of an open and free press.\" The [[White House Correspondents Association]] called the ban \"wholly inappropriate, wrong-headed, and weak.\"<ref name=\"bbcrow\" /><ref name=\"abcnewsdeny\" /> [[Jay Wallace (journalist)|Jay Wallace]], president of [[Fox News]], issued a statement in support of Collins, saying that his organization \"[stood] in strong solidarity with CNN for the right to full access for our journalists as part of a free and unfettered press.\"<ref name=\"bbcrow\" />\n\nIn April 2020, she questioned the president about his claim of total authority.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.salon.com/2020/04/14/paula-reid-and-kaitlan-collins-pop-the-toddler-kings-balloon--and-he-melts-down/|title=Paula Reid and Kaitlan Collins pop the toddler king's balloon \u2014 and he melts down|date=2020-04-14|website=Salon|language=en|access-date=2020-04-15}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.thedailybeast.com/defiant-trump-claims-authority-of-the-president-is-total-in-reopening-economy|title=Defiant Trump Claims \u2018Authority of the President Is Total\u2019 in Reopening Economy|last=Tucker|first=Emma|date=2020-04-13|website=The Daily Beast|language=en|access-date=2020-04-15}}</ref>\n\n== Recognition ==\nIn 2018, Collins was [[Mediaite]]'s number 50 Most Influential person in News Media amongst news figures such as [[Jake Tapper]], [[Trevor Noah]], and [[Rachel Maddow]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.mediaite.com/online/mediaites-most-influential-in-news-media-2018/3/ |title=Mediaite's Most Influential in News Media 2018 - Part 3 |publisher=Mediaite.com |date=December 6, 2018 |accessdate=July 5, 2019}}</ref> Collins was named to Crain's NewsPro's 12 to Watch in TV News in January 2019.<ref>[https://www.crainsnewspro.com/assets/newspro/pdf/2019-01-newspro.pdf ''Crain News Pro'']. January 2019. p. 11.</ref> She was also named one of ''[[Forbes]]'' magazine's ''30 under 30: Media'' in 2019.<ref>{{cite web|author= |url=https://www.forbes.com/30-under-30/2019/media/#43d322546a59 |title=30 Under 30 2019: Media |publisher=Forbes.com |date=November 13, 2018 |accessdate=July 5, 2019}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n== External links ==\n* {{IMDb name}}\n\n{{authority control}}\n{{CNN Anchors}}\n{{CNN International personalities}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Collins, Kaitlan}}\n[[Category:1992 births]]\n[[Category:American television reporters and correspondents]]\n[[Category:CNN people]]\n[[Category:University of Alabama alumni]]\n[[Category:Journalists from Alabama]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:People from Prattville, Alabama]]\n[[Category:American women television journalists]]\n[[Category:21st-century American journalists]]\n[[Category:21st-century American women writers]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|American journalist}}\n{{Use American English|date=November 2019}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=November 2019}}\n{{Infobox person\n| name               = Kaitlan Collins\n| image              = <!-- filename only, no \"File:\" or \"Image:\" prefix, and no enclosing [[brackets]] -->\n| alt                = <!-- descriptive text for use by speech synthesis (text-to-speech) software -->\n| caption            = \n| birth_name         = <!-- only use if different from name -->\n| birth_date         = {{Birth date and age|1992|04|07}}\n| birth_place        = \n| nationality        = \n| other_names        = \n| alma_mater         = [[University of Alabama]] (BA)\n| occupation         = Journalist\n| years_active       = 2014\u2013present\n| known_for          = \n| notable_works      = \n}}\n'''Kaitlan Collins''' (born April 7, 1992)<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.instagram.com/p/Bv9digXHmJa/|title=@kaitlancollins|publisher=Instagram|accessdate=17 January 2020|quote=Last ride on Air Force One as a 26-year-old. \ud83d\ude0e}}</ref> is an American journalist. She is a [[White House Correspondents' Association|White House correspondent]] for [[CNN]]. Previously, Collins served as the White House Correspondent for the website ''[[The Daily Caller]]''.<ref name=\"adweek\">{{cite web|url=http://www.adweek.com/tvnewser/kaitlan-collins-joins-cnn-from-the-daily-caller/332413|title=Kaitlan Collins Joins CNN from The Daily Caller|website=www.adweek.com|language=en-US|access-date=January 28, 2018}}</ref>\n\n== Early life ==\nCollins graduated from [[Prattville High School]] in [[Prattville, Alabama]] and went on to attend the [[University of Alabama]].<ref>Ivana Hrynkiw, [https://www.al.com/news/birmingham/2018/10/cnn_reporter_alabama_native_ap.html CNN's Kaitlan Collins apologizes for tweets from her University of Alabama days], [[AL.com]] (October 8, 2018).</ref> Collins attended the University of Alabama where she was also a member of [[Alpha Phi]] sorority. After graduating with a [[Bachelor of Arts]] in journalism and political science in May 2014, Collins moved to [[Washington, D.C.]].<ref name=\":0\" />\n\n==Career ==\nIn June 2014, Collins was hired by ''The Daily Caller'' as an entertainment reporter; she became the website's [[White House correspondent]] in January 2017.<ref name=\":0\">{{cite web|url=https://www.adweek.com/tvnewser/kaitlan-collins-joins-cnn-from-the-daily-caller/332413|title=Kaitlan Collins Joins CNN from The Daily Caller|website=www.adweek.com|language=en-US|access-date=August 4, 2018}}</ref> In 2017, Collins joined CNN as a White House correspondent.<ref name=\"adweek\" /> She has traveled with President Trump to at least half a dozen countries.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://edition.cnn.com/profiles/kaitlan-collins|title=Kaitlan Collins official Biography at the CNN site|accessdate=July 27, 2018|work=www.cnn.com}}</ref>\n\nIn July 2018, Collins was barred from a [[Trump administration]] press conference in the [[White House Rose Garden]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.foxnews.com/politics/cnn-correspondent-blocked-from-white-house-press-event|title=CNN correspondent blocked from White House press event|date=July 25, 2018|author=Matt Richardson|publisher=Fox News}}</ref> Collins said that she was barred from the event after asking Trump questions about Russian President [[Vladimir Putin]] and Trump's former attorney [[Michael Cohen (lawyer)|Michael Cohen]] in the Oval Office. Collins said she was told by senior White House officials that such questions were \"inappropriate for that venue.\"<ref name=bbcrow>{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/world-us-canada-44963659|title=Kaitlan Collins: Row over CNN reporter's White House ban|publisher=BBC News|date=July 26, 2018}}</ref> Trump's press secretary Sarah Sanders asserted that Collins \"shouted questions and refused to leave,\"<ref name=bbcrow/> while Trump's advisor [[Kellyanne Conway]] said that the action was about \"being polite.\"<ref name=\"abcnewsdeny\">{{cite web|url=https://abcnews.go.com/Politics/white-house-disputes-cnns-kaitlan-collins-banned/story?id=56837450|title=White House disputes that CNN's Kaitlan Collins was 'banned'|author=Jordyn Phelps|date=July 26, 2018|publisher=ABC News}}</ref> Trump's deputy chief of staff for communications, [[Bill Shine]], objected to the characterization of the White House's action as a \"ban\" but \"declined to tell reporters what word he would use to characterize the White House\u2019s decision to block her from attending the event.\"<ref name=\"abcnewsdeny\"/> CNN stated that the ban on Collins was \"retaliatory\" and \"not indicative of an open and free press.\" The [[White House Correspondents Association]] called the ban \"wholly inappropriate, wrong-headed, and weak.\"<ref name=\"bbcrow\" /><ref name=\"abcnewsdeny\" /> [[Jay Wallace (journalist)|Jay Wallace]], president of [[Fox News]], issued a statement in support of Collins, saying that his organization \"[stood] in strong solidarity with CNN for the right to full access for our journalists as part of a free and unfettered press.\"<ref name=\"bbcrow\" />\n\nIn April 2020, she questioned the president about his claim of total authority.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.salon.com/2020/04/14/paula-reid-and-kaitlan-collins-pop-the-toddler-kings-balloon--and-he-melts-down/|title=Paula Reid and Kaitlan Collins pop the toddler king's balloon \u2014 and he melts down|date=2020-04-14|website=Salon|language=en|access-date=2020-04-15}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.thedailybeast.com/defiant-trump-claims-authority-of-the-president-is-total-in-reopening-economy|title=Defiant Trump Claims \u2018Authority of the President Is Total\u2019 in Reopening Economy|last=Tucker|first=Emma|date=2020-04-13|website=The Daily Beast|language=en|access-date=2020-04-15}}</ref>\n\n== Recognition ==\nIn 2018, Collins was [[Mediaite]]'s number 50 Most Influential person in News Media amongst news figures such as [[Jake Tapper]], [[Trevor Noah]], and [[Rachel Maddow]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.mediaite.com/online/mediaites-most-influential-in-news-media-2018/3/ |title=Mediaite's Most Influential in News Media 2018 - Part 3 |publisher=Mediaite.com |date=December 6, 2018 |accessdate=July 5, 2019}}</ref> Collins was named to Crain's NewsPro's 12 to Watch in TV News in January 2019.<ref>[https://www.crainsnewspro.com/assets/newspro/pdf/2019-01-newspro.pdf ''Crain News Pro'']. January 2019. p. 11.</ref> She was also named one of ''[[Forbes]]'' magazine's ''30 under 30: Media'' in 2019.<ref>{{cite web|author= |url=https://www.forbes.com/30-under-30/2019/media/#43d322546a59 |title=30 Under 30 2019: Media |publisher=Forbes.com |date=November 13, 2018 |accessdate=July 5, 2019}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n== External links ==\n* {{IMDb name}}\n\n{{authority control}}\n{{CNN Anchors}}\n{{CNN International personalities}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Collins, Kaitlan}}\n[[Category:1992 births]]\n[[Category:American television reporters and correspondents]]\n[[Category:CNN people]]\n[[Category:University of Alabama alumni]]\n[[Category:Journalists from Alabama]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:People from Prattville, Alabama]]\n[[Category:American women television journalists]]\n[[Category:21st-century American journalists]]\n[[Category:21st-century American women writers]]\n", "name_user": "Mhsmd", "label": "safe", "comment": "More concise.", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Kaitlan_Collins"}
{"title_page": "Michael Schumacher", "text_new": "{{about||the American politician|Michael Shoemaker|the Luxembourgian athlete|Mike Schumacher}}\n{{use dmy dates|date=October 2019}}\n{{short description|German racing driver}}\n{{Infobox F1 driver\n| name            = Michael Schumacher\n| image           = File:Schumacher china 2012 crop.jpg\n| caption         = Schumacher at the [[2012 Chinese Grand Prix]]\n| birth_date      = {{birth date and age|1969|1|3|df=y}}\n| birth_place     = [[H\u00fcrth]], [[West Germany]]\n| nationality     = {{flagicon|DEU}} German\n| Years           = {{F1|1991}}\u2013{{F1|2006}}, {{F1|2010}}\u2013{{F1|2012}}\n| Team(s)         = [[Jordan Grand Prix|Jordan]], [[Benetton Formula|Benetton]], [[Scuderia Ferrari|Ferrari]], [[Mercedes-Benz in Formula One|Mercedes]]\n| Races           = 308 (306 starts)\n| Championships   = 7 ({{F1|1994}}, {{F1|1995}}, {{F1|2000}}, {{F1 |2001}}, {{F1|2002}}, {{F1|2003}}, {{F1|2004}})\n| Wins            = [[List of Formula One Grand Prix wins by Michael Schumacher|91]]\n| Podiums         = 155\n| Points          = 1,566\n| Poles           = 68<!--Please do not change this to 69. Because pole refers to the position in which you start, not the position you qualify the 2012 Monaco Grand Peix does not contribute to this total.-->\n| Fastest laps    = 77\n| First race      = [[1991 Belgian Grand Prix]]\n| First win       = [[1992 Belgian Grand Prix]]\n| Last win        = [[2006 Chinese Grand Prix]]\n| Last race       = [[2012 Brazilian Grand Prix]]\n| module1         = \n  {{Infobox Le Mans driver|subbox=yes\n  | Years       = {{24hLM|1991}}\n  | Teams       = [[Sauber|Team Sauber]] [[Mercedes-Benz in motorsport|Mercedes]]\n  | Best Finish = 5th in C2 (1991)\n  | Class Wins  = 0\n  }}\n}}\n\n'''Michael Schumacher''' ({{IPAc-en|\u02c8|\u0283|u\u02d0|m|\u0251\u02d0|k|\u0259r}}; {{IPA-de|\u02c8m\u026a\u00e7a\u02d0\u0294e\u02d0l \u02c8\u0283u\u02d0max\u0250|lang|De-Michael-Schumacher.ogg}}; born 3 January 1969)<ref>{{cite web|url= https://www.upi.com/Top_News/2019/01/03/UPI-Almanac-for-Thursday-Jan-3-2019/1811546209344/|title= UPI Almanac for Thursday, Jan. 3, 2019|agency=[[United Press International]]|date=3 January 2019|accessdate=3 September 2019|archivedate=3 January 2019 |archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20190103223323/https://www.upi.com/Top_News/2019/01/03/UPI-Almanac-for-Thursday-Jan-3-2019/1811546209344/|url-status=live|quote= German racing champion Michael Schumacher in 1969 (age 50)}}</ref> is a retired German [[racing driver]] who raced in [[Formula One]] for [[Jordan Grand Prix]], [[Benetton Formula|Benetton]] and [[Scuderia Ferrari|Ferrari]], where he spent most of his career, as well as for [[Mercedes AMG Petronas|Mercedes]] upon his return to the sport. Widely regarded as one of the greatest Formula One drivers ever,<ref>{{cite news|url= http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport2/hi/motorsport/formula_one/3168114.stm|title= Who is the greatest ever?|publisher=BBC | work = Sport |first= Andrew |last= Benson|date=12 October 2003|accessdate= 30 July 2011}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |title= The final five could all have been No. 1, but only Foyt gets the prize |url=http://sports.espn.go.com/rpm/racing/columns/story?columnist=blount_terry&id=3407489 |publisher=[[ESPN]] |date= 23 May 2008 |accessdate=18 July 2011}}</ref><ref name=\"SchuAS2\">{{cite web|title=Formula 1's Greatest Drivers: 2. Michael Schumacher |url=http://f1greatestdrivers.autosport.com/?driver=2|work= [[Autosport]] |publisher=[[Haymarket Media Group|Haymarket Publications]] |date=10 December 2009|accessdate=10 December 2009}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.independent.co.uk/sport/motor-racing/the-ten-best-formula-one-drivers-1920034.html|first=Simon|last= Rice |title=The ten best Formula One drivers|date=12 March 2010|accessdate= 30 July 2011|work=The Independent |location=UK|publisher= Independent Print Ltd}}</ref> and regarded by some as the greatest of all time,<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/formula-1/2016/08/25/25-reasons-why-michael-schumacher-is-the-greatest-f1-driver-of-a/|first=Sean|last=Gibson|title=25 reasons why Michael Schumacher is the greatest F1 driver of all time|date=25 August 2016|accessdate= 13 June 2017|location=UK|work=The Telegraph}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/sport/2006/oct/18/formulaone.comment|title=Is Schumacher the greatest driver of all time?|date=19 October 2006|accessdate= 13 June 2017|location=UK|work=The Guardian}}</ref> Schumacher is the only driver in history to win seven Formula One [[List of Formula One World Drivers' Champions|World Championships]], five of which he won consecutively. The most successful driver in the history of the sport, Schumacher holds the records for the [[List of Formula One driver records#Total championships|most World Championship titles]] (7), the [[most Grand Prix wins]] (91), the [[List of Formula One driver records#Total fastest laps|most fastest laps]] (77) and the [[List of Formula One driver records#Most wins in a season|most races won in a single season]] (13), and according to the official Formula One website (Formula1.com), Schumacher was \"statistically the greatest driver the sport has ever seen\" at the time of his retirement from the sport.<ref name=\"most successful\">{{cite web |title=Michael Schumacher \u2013 the end of an era |publisher=Formula1.com |date=10 September 2006 |url=http://www.formula1.com/news/features/2006/9/4932.html |accessdate=24 October 2006 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20080629013120/http://www.formula1.com/news/features/2006/9/4932.html |archive-date=29 June 2008 |url-status=live  }}</ref> He was also noted throughout his career for pushing his car to the very limit for sustained periods and a pioneering fitness regime.<ref name=\"autoracing\" /><ref name=\":1\" />\n\nAfter success in [[kart racing|karting]] as a child, Schumacher won titles in [[Formula K\u00f6nig]] and [[Formula Three]] before joining [[Mercedes-Benz in motorsport|Mercedes]] in the [[World Sportscar Championship]]. In 1991 his Mercedes-funded race debut for the [[Jordan Grand Prix|Jordan]] Formula One team resulted in Schumacher being signed by [[Benetton Formula|Benetton]] for the rest of that season. He finished third in 1992 and fourth in 1993, before becoming the first German World Drivers' Champion in 1994 by one point over [[Damon Hill]], albeit in controversial circumstances. In 1995 he repeated the success, this time with a greater margin. In 1996 Schumacher moved to [[Scuderia Ferrari|Ferrari]], who had last won the Drivers' Championship in [[1979 Formula One season|1979]], and helped them transform into the most successful team in Formula One history, as he came close to winning the 1997 and 1998 titles, before breaking his leg at the [[1999 British Grand Prix]], ending another title run.\n\nSchumacher won five consecutive drivers' titles from 2000 to 2004, including an unprecedented sixth and seventh title. In [[2002 Formula One season|2002]] Schumacher won the title with a record six races remaining and finished on the podium in every race. In [[2004 Formula One season|2004]] Schumacher won twelve out of the first thirteen races and went on to win a record 13 times as he won his final title. Schumacher retired from Formula One in 2006, after finishing runner-up to [[Renault in Formula One|Renault]]'s [[Fernando Alonso]].<ref name=\"retirement\">{{cite news |title=It's official: Schumi to retire |publisher=ITV |date=11 September 2006 |url=http://www.itv-f1.com/News_Article.aspx?PO_ID=37307 |accessdate=24 October 2006 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20061004204636/http://www.itv-f1.com/News_Article.aspx?PO_ID=37307 |archivedate=4 October 2006  }}</ref> Schumacher returned to Formula One in 2010 with [[Mercedes-Benz in Formula One|Mercedes]]. He produced the fastest qualifying time at the [[2012 Monaco Grand Prix]], and achieved his only podium on his return at the [[2012 European Grand Prix]], where he finished third. In October 2012 Schumacher announced he would retire for a second time at the end of the season.<ref name= SchuRetire>{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/0/formula1/19826983 |title=Michael Schumacher to retire from Formula 1 at end of season|date=4 October 2012|work=BBC Sport|accessdate=4 January 2014}}</ref>\n\nHis career was at times controversial, as he was twice involved in collisions in the final race of a season that determined the outcome of the World Championship, with [[Damon Hill]] in [[1994 Formula One season|1994]] in [[1994 Australian Grand Prix|Adelaide]], and with [[Jacques Villeneuve]] in [[1997 Formula One season|1997]] in [[1997 European Grand Prix|Jerez]].<ref>{{cite news |last=Benson |first=Andrew |title= Schumacher's chequered history |publisher=BBC | work = Sport |date= 28 May 2006 |url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/motorsport/formula_one/5024532.stm |accessdate=8 November 2006}}</ref> Schumacher is an ambassador for [[UNESCO]] and has been involved in numerous humanitarian efforts throughout his life, donating tens of millions of dollars to charity.<ref name=\"donated50mil\">{{cite news | last = Duff | first = Alex | title = Schumacher, Seven-Time Champion, to Quit Formula One (Update 1) | publisher = Bloomberg | date = 10 September 2006 | url = https://www.bloomberg.com/apps/news?pid=20601100&sid=azdH01IQrFLs&refer=germany | accessdate = 18 January 2007 }}</ref> Schumacher and his younger brother, [[Ralf Schumacher|Ralf]], are the only siblings to win races in Formula One, and they were the first brothers to finish 1st and 2nd in the same race, a feat they repeated in four subsequent races.\n\nOn 29 December 2013 Schumacher suffered severe brain injury in a skiing accident. He was placed in a [[Induced coma|medically induced coma]] for six months until 16 June 2014. He left the hospital in [[Grenoble]] for further rehabilitation at the [[University Hospital of Lausanne]].<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.24heures.ch/vaud-regions/lausanne-region/approche-novatrice-chuv-soigner-michael-schumacher/story/16189238|title=Neuro-r\u00e9\u00e9ducation: Au CHUV, Michael Schumacher recevra des soins de pointe |work=24 heures |accessdate=9 September 2014|date=17 June 2014 |last1=Mn |first1=Marie Nicollier / A. }}</ref> On 9 September 2014, Schumacher was relocated to his home where he continues to receive medical treatment and rehabilitation privately.<ref name=goinghome>{{cite news |url= https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/world-europe-29130742 |title= Michael Schumacher leaves hospital for recovery at home| publisher =BBC | work = News|accessdate=9 September 2014|date= 9 September 2014}}</ref> As of 2016, he remained unable to walk or stand.<ref name=walk1 /><ref name=walk2 /> In July 2019, former [[Ferrari]] manager [[Jean Todt]] said that Schumacher was making \"good progress\" but also \"struggles to communicate\".<ref name=\"telegraph-2019-07\" />\n\n== Early years ==\n[[File:Reynard F 903-001 1990 Michael Schuhmacher Formula 3 EMS.jpg|thumb|Schumacher's title-winning German [[Formula Three]] car from 1990]]\nSchumacher was born in [[H\u00fcrth]], North Rhine-Westphalia, to Rolf Schumacher, a [[bricklayer]],<ref name=\"schumacher hof\">{{cite web |title=Hall of Fame \u2013 World Champions: Michael Schumacher |first=Gerald |last=Donaldson |publisher=Formula1.com |url=https://www.formula1.com/en/championship/drivers/hall-of-fame/Michael_Schumacher.html |accessdate=28 May 2018 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20171006112041/https://www.formula1.com/en/championship/drivers/hall-of-fame/Michael_Schumacher.html |archivedate=6 October 2017}}</ref> and his wife Elisabeth. When Schumacher was four, his father modified his [[pedal car|pedal kart]] by adding a small motorcycle engine. When Schumacher crashed it into a lamp post in [[Kerpen]], his parents took him to the [[karting]] track at Kerpen-Horrem, where he became the youngest member of the karting club. His father soon built him a kart from discarded parts and at the age of six Schumacher won his first club championship. To support his son's racing, Rolf Schumacher took on a second job renting and repairing karts, while his wife worked at the track's canteen. Nevertheless, when Michael needed a new engine costing 800 [[German mark|DM]], his parents were unable to afford it; he was able to continue racing with support from local businessmen.<ref>{{cite book\n | last      = Collings\n | first     = Timothy\n | title     = Team Schumacher\n | publisher = Highdown\n | year      = 2005\n | pages     = 35\u201337\n | isbn      = 978-1-905156-03-0\n}}</ref>\n\nRegulations in Germany require a driver to be at least fourteen years old to obtain a kart license. To get around this, Schumacher obtained a license in [[Luxembourg]] at the age of 12.<ref name=\"early years\">{{cite web\n | title      = The Beginning\n | publisher  = mschumacher.com\n | year       = 2006\n | url        = http://www.mschumacher.com/history.html\n | accessdate = 23 April 2007\n}}</ref>\n\nIn 1983, he obtained his German license, a year after he won the German Junior Kart Championship. From 1984 on, Schumacher won many German and European kart championships. He joined Eurokart dealer Adolf Neubert in 1985 and by 1987 he was the German and European kart champion, then he quit school and began working as a mechanic. In 1988 he made his first step into single-seat car racing by participating in the German [[Formula Ford]] and [[Formula K\u00f6nig]] series, winning the latter.<ref name=\"early results\">{{cite book\n | last      = Domenjoz\n | first     = Luc\n | title     = Michael Schumacher : Rise of a genius\n | publisher = Parragon\n | year      = 2002\n | pages     = 10\u201312, 170\u2013171\n | isbn      = 978-0-7525-9228-2\n}}</ref>\n\nIn 1989, Schumacher signed with [[Willi Weber]]'s WTS [[Formula Three]] team. Funded by Weber, he competed in the German Formula 3 series, winning the title in 1990.<ref name=\"early years\" /> He also won the [[Macau Grand Prix]] in 1990 under controversial circumstances. He placed second behind [[Mika H\u00e4kkinen]] in the first heat, three seconds behind. At the start of the second heat, he overtook H\u00e4kkinen, who only had to finish within three seconds of Schumacher to clinch the overall win. In the closing laps, Schumacher made a mistake, allowing H\u00e4kkinen to attempt to overtake. Schumacher blocked his competitor, who crashed into the back of his car. While H\u00e4kkinen spun and lost time, Schumacher cruised to victory without a rear wing.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Kopu |first1=Ville |last2=Nottmeier |first2=Jan |title=Schumacher 500: Has the King Lost His Crown? |url=http://atlasf1.autosport.com/98/ger/schum.html |website=autosport.com |accessdate=27 February 2020 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20151007021024/http://atlasf1.autosport.com/98/ger/schum.html |archivedate=7 October 2015 |date=24 October 2006}}</ref>\n\nAt the end of 1990, along with his Formula 3 rivals [[Heinz-Harald Frentzen]] and [[Karl Wendlinger]], he joined the [[Mercedes-Benz|Mercedes]] junior racing programme in the [[1990 World Sportscar Championship season|World Sports-Prototype Championship]]. This was unusual for a young driver: most of Schumacher's contemporaries would compete in [[Formula 3000]] on the way to Formula One. However, Weber advised Schumacher that being exposed to professional press conferences and driving powerful cars in long distance races would help his career.<ref name=\"early years\" /> In the [[1990 World Sportscar Championship season]], Schumacher won the season finale at the [[Aut\u00f3dromo Hermanos Rodr\u00edguez]] in a [[Sauber]]\u2013[[Mercedes-Benz C11|Mercedes C11]], and finished fifth in the drivers' championship despite only driving in three of the nine races. He continued with the team in the [[1991 World Sportscar Championship season]], winning again at the final race of the season at [[Autopolis]] in Japan with a [[Sauber]]\u2013[[Mercedes-Benz C291]], leading to a ninth-place finish in the drivers' championship. He also competed at [[1991 24 Hours of Le Mans|Le Mans]] during that season, finishing 5th in a car shared with [[Karl Wendlinger]] and Fritz Kreutzpointner. In 1991, he competed in one race in the [[Formula Nippon|Japanese Formula 3000 Championship]], finishing second.<!--Commented out ref to DTM, as it does not appear in the ref I've used: \", and the [[DTM (racing)|German Touring Car Championship]] in the early 1990s.\"--><ref name=\"early results\" />\n\n== Formula One career ==\n<!-- [[otheus]]: this belongs somewhere else -->\nSchumacher was noted throughout his career for his ability to produce fast laps at crucial moments in a race and to push his car to the very limit for sustained periods.<ref name=\"autoracing\" /> He was also noted for his pioneering fitness regime and ability to galvanise teams around him.<ref name=\"SchuAS2\" /><ref name=\":1\">{{Cite book |last=Hamilton |first=Maurice |title=Formula One: The Champions: 70 years of legendary F1 drivers |publisher=White Lion Publishing |year=2020 |isbn=9781781319468 |pages=166\u2013175}}</ref> Motor sport author Christopher Hilton observed in 2003 that a \"measure of a driver's capabilities is his performance in wet races, because the most delicate car control and sensitivity are needed\", and noted that like other great drivers, Schumacher's record in wet conditions shows very few mistakes: up to the end of the 2003 season, Schumacher won 17 of the 30 races in wet conditions he contested.<ref>{{cite book\n | last      = Hilton\n | first     = Christopher\n | title     = Michael Schumacher : The greatest of all\n | publisher = Haynes\n | year      = 2003\n | pages     = 131\u2013132\n | isbn      = 978-1-84425-044-8\n}}\nHilton has defined a race in wet conditions as \"all races where it rained \u2013 even if that was a shower\".</ref><!--\n--> Some of Schumacher's best performances occurred in such conditions, earning him the nicknames \"''Regenk\u00f6nig''\" (rain king)<ref>{{cite web\n |last        = Hardcastle\n |first       = Jonathon\n |title       = Michael Schumacher\n |url         = http://www.artwoo.com/article/michael-schumacher\n |accessdate  = 12 July 2007\n |url-status     = dead\n |archiveurl  = https://web.archive.org/web/20070927204445/http://www.artwoo.com/article/michael-schumacher\n |archivedate = 27 September 2007\n |df          = dmy-all\n}}</ref><!--\n--> or \"''Regenmeister''\" (rain master),<ref name=\"autoracing\">{{cite web\n | title      = Michael Schumacher \u2013 Master of the F1 Circuit\n | publisher  = Auto Racing\n | url        = http://www.autoracing.com/formula-1/drivers/michael-schumacher/\n | accessdate = 12 July 2007\n}}</ref><ref>{{cite news\n | title      = Schumacher races to victory\n | work  = BBC Sport\n | date       = 18 March 2001\n | url        = http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/motorsport/formula_one/1227766.stm\n | accessdate = 24 October 2006\n}}</ref><!--\n--> even in the non-German-language media. He is known as \"the Red Baron\", because of his red Ferrari and in reference to the German [[Manfred von Richthofen]], the famous [[flying ace]] of World War I. Schumacher's nicknames include \"Schumi\",<ref>{{cite news\n |title=Alonso ahead of Schumi\n |publisher=News24\n |date=21 October 2006\n |url=http://www.news24.com/News24/Sport/More_Sport/0,9294,2-9-32_2018131,00.html\n |accessdate=22 October 2006\n |archivedate=30 September 2007\n |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20070930205306/http://www.news24.com/News24/Sport/More_Sport/0%2C9294%2C2-9-32_2018131%2C00.html\n |url-status=dead\n |df=\n}}</ref>\n\"Schuey\"<ref>{{cite news\n | first       = David\n | last       = Tremayne\n | title       = Schuey exit promises many twists and turns\n | work       = The Independent\n | location       = UK\n | date       = 22 October 2006\n | url       = http://sport.independent.co.uk/motor_racing/article1919061.ece\n | accessdate       = 22 October 2006\n | url-status       = dead\n | archiveurl       = https://web.archive.org/web/20070930182154/http://sport.independent.co.uk/motor_racing/article1919061.ece\n | archivedate       = 30 September 2007\n | df       = dmy-all\n }}</ref>\nand \"Schu\".<ref>{{cite news\n | title      = Schu brought down to earth\n | publisher      = ITV\n | date      = 11 October 2006\n | url      = http://www.itv-f1.com/News_Article.aspx?PO_ID=37706&PO=37706\n | accessdate      = 14 October 2006\n | url-status      = dead\n | archiveurl      = https://web.archive.org/web/20070929092158/http://www.itv-f1.com/News_Article.aspx?PO_ID=37706&PO=37706\n | archivedate      = 29 September 2007\n | df      = dmy-all\n }}</ref>\nSchumacher is often credited with popularising Formula One in Germany, where it was formerly considered a fringe sport.<ref name=\"superwheels\">{{cite web |author=Sapa |title=The greatest driver of all time! |publisher=SuperWheels |date=11 September 2006 |url=http://www.superwheels.co.za/default.asp?id=4846&des=sportstalk |accessdate=24 October 2006 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20060927153411/http://www.superwheels.co.za/default.asp?id=4846&des=sportstalk |archivedate=27 September 2006 |url-status=dead  }}</ref> When Schumacher retired in 2006, three of the top ten drivers were German, more than any other nationality and more than have ever been present in Formula One history. Younger German drivers, such as [[Sebastian Vettel]], felt Schumacher was key in their becoming Formula One drivers.<ref>{{cite news\n | first      = Jonathan\n | last       = Noble\n | title      = Vettel sorry to see 'idol' Schumacher go\n | work       = Autosport\n | date       = 25 September 2006\n | url        = http://www.autosport.com/news/report.php/id/54667\n | accessdate = 31 October 2006\n}}</ref> In the latter part of his Formula One career, and as one of the senior drivers, Schumacher was the president of the [[Grand Prix Drivers' Association]].<ref>{{cite news\n | title      = Schumacher retains GPDA position\n | publisher  = BBC\n | url        = http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport2/hi/motorsport/formula_one/5066186.stm\n | accessdate = 30 November 2007\n | date       = 9 June 2006\n}}</ref> In a 2006 [[F\u00e9d\u00e9ration Internationale de l'Automobile|FIA]] survey, Michael Schumacher was voted the most popular driver of the season among Formula One fans.<ref>{{cite news |title=Schumacher tops F1 supporter poll |work=BBC Sport |date=27 September 2006 |url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/motorsport/formula_one/5384692.stm |accessdate=25 October 2006}}</ref>\n\n=== Jordan (1991) ===\n[[File:Jordan 191 rain.png|thumb|Schumacher testing the [[Jordan 191]]]]\nSchumacher made his Formula One debut with the [[Jordan Grand Prix|Jordan]]-[[Ford Motor Company|Ford]] team at the [[1991 Belgian Grand Prix]], driving car number 32 as a replacement for the imprisoned [[Bertrand Gachot]]. Schumacher, still a contracted Mercedes driver, was signed by [[Eddie Jordan]] after Mercedes paid Jordan $150,000 for his debut.<ref>{{cite book\n | last      = Collings\n | first     = Timothy\n | title     = The Piranha Club\n | publisher = Virgin Books\n | year      = 2004\n | page      = 17\n | isbn      = 978-0-7535-0965-4\n}}</ref><!--\n-->\n\n==== Belgian Grand Prix debut ====\nThe week before the race, Schumacher impressed Jordan designer [[Gary Anderson (F1 designer)|Gary Anderson]] and team manager Trevor Foster during a test drive at [[Silverstone Circuit|Silverstone]]. His manager [[Willi Weber]] assured Jordan that Schumacher knew the challenging [[Circuit de Spa-Francorchamps|Spa]] track well, although in fact he had only seen it as a spectator. During the race weekend, teammate [[Andrea de Cesaris]] was meant to show Schumacher the circuit, but was held up with contract negotiations. Schumacher then learned the track on his own, by cycling around the track on a fold-up [[bicycle|bike]] he had brought with him.<ref>{{cite book\n | last       = Hilton\n | first      = Christopher\n | title      = Michael Schumacher: The whole story\n | publisher  = Haynes\n | year       = 2006\n | pages      = 62\u201366\n | isbn       = 978-1-84425-008-0\n}}</ref><!--\n--> He impressed the paddock by qualifying seventh in this race. This matched the team's season-best grid position, and out-qualified 11-year veteran de Cesaris. Motorsport journalist Joe Saward reported that after qualifying \"clumps of German journalists were talking about 'the best talent since [[Stefan Bellof]]{{' \"}}.<ref>{{cite book\n | last      = Hilton\n | first     = Christopher\n | title     = Michael Schumacher: The whole story\n | publisher = Haynes\n | year      = 2006\n | pages     = 67\u201368\n | isbn      = 978-1-84425-008-0\n}}</ref><!--\n--> Schumacher retired on the first lap of the race with [[clutch]] problems.<ref name=\"f1-1991 Belgian gp result\">{{cite web\n | title      = 1991 Belgian Grand Prix\n | work       = Results Archive\n | publisher  = Formula1.com\n | url        = http://www.formula1.com/results/season/1991/209/\n | accessdate = 24 October 2006\n}}</ref>\n<br /><!-- THESE BREAKS ARE SO THE HEADING DOES NOT GET JAMMED BY THE PRECEDING SECTION'S PHOTO!!! -->\n\n=== Benetton (1991\u20131995) ===\n[[File:Michael Schumacher 1992 Monaco.jpg|thumb|Schumacher driving for [[Benetton Formula|Benetton]] at the [[1992 Monaco Grand Prix]]]]\n\nFollowing his Belgian Grand Prix debut, and despite an [[wikt:agreement in principle|agreement in principle]] between Jordan and Schumacher's Mercedes management that would see the German race for the Irish team for the remainder of the season, Schumacher was engaged by [[Benetton Formula|Benetton]]-[[Ford Motor Company|Ford]] for the following race. Jordan applied for an injunction in the UK courts to prevent Schumacher driving for Benetton, but lost the case as they had not yet signed a final contract.<ref>{{cite book\n | last      = Collings\n | first     = Timothy\n | title     = The Piranha Club\n | publisher = Virgin Books\n | year      = 2007\n | chapter   = Welcome to the Piranha Club\n | isbn      = 978-1-85227-907-3\n}}</ref><!--\n-->\n\n==== 1991\u20131993 ====\nSchumacher finished the {{F1|1991}} season with four points out of six races. His best finish was fifth in his second race, the {{F1 GP|1991|Italian}}, in which he finished ahead of his teammate and three-time World Champion [[Nelson Piquet]].\n\nAt the start of the {{F1|1992}} season the [[Sauber]] team, planning their Formula One debut with Mercedes backing for the following year, invoked a clause in Schumacher's contract that stated that if Mercedes entered Formula One, Schumacher would drive for them. It was eventually agreed that Schumacher would stay with Benetton, [[Peter Sauber]] said that \"[Schumacher] didn't want to drive for us. Why would I have forced him?\".<ref>{{cite book\n | last      = Domenjoz\n | first     = Luc\n | title     = Michael Schumacher : Rise of a genius\n | origyear  = 2002\n | publisher = Parragon\n | page      = 38\n | isbn      = 978-0-7525-9228-2\n | year      = 2006\n}}</ref><!--\n--> The year was dominated by the Williams of [[Nigel Mansell]] and [[Riccardo Patrese]], featuring powerful Renault engines, [[Semi-automatic transmission|semi-automatic gearboxes]] and [[active suspension]] to control the car's ride height.<ref>{{cite book\n | editor-last  = Henry\n | editor-first = Alan\n | title        = Autocourse 1992\u201393\n | publisher    = Hazleton Publishing\n | year         = 1992\n | page         = 50\n | isbn         = 978-0-905138-96-1\n}}</ref><!--\n--> In the \"conventional\" Benetton B192 Schumacher took his place on the [[podium]] for the first time, finishing third in the {{F1 GP|1992|Mexican}}. He went on to take his first victory at the {{F1 GP|1992|Belgian}}, in a wet race at the [[Circuit de Spa-Francorchamps|Spa-Francorchamps]] circuit, which by 2003 he would call \"far and away my favourite track\".<ref>{{cite book | last = Kehm | first = Sabine | title =''Michael Schumacher. Driving Force'' | publisher=Random House |year=2003 | page = 14 | isbn = 978-0-09-189435-1 }}</ref> He finished third in the Drivers' Championship in 1992 with 53 points, three points behind runner-up Patrese.\n\nThe Williams of [[Damon Hill]] and [[Alain Prost]] also dominated the {{F1|1993}} season. Benetton introduced their own active suspension and traction control early in the season, last of the frontrunning teams to do so.<ref>{{cite web\n | url        = http://www.grandprix.com/gpe/rr538.html\n | title      = Grand Prix Results: Monaco GP, 1993\n | encyclopedia       = Grand Prix Encyclopedia\n | publisher  = GrandPrix.com\n | accessdate = 6 November 2006 }}. Benetton first raced traction control at the 1993 Monaco Grand Prix, having introduced active suspension at the 1993 European Grand Prix (Domenjoz (2002) p. 40). Williams had first raced an active system in 1987 and used it throughout 1992,(Autocourse (1992) p.50) while McLaren and Ferrari both introduced active cars in the final races of the 1992 season.(Autocourse (1992) pp.42 & 80)</ref><!--\n\n--> Schumacher won one race, the {{F1 GP|1993|Portuguese}} where he beat Prost, and had nine podium finishes, but retired in seven of the other 15 races. He finished the season in fourth, with 52 points.\n\n==== 1994\u20131995: World Championship years ====\n[[File:Benetton B 194 4841.JPG|thumb|Schumacher drove the [[Benetton B194]] to his first World Championship in 1994.]]\n[[File:Michael Schumacher 1995 Britain 2.jpg|thumb|Schumacher driving for Benetton at the [[1995 British Grand Prix]]]]\n\nThe {{F1|1994}} season was Schumacher's first [[List of Formula One World Drivers' Champions|Drivers' Championship]]. The season, however, was marred by the [[Death of Ayrton Senna|deaths]] of [[Ayrton Senna]] (witnessed by Schumacher, who was directly behind in 2nd position) and [[Roland Ratzenberger]] during the {{F1 GP|1994|San Marino}}, and by [[Allegations of cheating in the 1994 Formula One season|allegations that several teams]], but most particularly Schumacher's Benetton team, broke the sport's technical regulations.<ref name=genius-ms>{{cite book | title = Michael Schumacher: The Rise of a Genius | first = Luc | last = Domenjoz | isbn = 978-0-7525-9228-2 | publisher=[[Parragon]] | origyear = 2002 | pages = 44\u201347 | year = 2006}}</ref><ref name=saward>{{cite web | title = Globetrotter: Rocking the boat | url = http://www.grandprix.com/gt/gt00044.html | first = Joe | last = Saward | authorlink = Joe Saward | publisher=GrandPrix.com | date = 11 August 1994 | accessdate =28 August 2008}}</ref>\n\nSchumacher won six of the first seven races and was leading the {{F1 GP|1994|Spanish}}, before a gearbox failure left him stuck in fifth gear. Schumacher finished the race in second place.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.formula1.com/news/features/2003/4/288.html|title=A return to racing \u2013 Spanish Grand Prix 1994|date=30 April 2003|accessdate=26 May 2008|publisher=Formula1.com}}</ref> Following the San Marino Grand Prix, the Benetton, Ferrari and McLaren teams were investigated on suspicion of breaking the [[F\u00e9d\u00e9ration Internationale de l'Automobile|FIA]]-imposed ban on electronic aids. Benetton and McLaren initially refused to hand over their [[source code]] for investigation. When they did so, the FIA discovered hidden functionality in both teams' software, but no evidence that it had been used in a race. Both teams were fined $100,000 for their initial refusal to cooperate. However, the McLaren software, which was a gearbox program that allowed automatic shifts, was deemed legal. By contrast, the Benetton software was deemed to be a form of \"launch control\" that would have allowed Schumacher to make perfect starts, which was explicitly outlawed by the regulations. However, there was no evidence to suggest that this software was actually used.<ref>{{cite book\n | last      = Williams\n | first     = Richard\n | title     = The Death of Ayrton Senna\n | publisher = Bloomsbury\n | pages     = 177\u2013179\n | year      = 1999\n | isbn      = 978-0-7475-4495-1\n}}</ref>\n\nAt the {{F1 GP|1994|British}}, Schumacher was penalised for overtaking on the formation lap. He then ignored the penalty and the subsequent [[Racing flag#The black flag|black flag]], which indicates that the driver must immediately return to the pits, for which he was disqualified and later given a two-race ban. Benetton blamed the incident on a communication error between the stewards and the team.<ref>{{cite book\n | last      = Hilton\n | first     = Christopher\n | title     = Michael Schumacher: The whole story\n | publisher = Haynes\n | year      = 2006\n | pages     = 118\u2013120\n | isbn      = 978-1-84425-008-0\n}}</ref> Schumacher was also disqualified after winning the {{F1 GP|1994|Belgian}} after his car was found to have illegal wear on its [[Formula One car#Ground effect|skidblock]], a measure used after the accidents at Imola to limit [[downforce]] and hence cornering speed.<ref name=\"f1-1994 Belgian gp result\">{{cite web\n | url        = http://www.grandprix.com/gpe/rr559.html\n | title      = Grand Prix Results: Belgian GP, 1994\n | encyclopedia       = Grand Prix Encyclopedia\n | publisher  = GrandPrix.com\n | accessdate = 13 May 2006\n}}</ref><!--\n--> Benetton protested that the skidblock had been damaged when Schumacher spun over a kerb, but the FIA rejected their appeal because of the pattern of wear and damage visible on the block.<ref>{{cite book\n | last      = Hilton\n | first     = Christopher\n | title     = Michael Schumacher: The whole story\n | publisher = Haynes\n | year      = 2006\n | page      = 142\n | isbn      = 978-1-84425-008-0\n}}</ref>\n\nThese incidents helped Damon Hill close the points gap, and Schumacher led by a single point going into the final race in [[1994 Australian Grand Prix|Australia]]. On lap 36 Schumacher hit the guardrail on the outside of the track while leading. Hill attempted to pass, but as Schumacher's car returned to the track there was a collision on the corner causing them both to retire.<ref>{{cite news\n | last       = Benson\n | first      = Andrew\n | url        = http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/low/motorsport/formula_one/5024532.stm\n | title      = Schumacher's chequered history\n | work  = BBC Sport\n | date       = 28 May 2006\n | accessdate = 15 June 2007}}</ref> As a result, Schumacher won a very controversial championship, the first German to do so ([[Jochen Rindt]] raced under the Austrian flag). At the FIA conference after the race, the new World Champion dedicated his title to Ayrton Senna.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.todayinhistory.de/index.php?what=thmanu&manu_id=1644&tag=13&monat=11&year=2013&dayisset=1&lang=en |title=Today in History \u2013 DW.COM |publisher=Todayinhistory.de |date=13 November 1994 |accessdate=26 November 2015}}</ref>\n\nIn {{F1|1995}} Schumacher successfully defended his title with Benetton. He now had the same Renault engine as Williams. He accumulated 33 more points than second-placed Damon Hill. With teammate [[Johnny Herbert]], he took Benetton to its first [[List of Formula One World Constructors' Champions|Constructors' Championship]] and became the youngest two-time World Champion in Formula One history.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.foxsports.com/motor/gallery/the-1995-f1-season-images-030515|title=Throwback: The 1995 Formula One season in photos|work=FOX Sports|access-date=22 March 2018|language=en-US}}</ref>\n\nThe season was marred by several collisions with Hill, in particular an overtaking manoeuvre by Hill took them both out of the {{F1 GP|1995|British}} on lap 45, and again on lap 23 of the [[1995 Italian Grand Prix|Italian Grand Prix]]. Schumacher won nine of the 17 races, and finished on the podium 11 times. Only once did he qualify worse than fourth; at the {{F1 GP|1995|Belgian}}, he qualified 16th, but nevertheless went on to win the race.\n\n=== Ferrari (1996\u20132006) ===\nIn {{F1|1996}}, Schumacher joined [[Scuderia Ferrari|Ferrari]], a team that had last won the Drivers' Championship in {{F1|1979}} and the Constructors' Championship in {{F1|1983}}, for a salary of $60&nbsp;million over 2 years. He left Benetton a year before his contract with them expired; he later cited the team's damaging actions in 1994 as his reason for opting out of his deal.<ref>{{cite magazine |last=Cooper |first=Steve |date=August 2007 |title=McLaren dream team turns into nightmare |magazine=Autosport |volume=189 |issue=6 |pages=6\u20138 }}</ref> A year later Benetton employees [[Rory Byrne]] (designer) and [[Ross Brawn]] (Technical Director) joined Ferrari.<ref>{{cite web | title = Ross Brawn Profile | publisher=theScuderia.net | url = http://www.thescuderia.net/rossbrawn.shtml | first = Matthew | last = Bewers | accessdate=3 January 2008}}</ref>\n\nFerrari had previously come close to the championship in 1982 and 1990. The team had suffered a disastrous downturn in the early 1990s, partially as its famous V12 engine was no longer competitive against the smaller, lighter and more fuel efficient V10s of its competitors. Various drivers, notably Alain Prost, had given the vehicles labels such as \"truck\", \"pig\", and \"accident waiting to happen\".<ref>{{cite news | title = Switch the key to Ferrari revival | publisher=Telegraph Sport |date=20 October 2006 | url = https://www.telegraph.co.uk/core/Content/displayPrintable.jhtml?xml=/sport/2006/10/20/smbake20.xml&site=2&page=0 |first = Andrew |last = Baker |accessdate =29 October 2006 | location=London}}</ref> Furthermore, the poor performance of the Ferrari pit crews was considered a running joke.<ref name=\"superwheels\" /> At the end of 1995, though the team had improved into a solid competitor, it was still considered inferior to front-running teams such as Benetton and Williams.<ref>{{cite book| last =Henry| first =Alan (ed.)| authorlink =Alan Henry| title =Autocourse 1996\u201397| publisher=Hazleton Publishing| year =1996| pages =46\u201348| isbn = 978-1-874557-91-3| title-link =Autocourse}}</ref> Schumacher declared the [[Ferrari 412 T2|Ferrari 412T]] good enough to win the Championship.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://jalopnik.com/remember-michael-schumachers-incredible-first-win-for-f-1677242856|title=Remember Michael Schumacher's Incredible First Win For Ferrari?|last=George|first=Patrick|work=Jalopnik|access-date=22 March 2018|language=en-US}}</ref>\n\nSchumacher, [[Ross Brawn]], [[Rory Byrne]], and [[Jean Todt]] (hired in 1993), have been credited as turning this once struggling team into the most successful team in Formula One history.<ref>{{cite web | title = Schumacher confirms retirement | publisher = MSN Cars | date = 11 September 2006 | url = http://crashnet.cars.msn.co.uk/news_view.asp?cid=1&id=137166 | archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20070928081027/http://crashnet.cars.msn.co.uk/news_view.asp?cid=1&id=137166 | url-status=dead | archive-date = 28 September 2007 | accessdate = 28 September 2006 }}</ref><ref>{{cite web | title = Ferrari: Formula 1's Most Successful Team Enters a New Era | publisher = about.com | url = http://formula1.about.com/od/teams/p/Ferrari.htm | accessdate = 12 June 2007 | archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20070712202105/http://formula1.about.com/od/teams/p/Ferrari.htm | archive-date = 12 July 2007 | url-status = dead }}</ref> Three-time World Champion [[Jackie Stewart]] believes the transformation of the Ferrari team was Schumacher's greatest feat.<ref name=\"stewart\">{{cite news | title = Schumacher 'made Ferrari great' |first = Andrew |last = Benson |work=BBC Sport |date=18 October 2006 | url = http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport2/low/motorsport/formula_one/6061442.stm | accessdate =6 November 2006}}</ref> [[Eddie Irvine]] also joined the team, moving from [[Jordan Grand Prix|Jordan]].<ref>{{cite web|title=Irvine to Ferrari!|url=http://grandprix.com/ns/ns00304.html|publisher=GrandPrix.com|date=2 October 1995|accessdate=15 May 2016}}</ref> During winter testing, Schumacher first drove a Ferrari, their 1995 [[Ferrari 412 T2]], and was two seconds faster than former regulars [[Jean Alesi]] and [[Gerhard Berger]] had been.<ref name=\"bbcspain96\">{{cite news|last1=Benson|first1=Andrew|title=Spanish Grand Prix: Why Michael Schumacher's epic 1996 win matters|url=https://www.bbc.com/sport/formula1/36277172|publisher=BBC|accessdate=15 May 2016|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160515190033/http://www.bbc.com/sport/formula1/36277172 |archivedate=15 May 2016|date=14 May 2016|work=BBC Sport}}</ref>\n\n==== 1996\u20131999 ====\n{{quote box|quote=\"It was not a race. It was a demonstration of brilliance.\"|source=[[Stirling Moss]] about Schumacher at the [[1996 Spanish Grand Prix|1996 Spanish GP]]<ref>{{cite news\n | title      = The Best of the Best\n | work       = Autosport\n | year       = 1999\n | url        = http://atlasf1.autosport.com/99/bra/preview/kalb.html\n | accessdate = 5 October 2006\n}}</ref>|width=23%|align=right}}\nSchumacher finished third in the Drivers' Championship in 1996 and helped Ferrari to second place in the Constructors' Championship ahead of his old team Benetton. He won three races, more than the team's total tally for the period from 1991 to 1995. Early in the 1996 season the car had reliability trouble and Schumacher did not finish six of the 16 races. He took his first win for Ferrari at the [[1996 Spanish Grand Prix|Spanish Grand Prix]], where he lapped the entire field up to third place in the wet.<ref name=\"early years\" /> Having taken the lead on lap 19, he consistently lapped five seconds faster than the rest of the field in the difficult conditions.<ref name=bbcspain96 /> In the {{F1 GP|1996|French}} Schumacher qualified in [[pole position]], but suffered engine failure on the race's formation lap.<ref name=\"96frenchgp\">{{cite news | title = Grand Prix Results: French GP, 1996 | publisher=grandprix.com | url = http://www.grandprix.com/gpe/rr590.html |first = Magny |last = Cours | accessdate =18 April 2007}}</ref> However, at [[1996 Belgian Grand Prix|Spa-Francorchamps]], Schumacher used well-timed pit-stops to fend off Williams's [[Jacques Villeneuve]]. Following that, at [[1996 Italian Grand Prix|Monza]], Schumacher won in front of the [[tifosi#Formula 1|tifosi]].\n\n[[File:Michael Schumacher 1997.jpg|thumb|Schumacher celebrates a second-place finish at the [[1997 German Grand Prix]]]]\n[[File:Schumacher and Coulthard in the 1998 British Grand Prix.jpg|thumb|Schumacher battles with [[David Coulthard]] at the [[1998 British Grand Prix]]]]\n\nMichael Schumacher and [[Jacques Villeneuve]] vied for the title in {{F1|1997}}. Villeneuve, driving the superior [[Williams FW19]], led the championship in the early part of the season.<ref>{{cite web| url = http://www.grandprix.com/race/r713fqreport.html| title = Friday Press Conference| accessdate = 8 November 2006| date = 10 October 2003| publisher = GrandPrix.com| archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20070929121002/http://www.grandprix.com/race/r713fqreport.html| archive-date = 29 September 2007| url-status=dead| df = dmy-all}}</ref> However, by mid-season, Schumacher had taken the championship lead, winning five races, and entered the season's [[1997 European Grand Prix|final Grand Prix]] with a one-point advantage. Towards the end of the race, held at [[Circuito de Jerez|Jerez]], Schumacher's Ferrari developed a coolant leak and loss of performance indicating he may not finish the race.<ref>{{cite web|url= http://www.emercedesbenz.com/autos/mercedes-benz/motorsports/michael-schumacher-seven-time-world-champion/|title=MICHAEL SCHUMACHER: SEVEN TIME WORLD CHAMPION|publisher= eMercedesBenz|date= 25 November 2012|accessdate=18 January 2014}}</ref> As Villeneuve approached to pass his rival, Schumacher attempted to provoke an accident, but got the short end of the stick, retiring from the race. Villeneuve went on and scored four points to take the championship. Schumacher was punished for unsportsmanlike conduct for the collision and was disqualified from the Drivers' Championship.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/europe/29895.stm|work=BBC News |title=Schumacher loses championship runner-up crown|date=11 November 1997|accessdate=5 July 2010}}</ref><ref name=\"fia97verdict\">{{cite news\n |title=FIA World Motor Sport Council \u2013 11&nbsp;November 1997\n |publisher=FIA\n |date=11 November 1997\n |url=http://www.fia.com/resources/documents/2064282370__11_11_1997_WMSC.pdf\n |accessdate=29 October 2006\n\n|url-status=dead\n |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20061102031434/http://www.fia.com/resources/documents/2064282370__11_11_1997_WMSC.pdf\n |archivedate=2 November 2006\n |df=\n}}</ref>\n\nIn {{F1|1998}}, Finnish driver [[Mika H\u00e4kkinen]] became Schumacher's main title competition. H\u00e4kkinen won the first two races of the season, gaining a 16-point advantage over Schumacher. Schumacher then won in Argentina and, with the Ferrari improving significantly in the second half of the season, Schumacher took six victories and had five other podium finishes. Ferrari took a 1\u20132 finish at the {{F1 GP|1998|French}}, the first Ferrari 1\u20132 finish since 1990, and the {{F1 GP|1998|Italian}}, which tied Schumacher with H\u00e4kkinen for the lead of the Drivers' Championship with 80 points, but H\u00e4kkinen won the Championship by winning the final two races. There were two controversies; at the {{F1 GP|1998|British}} Schumacher was leading on the last lap when he turned into the pit lane, crossed the start finish line and stopped for a ten-second stop go penalty. There was some doubt whether this counted as serving the penalty, but, because he had crossed the finish line when he came into the pit lane, the win was valid. At [[1998 Belgian Grand Prix#Schumacher collision with Coulthard|Spa]], Schumacher was leading the race by 40 seconds in heavy spray, but collided with [[David Coulthard]]'s McLaren when the Scot, a lap down, slowed in very poor visibility to let Schumacher past. After both cars returned to the pits, Schumacher leaped out of his car and headed to McLaren's garage in an infuriated manner and accused Coulthard of trying to kill him.<ref name=\"spa98\" /> Coulthard admitted five years later that the accident had been his mistake.<ref name=\"spa98\">{{cite news | title = Crash was my fault, Coulthard admits |agency=Reuters |date=7 June 2003 | url = http://www.smh.com.au/articles/2003/07/06/1057430084085.html | accessdate =28 September 2006 | work=Sydney Morning Herald}}</ref>\n\nSchumacher's efforts helped Ferrari win the Constructors' title in {{F1|1999}}. He lost his chance to win the Drivers' Championship at the {{F1 GP|1999|British}} at the high-speed ''Stowe Corner'', his car's rear brake failed, sending him off the track and resulting in a broken leg.<ref name=\"broken leg\">{{cite news |title = Schumacher out of action |url = http://www.grandprix.com/ns/ns02071.html |publisher=GrandPrix.com |date=12 July 1999 |accessdate =25 October 2006}}</ref> During his 98-day absence, he was replaced by Finnish driver [[Mika Salo]]. After missing six races he made his return at the inaugural {{F1 GP|1999|Malaysian}}, qualifying in pole position by almost a second. He then assumed the role of second driver, assisting teammate [[Eddie Irvine]]'s bid to win the Drivers' Championship for Ferrari.<ref>{{cite web\n | title      = Drivers: Michael Schumacher\n | publisher  = grandprix.com\n | url        = http://www.grandprix.com/gpe/drv-schmic.html\n | accessdate = 30 November 2006\n}}</ref> In the last race of the season, the {{F1 GP|1999|Japanese}}, H\u00e4kkinen won his second consecutive title. Schumacher would later say that H\u00e4kkinen was the opponent he respected the most.<ref name=\"hakkinen hof\">{{cite web | title = Hall of Fame \u2013 World Champions: Mika Hakkinen |first=Gerald |last=Donaldson |publisher=Formula1.com |url=https://www.formula1.com/en/championship/drivers/hall-of-fame/Mika_Hakkinen.html |accessdate=28 May 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180209184447/https://www.formula1.com/en/championship/drivers/hall-of-fame/Mika_Hakkinen.html |archive-date=9 February 2018}}</ref>\n\n==== 2000\u20132004: World Championship years ====\n[[File:Michael Schumacher 2001 Canada.jpg|thumb|Schumacher won his fourth World title in {{F1|2001}}.]]\n[[File:Mschumacher 2002.jpg|thumb|Schumacher driving the [[Scuderia Ferrari]] [[Marlboro (cigarette)|Marlboro]] [[Ferrari F2002|F2002]] at the [[2002 French Grand Prix]], the race at which he clinched the {{F1|2002}} Drivers' Championship, setting the record for the fewest races in locking up the title]]\n\nDuring this period Schumacher won more races and championships than any other driver in the history<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.carophile.org/greatest-race-car-drivers-of-all-time/10/|title=10 Greatest Race Car Drivers of All Time|date=7 May 2015|work=carophile.org|accessdate=9 April 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170409021343/http://www.carophile.org/greatest-race-car-drivers-of-all-time/10/|archive-date=9 April 2017|url-status=dead}}</ref> of the sport. Schumacher won his third World Championship in {{F1|2000}} after a year-long battle with H\u00e4kkinen. Schumacher won the first three races of the season and five of the first eight. Midway through the year, Schumacher's chances suffered with three consecutive non-finishes, <!-- *otheus: trivia, but interesting >>>> including being hit from behind at the first corner in [[2000 Austrian Grand Prix|Austria]] and [[2000 German Grand Prix|Germany]], --> allowing H\u00e4kkinen to close the gap in the standings. H\u00e4kkinen then took another two victories, before Schumacher won at the {{F1 GP|2000|Italian}}. At the post race press conference, after equalling the number of wins (41) won by his idol, [[Ayrton Senna]], Schumacher broke into tears.<ref>{{cite news |url= http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/motorsport/formula_one/3605579.stm|title= A death that shocked the world|date=21 April 2004|accessdate=21 April 2007|publisher=BBC |first = Andrew |last = Benson }}</ref> The championship fight would come down to the penultimate race of the season, the {{F1 GP|2000|Japanese}}. Starting from pole position, Schumacher lost the lead to H\u00e4kkinen at the start. After his second pit-stop, however, Schumacher came out ahead of H\u00e4kkinen and went on to win the race and the championship.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.bbc.com/sport/formula1/25549884|title=Michael Schumacher's best races \u2013 Japanese Grand Prix 2000|date=30 December 2013|work=BBC Sport|access-date=22 March 2018|language=en-GB}}</ref>\n\nIn {{F1|2001}}, Schumacher took his fourth drivers' title. Four other drivers won races, but none sustained a season-long challenge for the championship. Schumacher scored a record-tying nine wins and clinched the World Championship with four races yet to run. He finished the championship with 123 points, 58 ahead of runner-up Coulthard. Season highlights included the {{F1 GP|2001|Canadian}}, where Schumacher finished 2nd to his brother Ralf, thus scoring the first ever 1\u20132 finish by brothers in Formula One;<ref>{{cite web |url= http://www.globetrotter.net/gt/grandprix/en/statistiques.asp\n|title= Grand Prix du Canada \u2013 Statistiques |publisher=Telus |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20070927002728/http://www.globetrotter.net/gt/grandprix/en/statistiques.asp |archive-date=27 September 2007 |accessdate=15 June 2007}}</ref> and the [[2001 Belgian Grand Prix|Belgian Grand Prix]] in which Schumacher scored his 52nd career win, breaking Alain Prost's record for most career wins.<ref>{{cite news |url= http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/low/sports_talk/1520663.stm\n|title= Send your tributes to Schumacher|accessdate=3 February 2007|publisher=BBC | date=2 September 2001}}</ref>\n\nIn {{F1|2002}}, Schumacher used the [[Ferrari F2002]]<!--, widely considered to be one of the most dominant racing cars in Formula One,--> to retain his Drivers' Championship.<!-- No source to back up claim, hiding -->\nThere was again some controversy, however, at the {{F1 GP|2002|Austrian}}, where his teammate, [[Rubens Barrichello]] was leading, but in the final metres of the race, under [[team orders]], slowed down to allow Schumacher to win the race.<ref name=\"bbcaustria\" /> The crowd broke into outraged boos at the result and Schumacher tried to make amends by allowing Barrichello to stand on the top step of the podium. At the {{F1 GP|2002|United States}} later that year, Schumacher dominated the race and was set for a close finish with Barrichello. At the end he slowed down to create a formation finish with Barrichello, but slowed too much allowing Barrichello to take the victory.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/sport/motorsport/formulaone/3027644/Formula-One-Ferrari-team-mate-hands-Schumacher-controversial-victory.html|title=Formula One: Ferrari team-mate hands Schumacher controversial victory|journal=Daily Telegraph|date=12 May 2002|access-date=22 March 2018|language=en-GB|issn=0307-1235}}</ref> In winning the Drivers' Championship he equalled the record set by [[Juan Manuel Fangio]] of five World Championships. Ferrari won 15 out of 17 races, and Schumacher won the title with six races remaining in the season, which is still the earliest point in the season for a driver to be crowned World Champion.<ref>{{cite news|title=Top 10 Michael Schumacher moments|url=http://www.cbc.ca/sports/indepth/10-schumacher-momments.html|work=[[CBC Sports]]|publisher=[[Canadian Broadcasting Corporation]]|first=John C.|last=Molinaro|date=12 September 2006|accessdate=6 January 2012}}</ref> Schumacher broke his own record, shared with [[Nigel Mansell]], of nine race wins in a season, by winning eleven times and finishing every race on the podium. He finished with 144 points, a record-breaking 67 points ahead of the runner-up, his teammate [[Rubens Barrichello]]. This pair finished nine of the 17 races in the first two places.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.motorsportmagazine.com/database/championships/f1/2002-f1-world-championship|title=2002 F1 World Championship|date=3 July 2017|work=Motor Sport Magazine|access-date=22 March 2018|language=en}}</ref>\n\n[[File:Michael Schumacher Ferrari 2004.jpg|thumb|Schumacher at [[Indianapolis Motor Speedway|Indianapolis]] in 2004, where he won the [[2004 United States Grand Prix]]]]\n\nSchumacher broke Juan Manuel Fangio's record of five World Drivers' Championships by winning the drivers' title for the sixth time in {{F1|2003}}, a closely contested season. The biggest competition came once again from the [[McLaren]] Mercedes and [[WilliamsF1|Williams BMW]] teams. In the first race, Schumacher ran off track, and in the following two, was involved in collisions.<ref>{{cite news | title = Coulthard takes Melbourne thriller |work=BBC Sport |date=9 March 2003 | url = http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport2/hi/motorsport/formula_one/2832441.stm | accessdate =3 November 2006}}</ref><ref>{{cite news | title = Raikkonen claims maiden win |work=BBC Sport |date=23 March 2003 | url = http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport2/hi/motorsport/formula_one/2877461.stm | accessdate =3 November 2006}}</ref><ref>{{cite news | title = Raikkonen wins chaotic race |work=BBC Sport |date=6 April 2003 | url = http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport2/hi/motorsport/formula_one/2922651.stm | accessdate =3 November 2006}}</ref> He fell 16 points behind [[Kimi R\u00e4ikk\u00f6nen]]. Schumacher won the {{F1 GP|2003|San Marino}} and the next two races, and closed within two points of R\u00e4ikk\u00f6nen. Aside from Schumacher's victory in [[2003 Canadian Grand Prix|Canada]], and Barrichello's victory in [[2003 British Grand Prix|Britain]], the mid-season was dominated by Williams drivers [[Ralf Schumacher]] and [[Juan Pablo Montoya]], who each claimed two victories. After the {{F1 GP|2003|Hungarian}}, Michael Schumacher led Montoya and Kimi R\u00e4ikk\u00f6nen by only one and two points, respectively. Ahead of the next race, the FIA announced changes to the way tyre widths were to be measured: this forced [[Michelin]], supplier to Williams and McLaren among others, to rapidly redesign their tyres before the {{F1 GP|2003|Italian}}.<ref>{{cite news | title =FIA stands by tyre rulings |work=BBC Sport |date=9 September 2006 | url = http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/motorsport/formula_one/3092598.stm | accessdate =25 April 2007}}</ref> Schumacher, running on [[Bridgestone]] tyres, won the next two races.<!-- *otheus* were they decisive? Or extremely closely contested? cannot be both! 4u1e \u2013 actually they can. Close in terms of the race, decisive in terms of the championship! :) --> After Montoya was penalised in the {{F1 GP|2003|United States}}, only Schumacher and R\u00e4ikk\u00f6nen remained in contention for the title. At the final round, the {{F1 GP|2003|Japanese}}, Schumacher needed only one point whilst R\u00e4ikk\u00f6nen needed to win. By finishing the race in eighth place, Schumacher took one point and assured his sixth World Drivers' title, ending the season two points ahead of R\u00e4ikk\u00f6nen.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.motorsportmagazine.com/database/championships/f1/2003-f1-world-championship|title=2003 F1 World Championship|date=3 July 2017|work=Motor Sport Magazine|access-date=22 March 2018|language=en}}</ref>\n\nIn {{F1|2004}}, Schumacher won a record twelve of the first thirteen races of the season, only failing to finish in Monaco after an accident with Juan Pablo Montoya during a [[safety car]] period when he briefly locked his car's brakes. He clinched a record [[List of Formula One World Drivers' Champions|seventh drivers' title]] at the {{F1 GP|2004|Belgian}}. He finished that season with a record 148 points, 34 points ahead of the runner-up, teammate Rubens Barrichello, and set a new record of 13 race wins out of a possible 18, surpassing his previous best of 11 wins from the {{f1|2002}} season.<ref>{{cite web | title = A tribute to Michael Schumacher | publisher  = f1technical.net | year = 2006 | url = http://www.f1technical.net/news/3949 | accessdate = 1 December 2007}}</ref>\n\n==== 2005\u20132006 ====\n[[File:Lap4 Canada2005 McLaren and Ferrari.jpg|thumb|Schumacher battling with [[Kimi R\u00e4ikk\u00f6nen]] during the [[2005 Canadian Grand Prix]]]]\nRule changes for the 2005 season required tyres to last an entire race,<ref name=rulechanges>{{cite news | url= http://www.formula1.com/news/headlines/2004/10/2367.html | title = FIA announce rule changes for 2005 and 2006 | work=Formula1.com |date=22 October 2004 | accessdate=13 April 2007 }}</ref> tipping the overall advantage to teams using Michelins over teams such as Ferrari that relied on Bridgestone tyres.<ref>{{cite news |title = Michael Schumacher |url = http://www.f1complete.com/content/view/376/273/ |publisher = f1complete.com |accessdate = 30 November 2007 |url-status=dead |archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20071012141942/http://f1complete.com/content/view/376/273/ |archivedate = 12 October 2007 |df = dmy-all }}</ref> The rule changes were partly in an effort to dent Ferrari's dominance and make the series more interesting.<ref name=\"superwheels\" /> The most notable moment of the early season for Schumacher was his battle with [[Fernando Alonso]] in [[2005 San Marino Grand Prix|San Marino]], where he started 13th and finished only 0.2 seconds behind the Spanish driver.<ref>{{cite news | title = Alonso holds off Schumacher surge |work=BBC Sport |date=24 April 2005 | url = http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport2/hi/motorsport/formula_one/4478747.stm | accessdate =3 November 2006}}</ref> Less than halfway through the season, Schumacher said \"I don't think I can count myself in this battle any more. It was like trying to fight with a blunted weapon.... If your weapons are weak you don't have a chance.\"<ref>{{cite news | title = Alonso within touching distance of title |work=The Guardian |date=27 July 2005 | url = http://sport.guardian.co.uk/formulaone/story/0,10069,1535586,00.html |first = Alan |last = Henry| accessdate =5 November 2006 | location=London}}</ref> Schumacher's sole win in 2005 came at the {{F1 GP|2005|United States}}. Before that race, the Michelin tyres were found to have significant safety issues. When no compromise between the teams and the FIA could be reached, all but the six drivers using Bridgestone tyres dropped out of the race after the formation lap.<ref>{{cite news |title = Schumacher takes hollow USGP victory |url = http://www.crash.net/news_view.asp?cid=1&id=113296 |publisher = Crash.net |date = 19 June 2005 |accessdate = 19 June 2007 |url-status=dead |archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20080630003918/http://www.crash.net/news_view.asp?cid=1&id=113296 |archivedate = 30 June 2008 |df = dmy-all }}</ref> Schumacher retired in six of the 19 races. He finished the season in third with 62 points, fewer than half the points of World Champion Alonso.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.motorsportmagazine.com/database/championships/f1/2005-f1-world-championship|title=2005 F1 World Championship|date=3 July 2017|work=Motor Sport Magazine|access-date=22 March 2018|language=en}}</ref>\n\n{{F1|2006}} became the last season of Schumacher's Ferrari career. After three races, Schumacher had just 11 points and was already 17 points behind Alonso. He won the following two races. His pole position at [[2006 San Marino Grand Prix|San Marino]] was his 66th, breaking Ayrton Senna's 12-year-old record.<ref>{{cite news | title =Unbeatable Schumi sets new pole record | publisher= GPUpdate.net | date= 22 April 2006 | url= http://www.gpupdate.net/en/f1-news/115825/unbeatable-schumi-sets-new-pole-record/}}</ref>\n\nSchumacher was stripped of pole position at the {{F1 GP|2006|Monaco}} and started the race at the back of the grid. This was due to his stopping his car and blocking part of the circuit while Alonso was on his qualifying lap; he still managed to work his way up to 5th place on the notoriously cramped Monaco circuit.\nBy the {{F1 GP|2006|Canadian}}, the ninth race of the season, Schumacher was 25 points behind Alonso, but he then won the following three races to reduce his disadvantage to 11. After his victories in [[2006 Italian Grand Prix|Italy]] (in which Alonso had an engine failure)<ref>{{cite news | title = Alonso's Renault Engine blew in spectacular fashion | publisher = Motorsport.com | date = 10 September 2006 | url = http://www.motorsport.com/news/article.asp?ID=232358 | accessdate = 1 August 2007 | url-status=dead | archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20070930024154/http://www.motorsport.com/news/article.asp?ID=232358 | archivedate = 30 September 2007 | df = dmy-all }}</ref> and [[2006 Chinese Grand Prix|China]], in which Alonso had tyre problems,<ref name=\":0\">{{cite news | title = Alonso has trouble with his front tires |work=The Washington Post |date=1 October 2006 | url = https://www.washingtonpost.com/wp-dyn/content/article/2006/10/01/AR2006100100207_2.html | accessdate =1 August 2007 | first=Salvatore | last=Zanca}}</ref> Schumacher led in the championship standings for the first time during the season. Although he and Alonso had the same point total, Schumacher was in front because he had won more races.<ref name=\":0\" />\n[[File:Michael Schumacher 2006 Brazil last overtaking cropped.jpg|thumb|Schumacher overtakes [[Kimi R\u00e4ikk\u00f6nen]] for 4th with three laps to go of [[2006 Brazilian Grand Prix|his final race for three years]] at [[Aut\u00f3dromo Jos\u00e9 Carlos Pace|Interlagos]], having dropped to 19th early on]]\nThe Japanese Grand Prix was led by Schumacher with only 16 laps to go, when, for the first time since the [[2000 French Grand Prix]], Schumacher's car suffered an engine failure. Alonso won the race, giving himself a ten-point championship lead. With only one race left in the season, Schumacher could only win the championship if he won the season finale and Alonso scored no points.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/sport/2006/oct/09/formulaone.sport|title=Formula One: Engine failure ruins Schumacher's dream|last=Henry|first=Alan|date=9 October 2006|newspaper=the Guardian|language=en|access-date=22 March 2018}}</ref>\n\nBefore the {{F1 GP|2006|Brazilian}}, Schumacher conceded the title to Alonso.<ref>{{cite news | title = Schumacher concedes title to Alonso |work=BBC Sport |date=8 October 2006 }}</ref> In pre-race ceremonies, [[association football|football]] legend [[Pel\u00e9]] presented a trophy<ref>{{cite news | title =Pele to present a trophy to Schumacher | work=International Herald Tribune |date=22 October 2006 | url = http://www.iht.com/articles/ap/2006/10/20/sports/LA_SPT_CAR_F1_Brazilian_GP_Notebook.php | accessdate =1 August 2007}}</ref> to Schumacher for his years of dedication to Formula One.<ref>{{cite news | title = Schumacher honored by a presentation from Pele | work=International Herald Tribune |date=22 October 2006 | url = http://www.iht.com/articles/ap/2006/10/22/sports/LA_SPT_CAR_F1_Schumachers_Finale.php | accessdate =1 August 2007}}</ref> During the race's qualifying session, Schumacher had one of the quickest times during the first session and was fastest in the second session; but a fuel pressure problem prevented him from completing a single lap during the third session, forcing him to start the race in tenth position.<ref>{{cite news | title = Schumacher suffers in qualifying |work=BBC Sport |date=21 October 2006 | url = http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport2/hi/motorsport/formula_one/6073264.stm | accessdate =1 August 2007}}</ref> Early in the race Schumacher moved up to sixth place. However, in overtaking Alonso's teammate, [[Giancarlo Fisichella]], Schumacher experienced a tyre puncture caused by the front wing of Fisichella's car.<ref>{{cite news | title = Fisi did cause Schu puncture | publisher = itv.com/f1 | date = 23 October 2006 | url = http://www.itv-f1.com/News_Article.aspx?PO_ID=37856 | accessdate = 23 October 2006 | url-status=dead | archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20070929115409/http://www.itv-f1.com/News_Article.aspx?PO_ID=37856 | archivedate = 29 September 2007 | df = dmy-all }}</ref> Schumacher pitted and consequently fell to 19th place, 70 seconds behind teammate and race leader [[Felipe Massa]]. Schumacher recovered and overtook both Fisichella and R\u00e4ikk\u00f6nen to secure fourth place. His performance was classified in the press as \"heroic\",<ref>{{cite news | title = Superb Schumi signs off in style |work=BBC Sport |date=22 October 2006 | url = http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport2/hi/motorsport/formula_one/6075782.stm | accessdate =3 November 2006}}</ref> an \"utterly breath-taking drive\",<ref>{{cite news|title=Brazil: Alonso takes championship, but Michael steals the show |publisher=ManipeF1 |date=22 October 2006 |url=http://www.manipef1.com/news/2006/index.php?id=1744 |accessdate=3 November 2006 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20070510225430/http://www.manipef1.com/news/2006/index.php?id=1744 |archivedate=10 May 2007 |df= }}</ref> and a \"performance that&nbsp;... sums up his career\".<ref>{{cite news | title = 2006 Brazil Grand Prix Report | publisher=PitPass | url = http://www.pitpass.com/src/seasons/2006/gp/brazil/report/result.php | accessdate =3 November 2006}}</ref>\n\n==== 2007\u20132009: retirement at Ferrari ====\n[[File:Thanks Michael 2006 Brazil.jpg|thumb|BMW Sauber with \"Thanks Michael\" messages towards Michael Schumacher on the back of their cars, Schumacher and [[Peter Sauber]] worked together in sports cars before entering F1 in 1992]]\n\nWhile Schumacher was on the podium after winning the [[2006 Italian Grand Prix]], Ferrari issued a press release stating that he would retire from racing at the end of the 2006 season.<ref name=\"press release\">{{cite press release | title =Michael Schumacher will retire from race driving at the end of the 2006 World Championship. | publisher =Ferrari S.p.A. | date =10 September 2006 | url =http://www.ferrariworld.com/events/ms/pdf/monza01_en.pdf | accessdate =24 October 2006 | archive-url =https://web.archive.org/web/20061102031431/http://www.ferrariworld.com/events/ms/pdf/monza01_en.pdf | archive-date =2 November 2006 | url-status=dead }}</ref> Schumacher confirmed his retirement.<ref name=\"retirement\" /> The press release stated that Schumacher would continue working for Ferrari. It was revealed on 29 October 2006 that Ferrari wanted Schumacher to act as assistant to the newly appointed CEO [[Jean Todt]].<ref name=\"newrole\">{{cite news | title = New role for Schumacher at Ferrari? | publisher=PitPass |date=29 October 2006 | url = http://www.pitpass.com/fes_php/pitpass_news_item.php?fes_art_id=29851 | accessdate =29 October 2006}}</ref> This would involve selecting the team's future drivers. After Schumacher's announcement, leading Formula One figures such as [[Niki Lauda]] and [[David Coulthard]] hailed Schumacher as the greatest all-round racing driver in the history of Formula One.<ref>{{cite news| title=Tributes to Schumi | url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport2/hi/motorsport/formula_one/6075194.stm |work=BBC Sport |date=22 October 2006 | accessdate =24 October 2006}}</ref> The tifosi and the Italian press, who did not always take to Schumacher's relatively cold public persona, displayed an affectionate response after he announced his retirement.<ref name=\"schumacher retirement responses3\">{{cite news |first = Simon |last = Evans |title = Italy shows gratitude to Schumacher |url = http://www.autosport.com/news/report.php/id/54449 |work=Autosport |date=11 September 2006 |accessdate =12 September 2006}}</ref>\n\n==== 2007: Ferrari advisor ====\nSchumacher attended several Grands Prix during the season. He drove the [[Ferrari F2007]] for the first time on 24 October at Ferrari's home track in [[Fiorano Circuit|Fiorano]], Italy. He ran no more than five laps and no lap times were recorded. A Ferrari spokesman said the short drive was done for the Fiat board of directors who were holding their meeting in [[Maranello]].<ref>{{cite news | first = Biranit | last = Goren |author2=Lostia, Michele | title = Schumacher in the F2007 for the first time | url = http://www.autosport.com/news/grapevine.php/id/59831 | work=[[Autosport]] | publisher=[[Haymarket Group|Haymarket Publications]] | accessdate =31 January 2009 | date = 25 October 2007}}</ref>\n\n[[File:Schumacher test.jpg|thumb|Schumacher at Finali Mondiali celebrations in the F2007]]\nDuring the {{F1|2007}} season, Schumacher acted as Ferrari's adviser and Jean Todt's 'super assistant'.<ref>{{cite news\n | title      = Schumacher to help Ferrari select drivers\n | work       = Autosport\n | date       = 29 October 2007\n | url        = http://www.autosport.com/news/report.php/id/55462\n | accessdate = 30 November 2007\n}}</ref>\nOn 13 November 2007 Schumacher, who had not driven a Formula One car since he had retired a year earlier, undertook a formal test session for the first time aboard the F2007. He returned in December 2007 to continue helping Ferrari with their development programme at [[Circuito Permanente de Jerez|Jerez circuit]]. He focused on testing electronics and tyres for the 2008 Formula One season.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.autosport.com/f1/news/63934/schumacher-stays-on-top-in-barcelona|title=Schumacher stays on top in Barcelona \u2013 F1 \u2013 Autosport|last=Elizalde|first=Pablo|work=Autosport.com|access-date=22 March 2018|language=en}}</ref>\n\n==== 2008: Ferrari road car development ====\nIn 2007, former Ferrari top manager Ross Brawn said that Schumacher was very likely and also happy to continue testing in 2008; Schumacher later explained his role further saying that he would \"deal with the development of the car inside Gestione Sportiva\" and as part of that \"I'd like to drive, but not too often\".<ref>{{cite web | title = Schumi in charge of developing cars | work=[[Gazzetta dello Sport]] via f1technical.net | date = 11 January 2008 | url = http://www.f1technical.net/news/7958?sid=46d7fcb4610cac76f4d809a27d741051 | accessdate =11 January 2008}}</ref>\n\nDuring 2008 Schumacher also competed in [[motorcycle sport|motorcycle racing]] in the [[CIV Superbike|IDM Superbike]]-series, but stated that he had no intention of a second competitive career in this sport.<ref>''Schumacher slips up in Superbike race'' [http://www.itv-f1.com/News_Article.aspx?id=42681&PO=42681 www.itv-f1.com]{{dead link|date=September 2016 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes}}. Retrieved 5 July 2008.</ref> He was quoted as saying that riding a Ducati was the most exhilarating thing he had done in his life, the second most being sky diving.<ref>Motorcycle Sport and leisure magazine, November 2008 (interview with Randy Mamola)</ref>\n\n==== 2009: planned Massa substitution ====\nIn his capacity as racing advisor to Ferrari, Schumacher was present in [[Budapest]] for the {{F1 GP|2009|Hungarian}} when Ferrari driver [[Felipe Massa]] was seriously injured after being struck by a suspension spring during qualifying. As it became clear that Massa would be unable to compete in the next race at [[Valencia Street Circuit|Valencia]], Schumacher was chosen as a replacement for the Brazilian driver<ref>{{cite web | title = Manager rules out Schumi F1 return | publisher = F1 [[ITV (TV network)|ITV]] | date = 28 July 2009 | url = http://www.itv-f1.com/News_Article.aspx?id=46506 | accessdate = 29 July 2009 | url-status=dead | archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20090731104343/http://www.itv-f1.com/News_Article.aspx?id=46506 | archivedate = 31 July 2009 | df = dmy-all }}</ref> and on 29 July 2009, Ferrari announced that they planned to draft in Schumacher for the {{F1 GP|2009|European}} and subsequent Grands Prix until Massa was able to race again.<ref name=\"2009_comeback\">{{cite web|url=http://www.michaelschumacher.de/?page=news&story_id=82078&lang=uk |title=Michael happy to help |publisher=Michael Schumacher \u2013 Official Website |accessdate=8 August 2009}}</ref> Schumacher tested in a modified F2007 to prepare himself<ref>{{cite news|url=http://globoesporte.globo.com/Esportes/Noticias/Formula_1/0,,MUL1248620-15011,00.html |title=Lealdade custa caro: Schumi ganhar\u00e1 cerca de R$8,5 milh\u00f5es por corrida |publisher=[[Globo.com|Globo]] |date=29 July 2009 |accessdate=30 July 2009 |language=Portuguese |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090802203026/http://globoesporte.globo.com/Esportes/Noticias/Formula_1/0%2C%2CMUL1248620-15011%2C00.html |archivedate=2 August 2009 |df= }}</ref> as he had been unable to test the [[Ferrari F60|2009 car]] due to testing restrictions. Ferrari appealed for special permission for Schumacher to test in a 2009 spec car, but [[WilliamsF1|Williams]], [[Red Bull Racing|Red Bull]] and [[Scuderia Toro Rosso|Toro Rosso]] were against this test.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.gpupdate.net/en/f1-news/217204/williams-against-schumacher-ferrari-test/ |title=Williams against Schumacher Ferrari test |publisher=GPUpdate.net |date=3 August 2009 |accessdate=1 February 2011}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.gpupdate.net/en/f1-news/217220/red-bull-echoes-williams-ferrari-sentiments/ |title=Red Bull echoes Williams's Ferrari sentiments |publisher=GPUpdate.net |date=4 August 2009 |accessdate=1 February 2011}}</ref> In the end, Schumacher was forced to call off his return due to the severity of the neck injury he had received in a motorcycle accident earlier in the year.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.carthusiast.com/schumacher-cancels-f1-return-2056.html |title=Schumacher cancels F1 return |publisher=carthuasiast.com |accessdate=12 August 2009 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090814231008/http://www.carthusiast.com/schumacher-cancels-f1-return-2056.html |archivedate=14 August 2009 |df= }}</ref> Massa's place at Ferrari was instead filled by [[Luca Badoer]] and [[Giancarlo Fisichella]].<ref>{{cite news|last=Noble|first=Jonathan|title=Fisichella: Ferrari drive a dream for me|publisher=[[Haymarket Group|Haymarket Publishing]]|work=autosport.com|url=http://www.autosport.com/news/report.php/id/78286|date=3 September 2009|accessdate=27 November 2016}}</ref>\n\n==== 2019: 50th birthday commemoration ====\nThe Ferrari Museum in Maranello, Italy stated it was planning an exhibition, that would commence on his birthday and span a few months \"both as a celebration and a mark of gratitude to the most successful Prancing Horse driver ever\".<ref>{{Cite journal|date=27 December 2018|title=Schumacher at 50 \u2013 plans to honour a sporting icon|url=https://www.rte.ie/sport/motorsport/2018/1227/1019191-schumacher-at-50-plans-to-honour-a-sporting-icon/|journal=RT\u00c9.ie|language=en}}</ref>\n\n=== Mercedes (2010\u20132012) ===\n{{quote box|quote=\u201cHe played a crucial role when we re-joined F1 and was one of the people who laid the foundation for our future success. We're extremely grateful for everything he did for us.\"|source=Mercedes' team principal [[Toto Wolff]] about Schumacher's influence on the Mercedes team<ref>{{cite news\n | title      = Schumacher a 'founding father\u2019 of Mercedes success \u2013 Wolff\n | work       = Formula One\n | year       = 2019\n | url        = https://www.formula1.com/en/latest/article.schumacher-a-founding-father%27-of-mercedes-success-wolff.1okFZ3mv6kaIicqWKCEaUY.html\n | accessdate = 4 April 2020\n}}</ref>|width=23%|align=right}}\nIn December 2009 it was announced that Schumacher would be returning to Formula One in the {{F1|2010}} season alongside fellow German driver [[Nico Rosberg]] in the new [[Mercedes-Benz in Formula One|Mercedes GP]] team.<ref name = SchuMerc>{{cite news|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/motorsport/formula_one/8427552.stm |title=Michael Schumacher signs up for F1 return with Mercedes|date=23 December 2009|work=BBC Sport |accessdate=23 December 2009}}</ref> The new Mercedes team was their first majority involvement in an F1 team since 1955. Schumacher stated that his preparations to replace the injured Massa for Ferrari had initiated a renewed interest in F1, which, combined with the opportunity to fulfil a long-held ambition to drive for Mercedes and to be working again with team principal Ross Brawn, led Schumacher to accept the offer once he was passed fit.<ref name = SchuMerc /><ref>{{cite web | url =http://www.theroar.com.au/2009/12/24/schumacher-returns-for-a-legacy-or-misery/ | title = Schumacher returns for a legacy or misery | last=Musolino | first=Adrian | date =24 December 2009| work=The Roar| accessdate =24 December 2009}}</ref> After a period of intensive training medical tests, it was confirmed that the neck injury that had prevented him driving for Ferrari the year before had fully healed.<ref name = SchuMerc /> Schumacher signed a three-year contract, reportedly worth \u00a320m.<ref name = SchuMerc />\n\nSchumacher's surprise return to F1 was compared to [[Niki Lauda]]'s in 1982 at age 33 and [[Nigel Mansell]]'s return in 1994 at age 41. Schumacher turned 41 in January 2010 and his prospects with Mercedes were compared with the record set by the oldest F1 champion [[Juan Manuel Fangio]] who was 46 when he won his fifth championship.<ref name = SchuMerc />\n\n==== 2010: return from retirement ====\n[[File:Michael Schumacher 2010 Malaysia 2nd Free Practice.jpg|thumb|Schumacher practising for the {{f1 gp|2010|Malaysian}} from which he retired with a faulty wheel nut]]\n\nSchumacher's first drive of the 2010 Mercedes car&nbsp;\u2013 the [[Mercedes MGP W01]]&nbsp;\u2013 was at an official test in February 2010 in [[Circuit Ricardo Tormo|Valencia]]. He finished sixth in the first race of the season at the {{F1 GP|2010|Bahrain}}. After the Malaysian race, former driver [[Stirling Moss]] suggested that Schumacher, who had finished behind his teammate in each of the first four qualifying sessions and races, might be \"past it\".<ref>{{cite news|title=Schumacher is 'past it' \u2013 Moss|url=http://en.espnf1.com/mercedes/motorsport/story/15453.html|date=27 April 2010|accessdate=25 August 2011|publisher=ESPN F1}}</ref> Many other respected former Formula One drivers thought otherwise, including former rival Damon Hill, who warned \"you should never write Schumacher off\".<ref>{{cite news|url=http://theblackstuff.co.uk/?p=1438 |title=Damon Hill: Never, Ever, Ever, Ever Write Off Schumacher |date=8 July 2010 |accessdate=25 August 2011 |work=The Black Stuff |publisher=The Media Halls |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120331062909/http://theblackstuff.co.uk/?p=1438 |archivedate=31 March 2012 |df= }}</ref> GrandPrix.com identified the inherent [[understeer]] of the Mercedes car, exacerbated by the narrower front tyres introduced for the 2010 season, as contributing to Schumacher's difficulties.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.grandprix.com/ns/ns22213.html|title=Will chassis upgrade solve Schumacher woes?|date=3 May 2010|publisher=Inside F1, inc|accessdate=27 May 2010}}</ref> [[Jenson Button]] would later claim that Mercedes's 2010 car was designed for him, and that their differing driving styles may have contributed to Schumacher's difficulties.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.worldcarfans.com/110072827638/schumachers-car-designed-for-me---button#ixzz17z1I3vRO|title=Schumacher's car designed for me \u2013 Button|work=WorldCarFans|publisher=Black Falcon Media Group|date=28 July 2010|accessdate=13 December 2010}}</ref>\n\nMercedes upgraded their car for the {{F1 GP|2010|Spanish}} where Schumacher finished fourth. At the {{F1 GP|2010|Monaco}} Schumacher finished sixth after passing Ferrari's [[Fernando Alonso]] on the final corner of the race when the safety car returned to the pits. However, he was penalised 20 seconds after the race by the race stewards dropping him to 12th. The stewards judged the pass to be in breach of the FIA's sporting code. Mercedes's differing interpretation of the regulation would later lead to it being clarified by the FIA.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.grandprix.com/ns/ns22278.html|title=FIA To Clarify Safety Car Regulations|date=20 May 2010|publisher=GrandPrix.com|accessdate=27 May 2010}}</ref>\n\n[[File:Schumacher abu dabi 2010.jpg|thumb|Schumacher's {{F1|2010}} season ended with a first lap crash at the {{F1 GP|2010|Abu Dhabi}}.]]\nIn [[2010 Turkish Grand Prix|Turkey]], Schumacher qualified fifth, and finished fourth in the race, both his best results since his return. In {{F1 GP|2010|European}} in Valencia, Schumacher finished 15th, the lowest recorded finish in his career.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.mirror.co.uk/sport/motorsport/2010/06/27/michael-schumacher-blasts-valencia-grand-prix-stewards-115875-22365702/|title=Michael Schumacher blasts Valencia Grand Prix stewards|work=Daily Mirror |location=UK|first=Byron|last=Young|date=27 June 2010|accessdate=15 November 2010}}</ref> In [[2010 Hungarian Grand Prix|Hungary]], Schumacher finished outside the points in eleventh, but was found guilty of dangerous driving at {{convert|180|mph|0|abbr=on}} while unsuccessfully defending tenth position against [[Rubens Barrichello]]. As a result, he was demoted ten places on the grid for the following race, the [[2010 Belgian Grand Prix|Belgian Grand Prix]], where he finished seventh, despite starting 21st after his grid penalty.\n\nAt the season finale in [[2010 Abu Dhabi Grand Prix|Abu Dhabi]], Schumacher was involved in a major accident on the first lap, which occurred after a spin. In recovering from the incident [[Vitantonio Liuzzi]]'s car collided with Schumacher, barely missing his head.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.usatoday.com/sports/motor/2010-11-14-3633796092_x.htm|title=Schumacher escapes unhurt from crash at Abu Dhabi|work=USA Today|publisher=David Hunke; [[Gannett Company]]|date=14 November 2010|accessdate=20 November 2010|agency=[[Associated Press]]}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/sport/motorsport/formulaone/michael-schumacher/8132363/F1-Abu-Dhabi-Grand-Prix-2010-lucky-escape-for-Michael-Schumacher-after-crash-with-Vitantonio-Liuzzi.html|title=Lucky escape for Michael Schumacher after crash with Vitantonio Liuzzi|work=The Daily Telegraph |location=UK|date=14 November 2010|accessdate=20 November 2010}}</ref> Nobody was hurt in the crash, but Schumacher said the crash had been \"frightening\".<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.autosport.com/news/report.php/id/88284|title=Schumacher says crash was frightening|first=Simon|last=Strang|work=Autosport|publisher=[[Haymarket Group|Haymarket Publications]]|date=14 November 2010|accessdate=14 November 2010}}</ref>\n\nHe finished the season 9th with 72 points. Before, it had happened only in [[1991 Formula One season|his d\u00e9but in 1991]] that he finished without a win, pole position, podium or fastest lap.\n\n==== 2011 ====\n[[File:Michael Schumacher 2011 Malaysia FP1 2.jpg|thumb|right|Schumacher at the [[2011 Malaysian Grand Prix]]]]\nSchumacher's first points of 2011 were scored in [[2011 Malaysian Grand Prix|Malaysia]]; he later came sixth in Spain and had a strong race at the {{F1 GP|2011|Canadian}} finishing fourth, after running as high as second in a wet race. Schumacher was passed late in the race by eventual winner [[Jenson Button]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.f1fanatic.co.uk/2011/06/12/canadian-grand-prix-report/|title=2011 Canadian GP review: Button bounces back to win|date=12 June 2011|website=F1 Fanatic|access-date=25 January 2017}}</ref>\n[[File:2011 Canadian GP Friday 18.jpg|thumb|right|Schumacher finished fourth in the [[2011 Canadian Grand Prix]]]]\n\nSchumacher clashed with [[Vitaly Petrov]] in Valencia, and with [[Kamui Kobayashi]] in Britain, and marked the 20th anniversary of his Formula One d\u00e9but at the {{F1 GP|2011|Belgian}}. Despite starting last in Belgium, Schumacher raced well and finished fifth. Schumacher again raced well in Italy, duelling with [[Lewis Hamilton]] for fourth place. The {{F1 GP|2011|Japanese}} saw Schumacher lead three laps during the race, marking the first time he had led a race since 2006.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/motorsport/formula_one/9610783.stm|title=Japanese Grand Prix as it happened|work=[[BBC Sport]]|publisher=BBC|date=9 October 2011|accessdate=10 October 2011|first=Sam|last=Sheringham|quote=Lap 40: This is the first time Schuey has led a race since the Japanese GP in 2006.}}</ref> In doing so, he became the oldest driver to lead a race since [[Jack Brabham]] in {{F1|1970}}.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.abc.net.au/news/2013-12-30/michael-schumacher-the-greatest-formula-one-driver-of-all-time/5178660?pfmredir=sm|title=Michael Schumacher the greatest F1 driver of all time|date=30 December 2013|newspaper=ABC News|language=en-AU|access-date=25 January 2017}}</ref>\n\nAt the {{F1 GP|2011|Indian}} Schumacher started well and finished fifth after overtaking Rosberg at the end of the race. Schumacher diced again with Rosberg in {{F1 GP|2011|Abu Dhabi}}, battling over sixth position on the first lap. Schumacher finished the season in eighth place in the Drivers' Championship, with 76 points.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.f1-fansite.com/f1-results/results-2011-formula-1-season/|title=2011 F1 Results & Standings Schedule {{!}} F1-Fansite.com|newspaper=F1-Fansite.com|language=en-US|access-date=25 January 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170202041227/http://www.f1-fansite.com/f1-results/results-2011-formula-1-season/|archive-date=2 February 2017|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n\n==== 2012: final season ====\n[[File:2012 Australian Grand Prix 10.jpg|thumb|right|Schumacher climbs out of his car after spinning off during the final practice session at the {{F1 GP|2012|Australian}}. He retired from the race with gearbox problems.]]\nSchumacher was again partnered by Rosberg at Mercedes for the 2012 season.<ref name=\"Schumacher\">{{cite news|url=http://en.espnf1.com/mercedes/motorsport/story/7532.html|title=Schumacher could stay in F1 after 2012|publisher=ESPN F1|date=27 January 2010|accessdate=25 July 2010}}</ref> Schumacher retired from the inaugural race of the season {{F1 GP|2012|Australian}}, and scored a point in the second round in Malaysia.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.google.com/hostednews/ukpress/article/ALeqM5gcx7P9DYPxinDYuIuShwcYbp5pZg?docId=N1176961332075459939A|title=Brawn upbeat despite Melbourne failure|date=18 March 2012|accessdate=18 March 2012|agency=[[Press Association]]}}</ref> In China Schumacher started on the front row alongside Rosberg on pole, but retired due to a loose wheel after a mechanic's error during a pit stop.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.sportskeeda.com/f1/michael-schumachers-retirement-at-chinese-grand-prix-what-exactly-happens-when-a-wheel-nut-is-loose|title=Michael Schumacher's retirement at Chinese Grand Prix \u2013 What exactly happens when a wheel nut is loose?|date=19 April 2012|access-date=22 March 2018}}</ref>\n\nAfter causing a collision with [[Bruno Senna]] in Spain, Schumacher received a five-place grid penalty for the [[2012 Monaco Grand Prix|Monaco Grand Prix]]. Schumacher was fastest in qualifying in Monaco; but started sixth owing to his penalty.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/sport/motorsport/formulaone/michael-schumacher/9292074/Monaco-Grand-Prix-2012-grid-penalty-denies-Michael-Schumacher-of-pole-as-Mark-Webber-leads-the-line.html|title=Monaco Grand Prix 2012: grid penalty denies Michael Schumacher of pole as Mark Webber leads the line|journal=Daily Telegraph|last=Cary|first=Tom|date=26 May 2012|access-date=22 March 2018|language=en-GB|issn=0307-1235}}</ref> He later retired from seventh place in the race.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/sport/motorsport/formulaone/mercedes/9293463/Monaco-Grand-Prix-2012-bittersweet-weekend-for-Mercedes-as-Rosberg-shines-and-Schumachers-bad-luck-continues.html|title=Monaco Grand Prix 2012: bittersweet weekend for Mercedes as Rosberg shines and Schumacher's bad luck continues|journal=Daily Telegraph|last=Sport|first=Telegraph|date=27 May 2012|access-date=22 March 2018|language=en-GB|issn=0307-1235}}</ref>\n[[File:Michael Schumacher pole lap monaco 2012.JPG|thumb|Schumacher qualified fastest at the [[2012 Monaco Grand Prix]].]]\nAt the {{F1 GP|2012|European}}, Schumacher finished third in the race, his only podium finish since his return to F1 with Mercedes. At the age of 43 years and 173 days, he became the oldest driver to achieve a podium since [[Jack Brabham]]'s second-place finish at the [[1970 British Grand Prix]]. Further records were set by Schumacher in Germany, where he set the fastest lap in a Grand Prix for the 77th time in his career, and in Belgium where he became the second driver in history to race in 300 Grands Prix.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www1.skysports.com/formula-1/news/22058/7928246/Conclusions-from-the-German-GP |title=Conclusions from the German GP |work=[[Sky Sports]] |publisher=[[BSkyB]] |date=23 July 2012 |accessdate=24 July 2012 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120726015714/http://www1.skysports.com/formula-1/news/22058/7928246/Conclusions-from-the-German-GP |archivedate=26 July 2012 |df= }}</ref>\n\n[[File:Michael Schumacher, United States Grand Prix, Austin 2012.jpg|thumb|Schumacher at the [[2012 United States Grand Prix|2012 US Grand Prix]]]]\n\nSchumacher's indecision over his future plans in F1 led to him being replaced by [[Lewis Hamilton]] at Mercedes for the 2013 season.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.autosport.com/news/report.php/id/102906/|first=Jonathan|last=Noble|title=Schumacher's indecision prompted Mercedes to chase Hamilton|work=[[Autosport]]|publisher=[[Haymarket Media Group|Haymarket Publications]]|date=28 September 2012|accessdate=16 October 2012}}</ref> In October 2012, Schumacher announced he would retire for a second time at the conclusion of the season.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.formula1.com/news/headlines/2012/10/13863.html|title=Schumacher announces Formula One retirement|publisher=[[Formula One Group|Formula One Administration]]|date=4 October 2012|accessdate=4 October 2012}}</ref> The following week he was quoted as saying: \"There were times in the past few months in which I didn't want to deal with Formula One or prepare for the next Grand Prix.\"<ref>{{cite news|url=http://formula-one.speedtv.com/article/f1-michael-schumacher-ready-to-go-home-after-formula-one-retirement/|title=Schumacher Ready To Go 'Home' After Retirement|work=[[Speed (TV channel)|Speed]]|publisher=Speed Channel, Inc.|agency=GMM|date=14 October 2012|accessdate=16 October 2012|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20121015114312/http://formula-one.speedtv.com/article/f1-michael-schumacher-ready-to-go-home-after-formula-one-retirement|archivedate=15 October 2012}}</ref> The season and his 21-year F1 career concluded with the [[2012 Brazilian Grand Prix]], in which Schumacher finished seventh. He placed 13th in the 2012 Drivers' Championship.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.formula1.com/en/results.html/2012/drivers.html|title=2012 Driver Standings|website=Formula1.com|accessdate=5 November 2017}}</ref>\n\n== Helmet ==\nSchumacher, in conjunction with [[Schuberth]], helped develop the first lightweight carbon helmet. In 2004, a prototype was publicly tested by being driven over by a [[tank]]; it survived intact.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.jeccomposites.com/composites-news/682/Even-a-tank.html |title=Even a tank can't halt schu now |accessdate=8 November 2006 |publisher=JEC Composites |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20070108220644/http://www.jeccomposites.com/composites-news/682/Even-a-tank.html |archivedate=8 January 2007  }}</ref> <!-- What does this mean: \"The Layers were \"baked\" into the corners to achieve extra stiffness and extra magnesium.\"?-->The helmet keeps the driver cool by funneling directed airflow through fifty holes.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.theprancinghorse.co.uk/news/newsfeatures/1.html |title=Michael Schumacher Helmet Profile |accessdate=10 February 2007 |publisher=theprancinghorse.co.uk |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20061230064118/http://www.theprancinghorse.co.uk/news/newsfeatures/1.html |archivedate=30 December 2006 |url-status=dead }}</ref> Schumacher's original helmet sported the colours of the [[flag of Germany|German flag]] and his sponsor's decals. On the top was a blue circle with white [[astroid]]s.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.motorsport.com/f1/news/gallery-michael-schumacher-s-f1-helmets-939422/|title=Gallery: Michael Schumacher's F1 helmets|work=Motorsport.com|access-date=22 March 2018|language=en|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180323160204/https://www.motorsport.com/f1/news/gallery-michael-schumacher-s-f1-helmets-939422/|archive-date=23 March 2018|url-status=dead}}</ref> From the [[2000 Monaco Grand Prix]], in order to differentiate his colours from his new teammate [[Rubens Barrichello]] (whose helmet was predominantly white with a blue circle on top and a red ellipsis surrounding the visor), Schumacher changed the upper blue colour and some of the white areas to red.<ref name=\"mSchumacher biography\">{{cite web | title = Michael Schumacher Biography | url = http://www.mschumacher.com/biography.html | publisher=mschumacher.com | accessdate =25 October 2006}}</ref> For the Brazilian Grand Prix race of 2006 (at the time intended to be his final Grand Prix), he wore an all-red helmet that included the names of his ninety-one Grand Prix victories.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.pitpass.com/fes_php/pitpass_news_item.php?fes_art_id=29768 |title=Michael's winning helmet |date=21 October 2006 |accessdate=7 November 2006 |publisher=PitPass}}</ref><!--Contrary to widespread expectations, Schumacher neither reverted to the original design for his 2010 comeback with Mercedes GP{{clarify|date=November 2010}}, nor adopted a new silver version. Instead, the helmet remained red (Suzuka 2006 design), Schumacher stating it to be a reference to his links with Ferrari.{{Citation needed|June 2010|date=November 2010}} --> For the [[2011 Belgian Grand Prix]], Schumacher's 20th anniversary in Formula One, he wore a commemorative gold-leafed helmet.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://plus.autosport.com/free/feature/3825/behind-the-scenes-at-spa/|title=Behind the scenes at Spa|first=Jonathan|last=Noble|work=[[Autosport]]|publisher=[[Haymarket Group|Haymarket Publications]]|date=29 August 2011|accessdate=30 August 2011|quote=Helmet supplier Schuberth provided him with a special 21-carat gold plated helmet, which he wore as a special one-off for the weekend.}}</ref> The helmet, very similar to his current helmet, included the year of his d\u00e9but to the present, and the years of his seven World titles. For the [[2012 Belgian Grand Prix]], Schumacher's 300th Grand Prix appearance, he wore a special platinum-leafed helmet with a message of his achievement.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.cmhelmets.com/product/michael-schumacher-commemorative-2012-300th-gp-belgium-f1-replica-helmet-full-size/|title=Michael Schumacher 2012 300TH GP Commemorative F1 Replic|website=www.cmhelmets.com|access-date=}}</ref>\n<gallery mode=\"packed\" heights=\"200\">\nFile:Schumi 1994 Helmet.jpg|Helmet for the [[1994 Formula One season|1994 season]] ([[Benetton Formula|Benetton]]); Schumacher used the [[Bell Sports|Bell]] helmet for 9 years in Formula One, from the [[1992 Canadian Grand Prix]] to [[2001 Australian Grand Prix]].\nFile:Michael Schumacher 1995 helmet 2015 Grand Prix Museum.jpg|Bell helmet for the [[1995 Formula One season|1995 season]] ([[Benetton Formula|Benetton]]); Schumacher even kept using this white-coloured helmet after moving to Ferrari in {{f1|1996}} until he switched its colour to red at the [[2000 Monaco Grand Prix]].\nFile:Michael Schumacher helmet Museo Ferrari.jpg|Schuberth helmet for the [[2002 Formula One season|2002 season]] ([[Scuderia Ferrari|Ferrari]]); At the [[2001 Malaysian Grand Prix]], Schumacher switched his helmet from Bell to [[Schuberth]] though there was a contract with Bell for the [[2001 Formula One season|2001 season]]. From the 2001 season, Schumacher continued to use the Schuberth helmet until his last race in Formula One.\nFile:Schumacher 2011 helmet.jpg|Schuberth helmet for the [[2011 Formula One season|2011 season]] ([[Mercedes-Benz in Formula One|Mercedes GP]]); Schumacher kept using a red-coloured helmet at [[Silver Arrows|''Silver'' Arrows]]. [[Chinese dragon]] illustration and a [[Chinese characters|Chinese character]] \"[[Radical 19|\u529b]]\" (\"power\") are inscribed on the back of the helmet.\n</gallery>\n\n== Honours ==\n[[File:Michael-Schumacher-S.jpg|thumb|left|Turns 9\u201310 of the [[N\u00fcrburgring]] were renamed after Schumacher in 2007.]]\nSchumacher was honoured many times during his career. In April 2002, for his contributions to sport and his contributions in raising awareness of child education, he was named as one of the UNESCO Champions for sport,<ref name=\"UNESCO\">{{cite web | url=http://portal.unesco.org/en/ev.php-URL_ID=24019&URL_DO=DO_TOPIC&URL_SECTION=201.html | title=Michael Schumacher UNESCO Champion for sport | date=April 2002 | publisher=UNESCO | url-status=dead | archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20081024071425/http://portal.unesco.org/en/ev.php-URL_ID%3D24019%26URL_DO%3DDO_TOPIC%26URL_SECTION%3D201.html | archivedate=24 October 2008 | df=dmy-all }}</ref> joining the other eight, which include [[Pel\u00e9]], [[Sergey Bubka]] and [[Justine Henin]]. He won the [[Laureus World Sports Awards|Laureus World Sportsman of the Year]] award twice, in 2002 and 2004 for his performances in the {{F1|2001}} and {{F1|2003}} seasons respectively. He also received nominations for the 2001, 2003, 2005 and 2007 awards.<ref name=\"laureus-award Michael Schumacher\">{{cite web|url=http://www.laureus.com/winners?q=node/821 |title=Michael Schumacher |accessdate=18 April 2007 |year=2006 |work=Laureus |publisher=Laureus World Sport Awards Limited |archivedate=28 September 2007 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20070928063322/http://www.laureus.com/winners?q=node%2F821 |url-status=dead |df= }}</ref> He shares the record for having the second-most nominations for the award with [[Roger Federer]] with six nominations, and is eclipsed only by [[Tiger Woods]] who has been nominated seven times. He holds the distinction of having the most nominations for a motorsport athlete, ([[Fernando Alonso]] has been nominated only twice, [[Sebastian Vettel]] three times, and [[Valentino Rossi]] five times) and being the only motorsport athlete to have won the award more than once.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.laureus.com/winners|title=Winners|accessdate=11 August 2015}}</ref>\n\nIn honour of Schumacher's racing career and his efforts to improve safety and the sport, he was awarded an [[F\u00e9d\u00e9ration Internationale de l'Automobile|FIA]] Gold Medal for Motor Sport in 2006.<ref>{{cite news | url = http://www.formula1.com/news/headlines/2006/12/5395.html | title = Schumacher honoured by the FIA | accessdate =15 December 2006 |date=11 December 2006 | publisher=Formula1.com}}</ref> In 2007, in recognition of his contribution to Formula One racing, the [[N\u00fcrburgring]] racing track renamed turns 8 and 9 (the Audi and Shell Kurves) as the ''Schumacher S'',<ref>{{cite news | url = http://www.formula1.com/news/features/2007/7/6506.html | title = Schumacher honoured by having a corner named after him at Nurburgring | accessdate =21 July 2007 |date=21 July 2007 | publisher=Formula One}}</ref> and a month later he presented [[A1 Team Germany]] with the A1 World Cup at the [[2006\u201307 A1 Grand Prix season|A1GP World Cup]] of Motorsport 2007 awards ceremony.<ref>{{cite web | title=Michael Schumacher honours team Germany's A1GP success | work=f1.automoto365.com | publisher=A1GP | date=1 May 2007 | url=http://f1.automoto365.com/news/controller.php?lang=en&theme=default&month=5&year=2007&nextMode=GpNewsForm&news_id=25372 | accessdate=7 May 2007 | url-status=dead | archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20070927044225/http://f1.automoto365.com/news/controller.php?lang=en&theme=default&month=5&year=2007&nextMode=GpNewsForm&news_id=25372 | archivedate=27 September 2007 | df=dmy-all }}</ref> He was nominated for the [[Prince of Asturias Awards|Prince of Asturias Award for Sport]] for 2007, which he won both for sporting prowess and for his humanitarian record.<ref>{{cite web|title=Prince of Asturias Awards' Michael Schumacher page |url=http://www.fundacionprincipedeasturias.org/ing/04/premiados/trayectorias/trayectoria822.html |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20080725110508/http://www.fundacionprincipedeasturias.org/ing/04/premiados/trayectorias/trayectoria822.html |archivedate=25 July 2008 |df= }}</ref><ref name=\"astjury2007\">{{cite web|url=http://www.fundacionprincipedeasturias.org/ing/04/premios/premios6_2007.html |title=Asturias Jury report |date=5 September 2007 |publisher=Fundaci\u00f3n Princesa de Asturias |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20080724172918/http://www.fundacionprincipedeasturias.org/ing/04/premios/premios6_2007.html |archivedate=24 July 2008 |df= }}</ref>\n\nIn 2008, the [[Swiss Football Association]] appointed long-time Swiss resident Schumacher as the country's ambassador for the [[2008 UEFA European Football Championship|2008 European football championship]].<ref>{{cite news |url = http://www.gpupdate.net/en/f1-news/148435/schumacher-becomes-swiss-football-ambassador/ | title = Schumacher becomes Swiss football ambassador | accessdate =1 February 2011 |date=16 April 2007 | publisher=GPUpdate.net}}</ref>\n\nOn 30 April 2010, Schumacher was honored with the Officier of [[L\u00e9gion d'honneur]] title from French prime minister [[Fran\u00e7ois Fillon]].<ref>{{cite news |url = http://english.ruvr.ru/2010/04/30/7127906.html |title = L\u00e9gion d'honneur for Shumacher |accessdate = 3 May 2010 |date = 30 April 2010 |publisher = The Voice of Russia |archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20110716090954/http://english.ruvr.ru/2010/04/30/7127906.html |archive-date = 16 July 2011 |url-status=dead |df = dmy-all }}</ref>\n\nOn 13 November 2014, Schumacher was awarded the Millennium Trophy at the [[Bambi Award]]s.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://u2station.com/news/2014/11/ariana-grande-u2-among-winners-at-2014-bambi-awards.php |title=Ariana Grande, U2 Among Winners at 2014 Bambi Awards |publisher=U2 Station |date=14 November 2014 |accessdate=15 November 2014}}</ref>\n\n== Racing controversies ==\n\n=== Championship-deciding collisions ===\nGoing into the [[1994 Australian Grand Prix]], the final race of the [[1994 Formula One season|1994 season]], Schumacher led [[Damon Hill]] by a single point in the Drivers' Championship. Schumacher led the race from the beginning, but on lap 35 he went off track and hit the wall with his right side wheels,<ref name=\"autosportcrashes\">{{cite news | title =Schumacher 500: Has the King Lost His Crown? | work=Autosport |first = Ville |last = Kopu |author2=Nottmeier, Jan | url = http://atlasf1.autosport.com/98/ger/schum.html | accessdate =24 October 2006}}</ref> returning to the track at reduced speed, and with car damage, but still leading the race. At the next corner Hill attempted to pass on the inside, but Schumacher turned in sharply and they collided. Both cars were eliminated from the race and, as neither driver scored, Schumacher took the title.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/motorsport/formula_one/7951521.stm|title=Classic F1 \u2013 Australian Grand Prix 1994|date=23 March 2009|publisher=BBC |accessdate=24 March 2009}} Coverage of the collision occurs between 02:14 and 03:30.</ref> The race stewards judged it a racing accident and took no action against either driver, but public opinion is divided over the incident, and Schumacher was vilified in the [[British media]].<ref name=\"Molinaro\">{{cite news | title =Top 10 Michael Schumacher Moments | publisher=CBC Sports |first = John F. |last = Molinaro|date=12 September 2006 | url = http://www.cbc.ca/sports/indepth/10-schumacher-momments.html | accessdate =3 November 2006}}</ref><ref>{{cite book | last = Henry | first = Alan | title = Wheel to Wheel: Great Duels of Formula One Racing | origyear = 1996 | publisher=Weidenfeld Nicolson Illustrated | isbn = 978-0-7538-0522-0 | page = 117 | year = 1998}}</ref><ref>{{cite news | title = Now we are 76...: Murray Walker | publisher = grandprix.com | date = 18 October 1999 | url = http://www.grandprix.com/ft/ft00341.html | accessdate = 30 November 2007 | archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20071203081029/http://www.grandprix.com/ft/ft00341.html | archive-date = 3 December 2007 | url-status=dead | df = dmy-all }}</ref>\n\nAt the [[1997 European Grand Prix]] at [[Circuito Permanente de Jerez|Jerez]], the last race of the [[1997 Formula One season|season]], Schumacher led Williams's [[Jacques Villeneuve]] by one point in the Drivers' Championship. As Villeneuve attempted to pass Schumacher at the Dry Sac corner on lap 48, Schumacher turned in and the right-front wheel of Schumacher's Ferrari hit the left sidepod of Villeneuve's car. Schumacher retired from the race as a result, but Villeneuve finished in third place, taking four points and so becoming the World Champion.<ref name=\"autosportcrashes\" /> The race stewards did not initially award any penalty, but two weeks after the race Schumacher was disqualified from the entire 1997 Drivers' Championship after an [[F\u00e9d\u00e9ration Internationale de l'Automobile|FIA]] disciplinary hearing found that his \"manoeuvre was an instinctive reaction and although deliberate not made with malice or premeditation. It was a serious error.\"<ref name=\"fia97verdict\" /> Schumacher accepted the decision<ref name=\"schudisq\">{{cite news | title = Schumacher loses championship runner-up crown |work=BBC News |date=11 November 1997 | url = http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/europe/29895.stm | accessdate =24 October 2006}}</ref> and admitted having made a mistake.<ref name=\"1997grandprixcom\" /> Schumacher's actions were widely condemned in British, German, and Italian newspapers.<ref name=\"Molinaro\" /><ref name=\"1997grandprixcom\">{{cite news | title = The lost honor of Michael Schumacher | publisher=GrandPrix.com |date=3 November 1997 | url = http://www.grandprix.com/ns/ns01331.html | accessdate =24 October 2006}}</ref> This made Schumacher the only driver in the history of the sport, as of 2019, to be disqualified from a Drivers' World Championship.<ref>{{cite news | title = Calling time on a career | publisher = itv-f1.com | url = http://www.itv-f1.com/Feature.aspx?Type=James_Allen&PO_ID=37290 | accessdate = 15 December 2007 | url-status=dead | archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20080314131806/http://www.itv-f1.com/Feature.aspx?Type=James_Allen | archivedate = 14 March 2008 | df = dmy-all }}</ref>\n\n=== Team orders ===\n[[File:2002 Austrian GP.jpg|thumb|[[Rubens Barrichello]] makes way for Schumacher at the end of the [[2002 Austrian Grand Prix]]]]\nHistorically, [[team orders]] have always been an accepted part of Formula One. However, in the final metres of the [[2002 Austrian Grand Prix]], Schumacher's teammate, [[Rubens Barrichello]], slowed his car under orders from Ferrari to allow Schumacher to pass and win the race.<ref name=\"bbcaustria\">{{cite news | title = Schumacher steals Austrian win |work=BBC Sport |date=12 May 2002 | url = http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport2/hi/motorsport/formula_one/1982612.stm | accessdate =24 October 2006}}</ref> Although the switching of positions did not break any actual sporting or technical regulation, it angered fans and it was claimed that the team's actions showed a lack of sportsmanship and respect to the spectators. Many argued that Schumacher did not need to be \"given\" wins in only the 6th race of the season, particularly given that he had already won four of the previous five Grands Prix, and that Barrichello had dominated the race weekend up to that point. At the podium ceremony, Schumacher pushed Barrichello onto the top step,<ref name=\"bbcaustria\" /> and for this disturbance, the Ferrari team incurred a US$1&nbsp;million fine.<ref>{{cite news | title = Record fine for Turks |agency=Reuters | url = http://www.eurosport.co.uk/formula1/sport_sto967344.shtml | accessdate =24 October 2006}}</ref> Later in the season at the end of the [[2002 United States Grand Prix]], Schumacher slowed down within sight of the finishing line, allowing Barrichello to win by 0.011 seconds, the 2nd closest margin in F1 history. Schumacher's explanation varied between it being him \"returning the favour\" for Austria (now that Schumacher's title was secure), or trying to engineer a dead-heat (a feat derided as near-impossible in a sport where timings are taken to within a thousandth of a second).<ref>{{cite news | first = Jonathan | last = Legard | authorlink = Jonathan Legard | url = http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/motorsport/formula_one/2287699.stm | title = Ferrari's own goal |publisher=BBC |work=BBC Sport | date = 30 September 2002 | accessdate =28 February 2009}}</ref> The FIA subsequently banned \"team orders which interfere with the race result\",<ref>{{cite news | title = Formula One closes door on team orders | work=USA Today |date=28 October 2002 | url = https://www.usatoday.com/sports/motor/formula1/2002-10-28-changes_x.htm |first = Stephen |last = Wade | accessdate =28 October 2006}}</ref><ref>{{cite press release|title=F1 Commission declaration |publisher=FIA |date=28 October 2002 |url=http://www.fia.com/gate?action=retrievePage&locale=en_GB&PageID=331368089&printer=on |accessdate=30 October 2006 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20070326115324/http://www.fia.com/gate?action=retrievePage&locale=en_GB&PageID=331368089&printer=on |archivedate=26 March 2007 |df= }}</ref> but the ban was lifted for the 2011 season because the ruling was difficult to enforce.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/motorsport/formula_one/9275796.stm|title=F1 chiefs drop the ban on team orders in new rules|work=BBC Sport |date=10 December 2010|accessdate=27 January 2011}}</ref>\n\n=== Dangerous driving ===\nDuring his spell in [[Sauber]], in the 1991 Sportscar World Championship, Schumacher was involved in a serious incident with [[Derek Warwick]] in that year's [[1991 430&nbsp;km of N\u00fcrburgring|430 km of N\u00fcrburgring]]. While trying to set his flying lap in qualifying, Schumacher encountered Warwick's [[Jaguar XJR-14|Jaguar]] on a slow lap resulting in lost time for Schumacher. As retaliation for being in his way, Schumacher swerved the Sauber into Warwick's car, hitting the Jaguar's nose and front wheel. Enraged by the German's attitude, Warwick drove to the pits and chased a fleeing Schumacher on foot through the Sauber pits. He eventually caught up with Schumacher, and it took intervention from [[Jochen Mass]] to prevent Warwick physically assaulting Schumacher.<ref>{{cite magazine|url=http://www.autosport.com/journal/article.php/id/347/|title=Schumacher at Sauber|magazine=Autosport |date=February 2005|accessdate=17 December 2012|first=Gary|last=Watkins}}</ref>\n\nToward the end of the [[2010 Hungarian Grand Prix]], [[Rubens Barrichello]] attempted to pass Schumacher down the inside on the main straight. Schumacher closed the inside line to force Barrichello onto the outside, but Barrichello persisted on the inside at {{convert|180|mph|km/h|abbr=on}}, despite the close proximity of a concrete wall and Schumacher leaving him only inches to spare. Barrichello said \"It is the most dangerous thing that I have been through\", and \"There is not a rule for that, but between ourselves we should take a line, stick to it and that's it.\" Schumacher said that \"Obviously there was space enough to go through. We didn't touch, so I guess I just left enough space for him to come through.\" Ross Brawn said \"at the end of the day he gave him enough space. You can argue that it was marginal, but it was just tough \u2013 tough racing.\" A range of ex-drivers and commentators were highly critical of Schumacher. Although there was no accident, the race steward, the same Derek Warwick of the 1991 N\u00fcrburgring incident, wanted to black flag Schumacher since that \"would have shown a better example to our young drivers\". The Hungaroring incident was ruled to be dangerous and Schumacher received a 10 place grid penalty for the [[2010 Belgian Grand Prix|next race]]. Schumacher accepted the decision, and apologised.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/motorsport/formula_one/8875370.stm|title=Schumacher punished for dangerous move on Barrichello|work=BBC Sport|date=1 August 2010|accessdate=2 August 2010|first=Richard|last=Rae}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/sport/motorsport/formulaone/michael-schumacher/7922228/Michael-Schumacher-defended-by-Ross-Brawn-after-Rubens-Barrichello-near-miss.html|work=The Daily Telegraph |location=UK|date=2 August 2010|accessdate=27 January 2011|title=Michael Schumacher defended by Ross Brawn after Rubens Barrichello near-miss}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=http://en.espnf1.com/hungary/motorsport/story/25330.html|title=Schumacher apologises to Barrichello|publisher=ESPN F1|date=2 August 2010|accessdate=27 January 2011}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=http://en.espnf1.com/f1/motorsport/story/25188.html|title= Rubens fumes at 'dangerous' Schumacher move|publisher=ESPN F1|date=1 August 2010|accessdate=27 January 2011}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.f1technical.net/news/15260|title=Mercedes GP leave Budapest empty handed|date=1 August 2010|accessdate=27 January 2011|publisher=F1Technical.net}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=http://en.espnf1.com/f1/motorsport/story/25393.html|title=Schumacher lucky not to be disqualified \u2013 Warwick|publisher=ESPN |date=3 August 2010|accessdate=17 December 2012}}</ref>\n\n=== Other incidents ===\nIn 1994, suspicion of foul play by the Benetton team (who were eventually found to have been responsible for some [[1994 Formula One cheating controversy|technical violations]] over the course of the season) was said to have troubled Ayrton Senna that season. For example, in the words of his then teammate, Damon Hill, Senna had chosen to stay at the first corner of the Aida circuit following his retirement from the [[1994 Pacific Grand Prix|Pacific Grand Prix]]. After listening to Schumacher's [[Benetton B194]] as it went past, Senna \"concluded that there was, what he regarded, as unusual noises from the engine\".<ref>{{cite video|title=The Last Teammate (1994 San Marino Grand Prix's 20th Anniversary documentary) @ 8'25\" |url=http://www1.skysports.com/watch/video/sports/f1/9293944/ |publisher=SkySportsF1 |accessdate=2 May 2014 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140503185230/http://www1.skysports.com/watch/video/sports/f1/9293944/ |archivedate=3 May 2014 |df= }}</ref> The FIA subsequently issued a press release setting out action that it required teams to take before the [[1994 German Grand Prix|German Grand Prix]], given that various cars were found to have an advanced engine management systems emulating launch and traction control.<ref>{{cite web|title=Interview with Max Mosley|url=http://www.motorsport.com/f1/news/interview-with-max-mosley|date=8 May 1994|accessdate=14 November 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Engine management software FIA press release|url=http://www.motorsport.com/f1/news/engine-management-software-fia-press-release/|date=8 May 1994|accessdate=14 November 2015}}</ref>\n\nIn 1995, Schumacher and Williams driver [[David Coulthard]] were disqualified for fuel irregularities, after a switch to Renault engines and Elf oils.<ref>{{cite web|title=Exclusion of Car No.1 (Schumacher/Benetton) and Car No. 6 (Coulthard/Williams) from the results of the Brazilian Grand Prix |url=http://www.fia.com/resources/documents/314726189__29_03_1995_F1_BRA_GP_Fuel.pdf |publisher=FIA |date=29 March 1995 |accessdate=22 October 2012 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20050302043419/http://www.fia.com/resources/documents/314726189__29_03_1995_F1_BRA_GP_Fuel.pdf |archivedate=2 March 2005 |df= }}</ref> On appeal, both drivers had their results and points reinstated, but both teams lost the points the results would normally have earned in the Constructors' Championship.<ref>{{cite book | chapter = 1995 Grands Prix: Brazilian Grand Prix | last = Henry | first = Alan | authorlink = Alan Henry | title = Autocourse 1995\u201396 | origyear = 1995 | publisher = Hazleton Publishing | isbn = 978-1-874557-36-4 | page = 90 |date=December 1995| title-link = Autocourse }}</ref>\n\nThe 1998 Canadian Grand Prix saw Schumacher accused of dangerous driving when his exit from the pit-lane forced [[Heinz-Harald Frentzen]] off the track and into retirement. Despite receiving a 10-second penalty, Schumacher recovered and won the race.<ref>{{cite news | title = 1998 Canadian Grand Prix | publisher=grandprix.com | url = http://www.grandprix.com/gpe/rr621.html | accessdate =1 July 2009}}</ref>\n\nTwo laps from the finish of the [[1998 British Grand Prix]], Schumacher was leading the race when he was issued a stop-and-go penalty for overtaking a lapped car ([[Alexander Wurz]]) during the early moments of a [[Safety Car]] period. This penalty involves going into the pit lane and stopping for 10 seconds, and the rules state that a driver must serve his penalty within three laps of the penalty being issued. On the third lap after receiving the penalty, Schumacher turned into the pit lane to serve his penalty, but as this was the last lap of the race, and as Ferrari's pit box was located after the start/finish line, Schumacher technically finished the race before serving the penalty.<ref>{{cite news | title = British Grand Prix Review | work=Autosport | url = http://atlasf1.autosport.com/98/bri/burley.html | accessdate =24 October 2006}}</ref> The stewards initially resolved that problem by adding 10 seconds to Schumacher's race time, then later rescinded the penalty completely due to the irregularities in how the penalty had been issued.{{failed verification|date=August 2017}}\n\nDuring qualifying for the [[2006 Monaco Grand Prix]], Schumacher set the fastest time, but his car stopped in the Rascasse corner on the racing line, leaving the corner partially blocked, while his main contender for the season title, [[Fernando Alonso]], was on his final qualifying lap. Schumacher stated that he simply locked up the wheels going into the corner and that the car then stalled while he attempted to reverse out.<ref name=\"monacopole\">{{cite news\n |title=Schumacher is stripped of pole\n |publisher=Formula1.com\n |date=27 May 2006\n |url=http://www.formula1.com/news/headlines/2006/5/4430.html\n |accessdate=24 October 2006\n |url-status=dead\n |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100722010449/http://www.formula1.com/news/headlines/2006/5/4430.html\n |archivedate=22 July 2010\n}}</ref> Alonso believed he would have been on pole if the incident had not happened,<ref>{{cite news | title = Post-qualifying press conference \u2013 Monaco | publisher=Formula1.com |date=27 May 2006 | url = http://www.formula1.com/race/news/4428/757.html | accessdate =24 October 2006 |archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20060906110504/http://www.formula1.com/race/news/4428/757.html |archivedate = 6 September 2006}}</ref> and Schumacher was stripped of pole position by the race stewards and started the race at the back of the grid.<ref name=\"monacopole\" /> In the same qualifying session, [[Giancarlo Fisichella]] was similarly found to have blocked [[David Coulthard]] from improving his time, but Fisichella was only demoted five places on the grid.<ref name=\"fisichella-drop\">{{cite web|url=http://www.formula1.com/race/news/4429/757.html|title=Fisichella punished by stewards|date=27 May 2006|publisher=Formula One official site |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20061019043940/http://www.formula1.com/race/news/4429/757.html |archivedate=19 October 2006}}</ref> At the [[2010 Monaco Grand Prix]], the safety car was deployed after an accident involving [[Karun Chandhok]] and [[Jarno Trulli]], and pulled into the pits on the last lap. Schumacher passed Alonso before the finish line. Mercedes held that \"the combination of the race control messages 'Safety Car in this lap' and 'Track Clear' and the green flags and lights shown by the marshals after safety car line one indicated that the race was not finishing under the safety car and all drivers were free to race.\"<ref>{{cite news|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/motorsport/formula_one/8690323.stm|title=Mercedes rule out appeal against Schumacher penalty|work=BBC Sport |date=18 May 2010|accessdate=27 January 2011}}</ref> However, an FIA investigation found Schumacher guilty of breaching Safety Car regulations and awarded him a 20-seconds penalty, which cost him six places.<ref>[http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/motorsport/formula_one/8685542.stm Michael Schumacher penalised for late-race pass] [[BBC Sport]] \u2013 F1</ref>\n\n== Personal life ==\nSchumacher's younger brother [[Ralf Schumacher|Ralf]] is also a racing driver. He competed in Formula One for ten years, starting from 1997 until the end of 2007.<ref name=\"schumacher hof\" /> Their step-brother [[Sebastian Stahl]] has also been a racing driver.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://grandprix.com/ns/ns05169.html|title=Schumacher half-brother looking for racing action|publisher=Granprix.com|date=20 November 2001|accessdate=19 December 2008}}</ref>\n\nIn August 1995, Michael married [[Corinna Schumacher|Corinna Betsch]].<ref name=\"BBCSPORT\"></ref> They have two children, a daughter Gina-Marie, born 20 February 1997 and a son [[Mick Schumacher|Mick]], born 22 March 1999. He has always been very protective of his private life<ref name=\"BBCSPORT\">{{cite news | title = Who is the real Schumacher? |work=BBC Sport |first = Sarah |last = Holt |date=22 October 2006 | url = http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport2/hi/motorsport/formula_one/6047606.stm | accessdate =22 October 2006}}</ref> and is known to dislike the celebrity spotlight. The family moved to a newly-built mansion near [[Gland, Switzerland]] in 2007, covering an area of  {{convert|650|m2|adj=on}} with a private beach on [[Lake Geneva]] and featuring an underground garage and petrol station, with a vintage Shell fuel pump.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.topgear.com.ph/features/feature-articles/michael-schumacher-s-house-has-its-own-vintage-shell-fuel-pump|title=Michael Schumacher's house has its own vintage Shell fuel pump|website=www.topgear.com.ph|access-date=24 December 2019}}</ref> On 19 January 2019, Michael's son Mick Schumacher was announced as a driver for the [[Ferrari Driver Academy]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://fda.ferrari.com/en/mick-schumacher-joins-the-fda/|title=Mick Schumacher joins the FDA|date=19 January 2019 |accessdate=29 January 2019}}</ref>\n\nSchumacher and his wife own horse ranches in [[Texas]]<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.cs-ranch.com/home|title=home :: CS Ranch|work=cs-ranch.com|accessdate=7 April 2017}}</ref> and Switzerland.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.cs-ranch.eu/home|title=Home :: CS Ranch|work=cs-ranch.eu|accessdate=7 April 2017}}</ref>\n\nThe family has two dogs \u2013 one stray that Corinna fell in love with in Brazil, and an [[Australian Shepherd]] named \"Ed\" whose arrival in the family made headlines. In fact, in 2007, Schumacher personally drove a taxi through the Bavarian town of [[Coburg]] to collect the dog and enable the family to make their return flight to Switzerland.<ref>{{cite news| title = Taxi for Schumacher |work=BBC Sport | date = 12 December 2007 | url = http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport2/hi/motorsport/7139910.stm | accessdate =12 December 2007}}</ref> Both Schumacher and the taxi driver were reprimanded by local police.<ref>{{cite news | title = Police fuming over Schumacher's taxi race |agency=Agence France-Presse | date = 15 December 2007 | url = http://www.hindustantimes.com/motor-sports/topstories/police-fuming-over-schumacher-s-taxi-race/article1-263341.aspx | accessdate =30 March 2008 }}</ref>\n\nOne of his main hobbies was horse riding, and he played [[association football|football]] for his local team [[FC Echichens]]. He has appeared in several charity football games<ref name=\"fifa-charity football\">{{cite news|title=FIFA Fair Play: Playing for a better world |url=https://www.fifa.com/en/fairplay/index/0,1255,104749,00.html?articleid=104749 |publisher=FIFA |date=16 December 2004 |accessdate=25 October 2006 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20060918063721/http://www.fifa.com/en/fairplay/index/0%2C1255%2C104749%2C00.html?articleid=104749 |archivedate=18 September 2006 |url-status=dead |df= }}</ref> and organised games between Formula One drivers.<ref name=\"schumacher retirement response thoughts\">{{cite news |title = Thoughts on Schumacher |url =http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport2/hi/motorsport/formula_one/5330382.stm |work=BBC Sport |date=10 September 2006 |accessdate =25 October 2006}}</ref> He is a supporter of [[1. FC K\u00f6ln]], his local football club when he grew up.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.independent.ie/sport/michael-schumachers-family-deeply-touched-after-fc-koln-and-schalke-unveil-banner-of-support-29937780.html |title=Michael Schumacher's family 'deeply touched' after FC Koln and Schalke unveil banner of support |last=De Menezes |first=Jack |date=21 January 2014 |website=Irish Independent |access-date=4 April 2020}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |url=https://fc.de/fc-info/news/detailseite/details/gute-besserung-schumi/ |title=\u201eGute Besserung, Schumi!\u201c |date=15 January 2014 |website=1. FC K\u00f6ln |language=de |access-date=4 April 2020}}</ref>\n\nOn 23 June 2003, Schumacher was appointed as an [[Ambassador-at-Large]] for the [[Most Serene Republic of San Marino]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.esteri.sm/on-line/en/Home/DiplomaticandConsularCorps/DiplomaticandConsularRepresentationsofSanMarinoatlarge.html|title=Diplomatic and Consular Representations of San Marino at large|publisher=[[Secretary of State for Foreign and Political Affairs (San Marino)|Secretary of State for Foreign and Political Affairs]]|accessdate=17 March 2010}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.motorsport.com/news/article.asp?ID=135649&FS=F1|title=Schumacher appointed ambassador of San Marino|date=2 September 2003|publisher=Motorsport.com|accessdate=17 March 2010|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110606200052/http://www.motorsport.com/news/article.asp?ID=135649&FS=F1|archivedate=6 June 2011}}</ref>\n\nSchumacher is a special ambassador to [[UNESCO]] and has donated 1.5&nbsp;million euros to the organization.<ref name=\"unesco-champion for sport\">{{cite web| url = http://portal.unesco.org/en/ev.php-URL_ID=6691&URL_DO=DO_TOPIC&URL_SECTION=201.html| title = Michael Schumacher, a UNESCO champion| accessdate = 25 October 2006| year = 2002| publisher = UNESCO| url-status=dead| archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20070221113842/http://portal.unesco.org/en/ev.php-URL_ID%3D6691%26URL_DO%3DDO_TOPIC%26URL_SECTION%3D201.html| archivedate = 21 February 2007| df = dmy-all}}</ref> Additionally, he paid for the construction of a school for poor children and for area improvements in [[Dakar]], Senegal. He supports a hospital for child victims of war in [[Sarajevo]], which specialises in caring for amputees. In [[Lima]], Peru he funded the \"Palace for the Poor\", a centre for helping homeless street children obtain an education, clothing, food, medical attention, and shelter. He stated his interest in these various efforts was piqued both by his love for children and the fact that these causes had received little attention. While an exact figure for the amount of money he has donated throughout his life is unknown, it is known that in his last four years as a driver, he donated at least $50&nbsp;million.<ref name=\"donated50mil\" /> In 2008, it was revealed that he had donated between $5M and $10M to the [[Clinton Foundation]].<ref name=\"Clinton Foundation Donors\">{{cite news |title = Clinton Foundation Donors |url =https://online.wsj.com/public/resources/documents/st_clintondonor_20081218.html |work=The Wall Street Journal|date=18 December 2008 |accessdate =18 December 2008}}</ref>\n\nSince his participation in an FIA European road safety campaign, as part of his punishment after the collision at the [[1997 European Grand Prix]], Schumacher continued to support other campaigns, such as [[Make Roads Safe]], which is led by the FIA Foundation and calls on [[G8]] countries and the UN to recognise global road deaths as a major global health issue. In 2008, Schumacher was the figurehead of an advertising campaign by [[Bacardi]] to raise awareness about responsible drinking, with a focus on communicating an international message 'drinking and driving don't mix'. He featured in an advertising campaign for television, cinema and online media, supported by consumer engagements, public relations and digital media across the World.<ref name=\"drinkdrive\">{{cite news | title = Schumacher puts the brakes on drink-driving |work=The Guardian | date = 4 July 2008 | url = https://www.theguardian.com/media/2008/jul/04/advertising.formulaone | accessdate =30 January 2009| location=London| first=Mark| last=Sweney}}</ref>\n\nOn the eve of the [[2002 British Grand Prix]], on behalf of Fiat, Schumacher presented a [[Ferrari 360 Modena]] to the [[Cricket in India|Indian cricketer]] [[Sachin Tendulkar]] at [[Silverstone Circuit|Silverstone]].<ref>{{cite news|title = When Schumacher met Sachin! |url =http://www.rediff.com/cricket/2002/jul/23slide.htm |publisher=Rediff Cricket Online|date=23 July 2002|accessdate =24 July 2002}}</ref>\n\nOn 21 June 2009, Schumacher appeared on the [[BBC]]'s motoring programme ''[[Top Gear (2002 TV series)|Top Gear]]'' as [[the Stig]].<ref name=\"Stig\">{{cite news |title = Schumacher 'revealed' as the Stig |url =http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/entertainment/8111588.stm |work=BBC Online |date=21 June 2009 |accessdate =22 June 2009}}</ref> Presenter [[Jeremy Clarkson]] hinted later in the programme that Schumacher was not the regular Stig, which the BBC subsequently confirmed. Schumacher was there on that occasion because Ferrari would not allow anyone else to drive the unique black [[Ferrari FXX]] that was featured in the show.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://en.f1-live.com/f1/en/headlines/news/detail/090622092912.shtml |title=F1 : Schumacher completes a stint as Top Gear Stig \u2013 SCHUMACHER |publisher=En.F1-Live.com |accessdate=8 August 2009}}</ref>\n\nDuring his interview with Clarkson, Schumacher stated that his road cars are a [[Fiat 500 (2007)#Abarth 500 (2008-)|Fiat 500 Abarth]], and a [[Fiat Croma]], which is his family car.<ref>{{Cite episode|title=Series 13, Episode 1|series=Top Gear|serieslink=Top Gear (series 13)|network=[[BBC Two]]|airdate=12 June 2009}}</ref>\n\n=== Finance and sponsorship ===\nIn 2004 ''Forbes'' magazine listed him as the second highest paid athlete in the world.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.forbes.com/2004/06/23/04athletesland.html |title=The Best-Paid Athletes |work=Forbes |accessdate=8 August 2009 |date=24 June 2004}}</ref> In 2005, ''Eurobusiness'' magazine identified Schumacher as the world's first billionaire athlete. His 2004 salary was reported to be around US$80&nbsp;million.<ref name=\"schumacher pay\">{{cite news |first = Angus |last = Reid |title = Sports: How Big Is Too Big? |url=https://thetyee.ca/Mediacheck/2006/07/11/TrendWatch/ |work=Mediacheck |publisher=thetyee.ca |date=11 July 2006 |accessdate =24 October 2006}} Forbes magazine has not yet included him on its [https://www.forbes.com/lists/2006/10/Rank_1.html billionaires list]. More recently, other sources have estimated his net worth in 2006 somewhat lower, www.f1i.com reported that it 'surpassed $800M'.{{cite news |title = Retired Schu to earn $26&nbsp;m in 2007 \u2013 report |url = http://www.f1i.com/content/view/5215/32/ |publisher=f1i.com |date=18 September 2006 |accessdate=23 January 2007 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20070506145347/http://www.f1i.com/content/view/5215/32/ |archivedate=6 May 2007}}</ref> [[Forbes|''Forbes'' magazine]] ranked him 17th in its \"The World's Most Powerful Celebrities\" list.<ref name=\"forbes celeb 100 2005\">{{cite news| url = http://forbes.com/lists/2005/53/Rank_1.html | title = The Celebrity 100| accessdate =25 October 2006|year=2005|work=Forbes}}</ref> A significant share of his income came from advertising. For example, [[Deutsche Verm\u00f6gensberatung]] paid him $8&nbsp;million over three years from 1999 for wearing a 10 by 8 centimetre advertisement on his post-race cap.<ref>{{cite news | title = MOT: Schumacher slaps $11.9&nbsp;m price on his head | publisher=AAP Sports News |date=11 November 1999 | url = http://www.highbeam.com/doc/1P1-24009938.html | archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20110516202251/http://www.highbeam.com/doc/1P1-24009938.html | url-status=dead | archive-date = 16 May 2011 | accessdate =24 October 2006}}</ref> The deal was extended until 2010.<ref>{{cite news | title = Schumacher's sponsor extends contract | publisher=GPUpdate.net |date=31 August 2005 | url = http://www.gpupdate.net/en/f1-news/96638/schumacher-s-sponsor-extends-contract/ | accessdate =1 February 2011}}</ref> He donated $10&nbsp;million for aid after the [[2004 Indian Ocean earthquake]].<ref name=\"cnn-tsunami relief\">{{cite news |title = Schumacher donates $10&nbsp;m relief aid |url = http://edition.cnn.com/2005/SPORT/01/04/tsunami.relief/index.html |publisher=CNN |date=4 January 2005 |accessdate =24 October 2006}}</ref> His donation surpassed that of any other sports person, most sports leagues, many worldwide corporations and even some countries.<ref name=\"si-sportsman of the year\">{{cite news| url = http://sportsillustrated.cnn.com/2005/magazine/specials/sportsman/2005/11/11/michael.schumacher/index.html | title = My Sportsman: Michael Schumacher| accessdate =25 October 2006| last = McAllister| first = Mike|date=11 November 2005| work=2005 Sportsman of the Year}}</ref> \n\nIn 2010 his personal fortune was estimated at \u00a3515 million.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://en.espnf1.com/f1/motorsport/story/15812.html|title=Drivers top the rich list|work=ESPN F1|accessdate=9 September 2014}}</ref>\n\n==2013 skiing accident==\nOn 29 December 2013, Schumacher was skiing with his then 14-year-old son [[Mick Schumacher|Mick]], descending the Combe de Saulire below the [[Dent de Burgin]] above [[M\u00e9ribel]] in the [[French Alps]]. While crossing an unsecured [[off-piste]] area between Piste Chamois and Piste Mauduit,<ref>{{cite web\n |url        = http://mitteleuropa.x10.mx/misc_newmaterial.html#schumacher\n |archive-date = 24 February 2014\n |archive-url = https://archive.today/20140224185128/http://mitteleuropa.x10.mx/misc_newmaterial.html%23schumacher\n |url-status   = dead\n |title      = Michael Schumacher's Skiing Accident in M\u00e9ribel \u2013 Locations\n |publisher  = X10\n |accessdate = 24 February 2014\n}}</ref><ref>{{cite web\n |url=http://www.snowindustrynews.com/articles/schumacher-head-injury-skiing/\n |title=Schumacher Head Injury Skiing\n |publisher=Snow Industry News\n |accessdate=20 April 2015\n |url-status=dead\n |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150427142904/http://www.snowindustrynews.com/articles/schumacher-head-injury-skiing/\n |archivedate=27 April 2015\n |df=\n}}</ref> he fell and hit his head on a rock, sustaining a serious head injury despite wearing a [[ski helmet]]. According to his physicians, he would most likely have died if he had not been wearing a helmet.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.autosport.com/news/report.php/id/111982|title=Helmet helped protect Michael Schumacher in skiing accident|last=Noble|first=Jonathan|date=30 December 2013|work=Autosport|publisher=Haymarket Publishing|accessdate=30 December 2013}}</ref> He was airlifted to [[Centre Hospitalier Universitaire de Grenoble|Grenoble Hospital]] where he underwent two surgical interventions.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.mirror.co.uk/sport/formula-1/michael-schumacher-ski-accident-10360005|title=What we know about Michael Schumacher after horror ski accident|last=Whaling|first=James|date=26 November 2017|work=mirror|access-date=18 December 2017}}</ref>\nSchumacher was put into a medically [[induced coma]] because of [[traumatic brain injury]]; his doctors reported on 7 March 2014 that his condition was stable.<ref name=CNN2014-03-07>{{cite news |url=http://edition.cnn.com/2014/03/07/sport/michael-schumacher-massa-f1-motorsport/ |title=Michael Schumacher 'still in wake-up phase' |publisher=CNN |date=7 March 2014 |accessdate=16 March 2014}}</ref><ref name=Autosport-postop>{{cite news|url=http://www.autosport.com/news/report.php/id/111981|title=Doctors say Michael Schumacher's condition 'extremely serious'|last=Noble|first=Jonathan|date=30 December 2013|work=Autosport|publisher=Haymarket Publishing|accessdate=30 December 2013}}</ref> On 4 April 2014, Schumacher's agent reported that he was showing \"moments of consciousness\" as he was gradually withdrawn from the medically induced coma, adding to reports by relatives of \"small encouraging signs\" over the preceding month.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/world-europe-26885624|title=Schumacher has 'conscious moments' \u2013 agent|date=4 April 2014|work=BBC News|accessdate=4 April 2014}}</ref>\n\nIn mid-June 2014, he was moved from intensive care into a rehabilitation ward.{{citation needed|date=November 2018}} By 16 June 2014, Schumacher had regained consciousness and left Grenoble Hospital for further rehabilitation at the [[University Hospital of Lausanne|University Hospital (CHUV)]] in [[Lausanne]], Switzerland.<ref>{{cite news|last1= Schmuck |first1= Pascal |last2= Nicollier |first2= Marie |url= http://www.24heures.ch/vaud-regions/lausanne-region/Schumacher-entre-les-mains-des-neurologues-du-CHUV/story/16481300 |title= Schumacher entre les mains des neurologues du CHUV |work= 24 Heures |language= French |date= 16 June 2014 |accessdate= 21 August 2014 }}</ref> On 9 September 2014, Schumacher left CHUV and was brought back to his home for further rehabilitation.<ref name=\"goinghome\" /> <!-- In October 2014, Michael's son Mick reported to an F1 commentator that Michael's road to recovery will be long and difficult, that he is waking up \"very slowly\", and that substantial blame for the injury was due to a [[GoPro]] camera attached to Michael's helmet.<ref>[http://au.ibtimes.com/articles/569422/20141014/michael-schumacher-coma-update-teenage-son.htm Michael Schumacher Coma Update From Teenage Son], 14 October 2014.</ref> need better ref: not reflected in source--> In November 2014, it was reported that Schumacher was \"paralysed and in a wheelchair\"; he \"cannot speak and has memory problems\".<ref name=\"Schumacher in Nov 2014\">{{cite news|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/sport/motorsport/formulaone/michael-schumacher/11241129/Michael-Schumacher-paralysed-and-in-a-wheelchair.html|title= Michael Schumacher: 'paralysed and in a wheelchair'|work=The Telegraph|accessdate=19 November 2014|date= 19 November 2014|last1= Williams|first1= Alexandra}}</ref> In a video interview released in May 2015, Schumacher's manager Sabine Kehm said that his condition is slowly improving \"considering the severeness of the injury he had\".<ref>{{cite web|title=Michael Schumacher Latest Health Update: F1 Racing Superstar Improving 17 Months After Ski Accident |url=http://www.gospelherald.com/articles/55707/20150526/michael-schumacher-health-update-f1-racing-superstar-improving-17-months-ski-crash.htm|first=Komfie|last=Manalo|date=26 May 2015|accessdate=27 May 2015}}</ref>\n\nIn September 2016, Felix Damm, lawyer for Schumacher, told a German court that his client \"cannot walk\", in response to false reports from December 2015 in German publication ''Die Bunte'' that he could \"walk a couple of steps\".<ref name=walk1>{{cite web|last1=Coppinger|first1=Mike|title=Lawyer refutes report, says Michael Schumacher 'cannot walk' or stand|url=https://www.usatoday.com/story/sports/motor/formula1/2016/09/19/michael-schumacher-lawsuit-die-bunte/90711600/|website=USA Today|accessdate=21 September 2016}}</ref><ref name=walk2>{{cite news|title=Michael Schumacher 'cannot walk', German court hears|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/world-europe-37406977|website=BBC News|accessdate=21 September 2016|date=19 September 2016}}</ref> In December 2016 Schumacher's manager stated that \"Michael's health is not a public issue, and so we will continue to make no comment in that regard\".<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/formula-1/2016/12/17/michael-schumacher-latest-news-f1-greats-health-will-remain/ |date=17 December 2016 |title=Michael Schumacher's health to remain a private matter, says manager Sabine Kehm |accessdate=24 December 2018 |newspaper=The Telegraph |publisher=Telegraph Media Group Limited}}</ref>\n\nIn July 2019, former [[Ferrari]] manager [[Jean Todt]] gave an interview to [[Radio Monte Carlo]] giving a brief update on Schumacher's health, saying that Schumacher was making \"good progress\" but also \"struggles to communicate\". Todt also said that Schumacher is able to watch Formula One races on television at his home in Switzerland.<ref name=\"telegraph-2019-07\">{{cite news |last1=Chazan |first1=David |title=Michael Schumacher 'making progress' in recovery from severe head injuries |url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/2019/07/30/michael-schumacher-making-progress-recovery-severe-head-injuries |newspaper=[[The Daily Telegraph|The Telegraph]] |accessdate=30 July 2019 |date=30 July 2019}}</ref>\n\nIn September 2019, ''[[Le Parisien]]'' reported that Schumacher had been admitted to the [[H\u00f4pital Europ\u00e9en Georges-Pompidou]] in Paris for treatment by cardiovascular surgeon Philippe Menasch\u00e9, described as a \"pioneer in cell surgery\". Following the treatment, which involved his receiving an anti-inflammatory stem cell perfusion, medical staff stated that Michael Schumacher was \"conscious\".<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/2019/09/11/michael-schumacher-conscious-pioneering-treatment-paris-says/|title=Michael Schumacher 'conscious' after pioneering treatment in Paris|last=Samuel|first=Henry|date=11 September 2019|work=The Telegraph|access-date=2019-09-12|language=en-GB|issn=0307-1235}}</ref>\n\n== Racing record ==\n\n=== Career summary ===\n{|class=\"wikitable\" style=\"text-align:center; font-size:90%;\"\n|-\n!Season\n!Series\n!Team\n!Races\n!Wins\n!Poles\n!F/Laps\n!Podiums\n!Points\n!Position\n|-\n!rowspan=\"3\"|1988\n|style=\"text-align:left;\"|European [[Formula Ford]] 1600\n|rowspan=\"2\" style=\"text-align:left;\"|Eufra Racing\n|4\n|1\n|1\n|0\n|3\n|50\n|style=\"background:#DFDFDF;\"|'''2nd'''\n|-\n|style=\"text-align:left;\"|German Formula Ford 1600\n|7\n|3\n|0\n|0\n|5\n|124\n|6th\n|-\n|style=\"text-align:left;\"|[[Formula K\u00f6nig]]\n|style=\"text-align:left;\"|Hoecker Sportwagenservice\n|10\n|9\n|1\n|1\n|10\n|192\n|style=\"background:#FBFFBF;\"|'''1st'''\n|-\n!rowspan=\"3\"|1989\n|style=\"text-align:left;\"|[[1989 German Formula Three Championship|German Formula Three]]\n|rowspan=\"3\" style=\"text-align:left;\"|WTS Racing\n|12\n|2\n|2\n|0\n|7\n|163\n|style=\"background:#FFDF9F;\"|'''3rd'''\n|-\n|style=\"text-align:left;\"|[[FIA European Formula Three Cup|European Formula Three Cup]]\n|1\n|0\n|0\n|0\n|0\n|N/A\n|NC\n|-\n|style=\"text-align:left;\